name: Abacus
description:
An abacus, an ancient tool used to count and calculate by moving beads. Depicted as a wooden frame with four or more rows or columns of variously positioned and colored beads.

Used for various content concerning mathematics and science (education) as well as calculations, counting, and numbers more generally.

Designs from Apple and Facebook resemble a Chinese abacus (suanpan), as did a previous Microsoft design. By one reckoning, Apple’s red-beaded design displays the number 108 and Emojipedia's, 12,031,981.

name: Accordion
description: A red accordion with a keyboard on one side, buttons on the other side, and bellows in the middle. Used to talk about accordion music or music in general. Also may be used in reference to things that expand and contract, or are folded like the bellows of an accordion.

name: Adhesive Bandage
description: An adhesive bandage used for first aid. Sometimes called a Band-Aid or band aid after the trademarked product. Sometimes called a plaster.

name: Admission Tickets
description: A ticket or tickets to an event that may say "Admit One" on the front. Shown in pink or yellow on most platforms.

name: Aerial Tramway
description:
An Aerial Tramway, most commonly seen at ski resorts, for transport between locations on a mountain. Can also be used as a tourist attraction, or as a form of public transport.

In 2018 this emoji was the focus of a grassroots campaign on Twitter where users of the platform began using this emoji more frequently. This was to update the least-used emoji on emojitracker.com (as tracked by the @leastUsedEmoji Twitter bot) from the Aerial Tramway to another emoji.

name: Airplane
description:
Used either as a literal airplane, to represent an overseas vacation, or sometimes as a proxy for airplane mode on a phone or tablet.

Use of this emoji declined in April 2020, potentially as a result of global air travel limitations.

name: Airplane Arriving
description: A plane approaching a runway for landing. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane facing toward the ground in a position that may result in a crash if attempted in the real world.

name: Airplane Departure
description: A plane taking off from a runway. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane elevated.

name: Alarm Clock
description:
A timepiece set in advance to startle a person awake at the designated time with its two bells. That is, before hitting snooze. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted as a classic, wind-up, bedside alarm clock, often red in color.

May be used for various content concerning alarms, alerts, sleeping, waking, and time more generally.

name: Alembic
description:
An apparatus for distilling, as used in medieval alchemy. Generally depicted as a round flask with a neck angled down to the right. Positioned on a short stand and containing a mysterious green, purple, or blue liquid.

Commonly used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May represent various liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well as metaphorical laboratories and experiments.

Thanks to the alembic’s association with alchemy, this emoji may also convey a sense of magic. And, thanks to its resemblance to a glass pipe, some use the emoji to represent a bong or other drug paraphernalia.

Samsung’s design previously featured a copper still, as used for making whiskey.

name: Alien Monster
description:
A friendly-looking, tentacled space creature with two eyes. Most major platforms style their design after aliens in classic arcade games like Space Invaders, rendering it purple and pixellated, as if in 8-bit graphics.

Samsung’s design resembles an octopus and previously featured a big-brained alien, à la Star Trek. Earlier designs from Google and Microsoft depicted more cartoon-like alien monsters.

May be used of topics concerning extraterrestrial life, outer space, gaming, and computing, but also enjoys a range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of weirdness, wackiness, or excitement, given that the emoji looks like it is raising its arms shouting Yay! on many platforms.

name: Ambulance
description: An ambulance, used to transport patients between their home and the hospital.

name: American Football
description: The oval ball used in the game of American football, known as gridiron in some countries.

name: Amphora
description:
A tall, ceramic jar with two handles and a narrow neck and foot. Represents an amphora, as used by ancient Greeks and Romans to hold water and wine.

Generally depicted as brownish-red earthenware ornamented with black and a Greek meander pattern.

May represent containers like vases, pottery, museums, history, and antiquity. May also be used in relation to the zodiac sign of Aquarius, the Water-Bearer.

Not to be confused with ‚ö±Ô∏è Funeral Urn.

name: Anatomical Heart
description:
A red anatomical heart, shown with blue or purple veins on some platforms.

Sometimes used interchangeably with ‚ù§Ô∏è Red Heart.

name: Anchor
description:
A metal device, dropped out of a boat to prevent it drifting away from the current location.
An anchor also refers to a place on a webpage that may be directly¬†linked to, rather than simply loading a page and requiring a user to scroll to the correct location.

name: Anger Symbol
description:
A red symbol found in Anime/Manga and used to represent the veins popping on a very angry person.

Also used in other comic books to indicate a punch landed, perhaps next to the words “Bam” or “Pow”.

name: Angry Face
description:
A yellow face with a frowning mouth and eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward in anger.

Conveys varying degrees of anger, from grumpiness and irritation to disgust and outrage. May also represent someone acting tough or being mean.

Samsung’s design previously featured a reddish face with clenched teeth and wrinkled chin. Google’s design also previously featured a reddish face, while Facebook’s and Microsoft's earlier designs had clenched teeth.

name: Anguished Face
description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes, open frown, and raised eyebrows. Samsung’s design shows upper teeth and tongue. Meaning widely varies, but may convey alarm, confusion, or sadness, as if gasping in shock or concern.

Bears the same eyes and mouth as üò¶ Frowning Face With Open Mouth on most platforms, but its eyebrows give it a more surprised expression.

name: Ant
description:
An ant, a small, industrious insect that lives in a colony. Depicted as a black or red ant in full profile on its six legs facing left, with a prominent abdomen and antennae.

May be used to represent various insects or other bugs.

Facebook’s ant is red, as was a previous Microsoft design. Google’s ant was previously blue, Facebook’s black.

name: Antenna with Bars
description: Bars increasing in height, showing the strength of the mobile (cellular) phone¬†signal. More bars signifies better reception.

name: Anticlockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows
description:
Two arrows forming a circle, pointing in an anticlockwise direction. Similar to symbols sometimes used for refresh or rotate. May also be used to indicate a task is in progress.

Previously showed in a clockwise direction on Windows.

name: Aquarius
description: The Aquarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Water-bearer.

name: Aries
description: The Aries astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Ram.

name: Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Downwards
description:
A curved arrow pointing down.

Generally used to highlight a piece of content placed below where this emoji can be used. This content could be a picture, a website link, or a different piece of text,

name: Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Upwards
description: A curved arrow pointing up.

name: Articulated Lorry
description: A large articulated lorry consisting of a tractor and a trailer connected by a pivoted bar. Most likely hauling stock for different companies and services, such as the items on sale within department stores.

name: Artist
description: A person engaged in the visual art of painting, shown holding a palette and paintbrush.

name: Artist Palette
description: A palette used by an artist when painting, to store and mix paint colors.

name: Astonished Face
description:
A yellow face with open eyes, raised eyebrows, and an open mouth, as if gasping in shock or surprise. Often depicted showing its upper teeth. May convey a wide range of emotions, including awe, amazement, admiration, disbelief, excitement, or concern.

Similar to üòØ Hushed Face, which features smaller eyes and mouth. Several earlier designs, including Apple’s, displayed X-shaped eyes, making the emoji resemble üòµ Dizzy Face. Google’s design previously depicted a wobbly expression, as if inebriated.

Huawei's design for this emoji includes a üí• Collision-like symbol behind its head, emphasising its astonishment.

name: Astronaut
description: An astronaut or cosmonaut shown wearing a space suit and helmet.

name: Athletic Shoe
description:
A sneaker – a comfortable shoe used in sports such as tennis or golf, or for fashion purposes.

An early Apple design was brown.

name: Atom Symbol
description: A symbol used to represent the atom and its associated sciences, showing lines representing electrons orbiting around a circular nucleus where protons are located.

name: Aubergine
description:
A long, bulbous, bright purple eggplant, or aubergine in British English, shown with a leafy stem. Considered lucky in Japan to dream of an eggplant the first night of the New Year. 

Widely used to represent a penis. Due to its phallic use, the hashtag #üçÜ was once banned (2015) on Instagram's search function.

name: Auto Rickshaw
description: An auto rickshaw, often referred to as a tuk tuk. This motorized version of a cycle rickshaw is used for transport in many regions of the world. Generally this emoji has three wheels and open sides without doors.

name: Automated Teller Machine
description: A square symbol showing the letter "ATM", standing for "Automated Teller Machine".

name: Automobile
description:
A car shown from the side, facing right-to-left. Appears as a red car on almost all platforms (which goes faster), though earlier Google designs displayed the vehicle as either silver or blue.

Facebook's first design for this emoji was also blue.

name: Avocado
description: A pear-shaped avocado, sliced in half to show its yellow-green flesh and large brown pit. Ready for toast, guacamole, or millennial jokes.

name: Axe
description: An axe with a wooden handle and a metal blade. On many platforms the blade is red, like a fire axe.

name: Baby
Baby Angel
description:
A baby with a halo and wings. Can represent a sweet baby, a biblical cherub, a mythological cupid, a decorative putto, or an angel as a supernatural being in general. This emoji can be used earnestly or in a tongue-in-cheek way to talk about goodness or innocence.

It is often used to express affection for people, especially children at birth or, more sadly, after death. This emoji pops up in a large variety of contexts ranging from innocence, love, Valentine's Day, positive feelings like gratitude, and the Christian faith, especially during Christmas.

See also üë∂ Baby.

name: Baby Bottle
description: A bottle of milk or formula, as or fed to a baby, with a bluish cap and rubber nipple or teat. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle, and filled to various levels, sometimes showing fill lines. Often used for newborns and childrearing. See also Breast-Feeding.

name: Baby Chick
description:
A yellow baby chicken (chick). Variously depicted as a chick in full profile, standing on its legs, or as a chick head. Both designs show the bird facing left, with an orange beak and feet.

Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry, eggs), spring, Easter, or slang senses of chick.

Not to be confused with üê£ Hatching Chick or üê•Front-Facing Baby Chick, though their applications overlap. See also üêî Chicken and üêì Rooster.

Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs feature a chick head; other major platforms display a full-bodied chick.

name: Baby Symbol
description: The symbol for a baby, usually used to indicate a room that is suitable to change a baby in. Often located in or near public restrooms.

name: Back with Leftwards Arrow Above
description: The word "back" with an arrow above it, pointing to the left.

name: Bacon
description: Strips of crispy, fatty, reddish-brown bacon, as fried for breakfast. Depicted as a pair on most platforms.

name: Bactrian Camel
description:
A Bactrian camel, a long-necked mammal with two large humps on its back. Depicted in light or yellowish brown, sometimes with a shaggy mane and humps, in full profile on all fours facing left.

Not to be confused with üê™ Camel (dromedary), though their applications generally overlap.

May be used in association with deserts, the Middle East and Central Asia, and Wednesday (Hump Day).

Samsung’s design features a camel with a shaggy head of hair and slight smile. Google’s design previously featured a blanket on its back, as for transport.

name: Badger
description:
A badger, a stocky mammal in the weasel family with a long, pointed head. Generally depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a gray coat, black-and-white-striped face, and short tail.

Google’s design used to feature a friendly, cartoon-styled black-and-white badger face. Facebook’s badger is sitting on its hind legs.

name: Badminton Racquet and Shuttlecock
description: A racquet and shuttlecock used in the sport of badminton. The racquet is generally depicted as blue, though Apple's racquet is yellow.

name: Bagel
description:
The brown bread of a bagel, shown sliced in two halves. Some platforms depict seeds, as sesame or poppy, and a schmear of cream cheese, with the bagel assembled as a sandwich. May resemble the Doughnut at small sizes.

After complaints, Apple updated the bagel emoji design during the iOS 12.1 beta cycle.

name: Baggage Claim
description: An icon representing the place where luggage can be collected from after the completion of a journey on the likes of an airplane or ferry.

name: Baguette Bread
description: The long, thin loaf of a baguette, with scoring on its golden-brown crust. A bread commonly associated with France. May also be used to denote financial success, as per the slang term "let's get this bread".

name: Ball of Yarn
description:
A ball of yarn, as used to knit a scarf. Color varies across platforms, but often depicted in green, blue, or magenta and shown with an end unraveling. Sometimes depicted with a pair of knitting needles stuck in the ball.

Commonly used for various content concerning knitting and needlework (e.g., sewing, crocheting), clothing and fashion, arts and crafts, cold weather, and cats.

name: Ballet Shoes
description: Shoes worn by ballet dancers for pointe work. Most platforms show a pair of pink shoes resting on their pointes. Sometimes used to represent dancing in general, rather than ballet specifically. Sometimes also used to represent the color pink.

name: Balloon
description:
A balloon on a string, as decorates a birthday party. Generally depicted in red, though WhatsApp’s is pink and Google’s orangish-red.

Commonly used to convey congratulations and celebration, especially when wishing someone a happy birthday.

Microsoft and Samsung's balloons were previously blue; SoftBank's was shown floating in the sky.

name: Ballot Box with Ballot
description:
A ballot box, as used to cast votes in an election. Depicted as a box, generally blue or gray, with a slot on top through which a paper ballot is being inserted. Many platforms display a cross mark or check mark on the ballot to indicate a vote, though Apple and Facebook leave theirs blank.

Commonly used for various content concerning voting and elections, especially in politics and government.

name: Banana
description: A ripe banana, peeled and ready to eat on major platforms. Great snack for a child or monkey.

name: Banjo
description: A banjo with a round body and a long neck. Used to talk about banjos or music in general.

name: Bank
description:
A retail bank branch, where people can perform money-related tasks. Also a common location to find an ATM.

This emoji came to also mean "slacking off" or evading responsibility in Japan, due to the BK letters being associated with the slang term bakkureru.

name: Banknote with Dollar Sign
description:
Cash money! A banded stack of U.S. dollar banknotes, the paper currency of the United States of America. Green hue and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the dollar sign, $. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.S.

Apple’s design depicts $1 bills with Cupertino and John Appleseed in the treasury signature sections. WhatsApp’s design depicts $10 bills, Facebook’s displays a Statue of Liberty torch.

name: Banknote with Euro Sign
description:
A banded stack of euro banknotes, the paper currency of the European Union (EU). Color and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the euro sign, €. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the EU.

Some vendors, including Apple and Samsung, depict green €100 bills; others, including Google, WhatsApp, and Facebook, depict blue €20 bills. Facebook additionally features the EU flag.

name: Banknote with Pound Sign
description:
Quids in! A banded stack of pound banknotes, the paper currency of the United Kingdom (England, Wales, Northern Ireland, and Scotland). Color and detail vary across platforms, but widely depicted as purple £20 notes with the pound sign, £.

Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.K. 

Samsung's design displays £10 notes.

name: Banknote with Yen Sign
description:
A banded stack of yen banknotes, the paper currency of Japan. Color and detail vary across platforms, but usually shown in green, yellow, or pink with the yen symbol, ¥. Commonly used for various content concerning money and wealth, not restricted to Japan.

Apple and WhatsApp’s designs depict the ¥1,000 banknote, Facebook’s features a Japanese character for yen (ÂÜÜ) and a cherry blossom.

name: Bar Chart
description:
A bar graph generally showing three different-colored, vertical rectangles at various heights, as compares values across a category. Commonly used to represent various types of data, information, facts, figures, and charts more generally.

Several platforms, including Apple, depict (left to right) a green, red (lowest), and blue bar (highest). Google’s design previously included four bars, with yellow being the highest.

name: Bar of Soap
description:
A bar of soap, as used in the shower, bath or for hand washing. Generally shown with lathered bubbles. Depicted in various colors, often pink, and at different angles.

Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning. May be used to represent the opposite of dirt or being dirty. Recommended for use to prevent the spread of COVID-19.

name: Barber Pole
description:
A pole spiraled with red, white, and blue stripes, as spins out front of a barbershop. Commonly used for various content concerning haircutting and hairstyling.

May also be associated with brothels in parts of Asia.

name: Baseball
description: A white baseball, with regulation red stitching. Used in the game of the same name, baseball.

name: Basket
description:
A basket, as used for storing or carrying such things as food or clothes. Appearance widely varies across platforms but generally depicted as woven from wicker with one or more handles. Commonly used to represent doing laundry or having a picnic.

Apple and WhatsApp’s designs, featuring a white cloth, suggest a bread or picnic basket. Samsung’s design displays green fabric, as knitted from yarn.

Microsoft’s design previously suggested a laundry basket by holding a blue garment or cloth.

Not to be confused with üóëÔ∏è Wastebasket.

name: Basketball and Hoop
description:
An orange-colored basketball. Originally intended to display as a basketball and a hoop, as per previous designs by Google, Samsung, and Microsoft.

This emoji can be sent on Facebook Messenger to unlock a hidden basketball game.

name: Bat
description:
A bat, the flying mammal of the night. Variously depicted as a brown, black, or gray bat, with wings outspread and pointy ears, facing forward or left.

Often used in association with Halloween, vampires, and Batman.

Google’s bat was previously purplish in color, bearing two fangs. Samsung’s bat was previously brown, and Facebook’s gray.

name: Bath
description:
A gender-unspecified person taking a soothing bath in a white tub with a shower head. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally. May also represent relaxation and self-care.

The appearance of the person, depicted in default yellow, varies. Apple's person is wearing a green shower cap, WhatsApp's a green washcloth. Google’s person appears to be playing in a bubble bath, with soapsuds atop their ahead. Other major vendors show the head of the bather with short, brown or blonde hair. Skin tone modifiers are available on supported platforms.

Vendors implement the same or a similar tub and shower head as for their üõÅ Bathtub, but with a person taking/having a bath.

name: Bathtub
description:
A white bathtub with a silver shower head. Often depicted as a cast-iron tub with claw-foot legs. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally.

Several platforms, including Apple and Facebook, feature soap bubbles or suds. Samsung’s design displays streaming water from the shower head.

Vendors implement üõÄ Person Taking a Bath with the same or a similar emoji, but with a person soaking in the tub.

name: Battery
description:
An electric battery, as used to power such devices as a flashlight. Generally depicted as an upright, green cylinder, as a AA or D cell, with white indicators for its positive (facing up) and negative terminals.

Commonly used for various content concerning electricity, charging, energy, and power, especially in figurative senses. Its green color also suggests the icon for battery power on a cell/mobile phone.

Apple’s design includes a voltage symbol; WhatsApp’s battery is blue.

name: Beach with Umbrella
description:
A beach showing sand, and an umbrella for protection from the sun.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity during the summer months.

name: Beans
description:
Beans, as used in cuisines around the world.  

May be used to talk about food, flatulence (caused by eating beans), or coffee beans.

Also used to discuss money, counting, or a small amount of something. 

May be used to refer to the head. Additionally may be used with phrases such as spill the beans, full of beans, or cool beans.

name: Bear Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of bear, looking straight ahead. Depicted as a brown bear with round ears and a tan muzzle. Resembles a teddy bear.

Often used with an affectionate tone. Does not have a full-bodied bear emoji counterpart.

May be used to refer to certain members of the LGBTQ community, a la the slang term "bear".

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Samsung’s bear was previously golden brown.

name: Bearded Person
description:
A person with a beard.

This emoji may be used to talk about bearded people in a gender-inclusive way. It was approved in 2017. Gendered variants of this emoji were approved three years later.

Variants include üßî‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man with a Beard and üßî‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman with a Beard, both approved in 2020.

name: Beating Heart
description:
A heart with vibration/movement lines above it or around it, indicating it is beating. Displayed in pink or red on most platforms.

An early version of this emoji on iOS had the same design as üíñ Sparkling Heart.

name: Beaver
description:
A brown beaver with buckteeth and a wide paddle-like tail. Can be used in the context of actual beavers, or metaphorically to evoke qualities of beavers like working hard, as in the expression beavering away. 

Commonly associated with Canada, as beavers are a national emblem of the country. May also be used in reference to the vagina, which is an informal sense of the word beaver.

name: Bed
description:
A bed, made up for sleeping in a house, hotel, or other sleeping accommodation. Shown with a headboard at the left, footboard, mattress, pillow, and sheet. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets.

Commonly used for various content concerning beds, furniture, and housing as well as sleeping, relaxing, and other bedroom activities.

Vendors implement the same style of bed for üõå Person in Bed, but without a sleeper under the covers.

name: Beer Mug
description: A beer, as a golden-colored lager, in a frosty mug. Depicted with a frothy head spilling over the brim. üçª Clinking Beer Mugs is a variation that displays two such beer mugs.

name: Beetle
description:
A green or brown beetle shown with antennae and six legs. Can be used to talk about beetles, bugs, or insects in general.

Not to be confused with üêû Lady Beetle, ü™≥ Cockroach, üêõ Bug, üêú Ant or other emoji representations of insects.

name: Bell
description: A gold or yellow bell, which is commonly used on mobile phones as an icon for notifications or ringing sounds.

name: Bell Pepper
description: A perfectly ripe red or green bell pepper. Can be used to talk about bell peppers or food in general.

name: Bell with Cancellation Stroke
description: A gold or yellow bell with a red line through it, which is¬†commonly used on mobile phones as an icon for the silencing of notifications or ringing sounds. A mute, or silent mode.

name: Bellhop Bell
description:
Ding! A call bell, as pressed at a front desk or reception to alert staff for service, such as from a concierge or bellhop (porter) to carry luggage at a hotel. Generally depicted as a golden bell on a wooden stand.

Commonly represents alerts or notifications to bring attention to important content. May also be used of various content concerning the hospitality and service industries.

Microsoft’s design previously featured a silver bell radiating yellow rays, as if ringing.

name: Bento Box
description: A Japanese bento, a lunch box divided into portions of rice, vegetables, and meat or seafood, such as sushi or fried shrimp.

name: Beverage Box
description:
Originally proposed as Juice, this emoji can be used to talk about juice or other liquids that come in boxes with straws. It can also be used metaphorically to talk about power, energy, respect, or an elusive quality that makes someone special.

While intended to be used to represent a broad selection of juices and other liquids, most vendors' designs feature a üçé Red Apple symbol. üçá Grapes, üçäTangerine, üçë Peach, üçí Cherries, üçê Pear, and a üåû Sun with Face across other more distinct designs.

name: Bicycle
description: A bicycle, sometimes called a push bike, used for transport or sport.

name: Bicyclist
description: A person riding a bicycle for leisure, sport or transport. Intended to be gender-neutral.

name: Bikini
description:
A two-piece bikini, worn at the beach, pool, or on vacation at a tropical destination.

Shown in a variety of colors and patterns across different platforms.

Related emojis include ü©≤ Briefs, ü©≥ Shorts, and ü©± One-Piece Swimsuit.

name: Billed Cap
description:
A plain soft hat with a rounded crown and a stiff bill. Most often shown in a shade of blue and displayed at an angle to clearly display its outwards- protruding bill.

Regularly associated with the slang term "capping", meaning "lying". Responding to a message with a single üß¢ emoji is viewable as an accusation of lying (“cap”) while stating "no üß¢" ("no cap") is intended to emphasize the truthfulness of a statement.

name: Billiards
description:
This emoji displays the black 8 ball on most platforms, which looks similar to the Magic 8-Ball toy. This is despite the fact that emoji was originally created intending to represent game of billiards, of which pool is a common version.

Samsung previously displayed this emoji with a cue and triangular arrangement of colored balls, as did Google and Microsoft (sans cue).

name: Biohazard Sign
description:
A hazard symbol used in the labeling of biological materials that carry a significant health risk, including viral and bacteriological samples.

Generally displayed on an orange or yellow background.

name: Bird
description:
A generic bird. Variously depicted as a blue or red bird, as a bluebird or cardinal, shown standing in full profile, or as a bird head. Both designs show the bird facing left.

May be used for a variety of wild and pet birds as well as for metaphorical senses of bird (e.g., birdie in golf).

Apple and WhatsApp’s designs feature a grayish bird head. Google, Samsung, and Facebook’s designs suggest a bluebird, Microsoft and Twitter’s a cardinal. Google’s bird previously resembled a canary, Samsung’s was previously green, and Microsoft and Twitter’s birds were once blue.

name: Birthday Cake
description: A frosted cake with lit candles, as presented for a birthday celebration. The style of cake widely varies across platforms. With white frosting and strawberries, Apple and Google’s designs suggest a Japanese Christmas cake. Other vendors depict a chocolate, pink, and/or sponge cake.

name: Bison
description: A brown bison shown in full profile with horns, a beard, and woolly mane. Also called a buffalo in North America.

name: Biting Lip
description:
A mouth with the top teeth biting down on one side of the lower lip.

Used in romantic contexts to express flirtation or arousal. Can be used to express anticipation or excitement in general. Also may be used to express anxiety, pain, worry, or insecurity.

name: Black Bird
description:
A bird with black feathers, shown either standing in full profile or as a bird head. Can be used to represent various black-feathered birds, such as crows, ravens, blackbirds, and more.

Black-feathered birds have been associated with magic and the occult across many global cultures, often as an omen of bad tidings.

name: Black Cat
description: A black cat shown in full profile, often with its tail curling upward.

name: Black Chess Pawn
description: A single black pawn used in the game of chess.

name: Black Circle for Record
description: A record icon, displayed as a circle.

name: Black Club Suit
description:
A club symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the clubs suit.

Apple's design previously displayed the black spade symbol on a white playing card.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Black Diamond Suit
description:
A diamond symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the diamonds suit.

Apple's design previously displayed the red diamond symbol on a white playing card.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Black Down-Pointing Double Triangle
description: Two triangles pointing down.¬†Similar to¬†rewind¬†icon,¬†rotated 90¬∞ counter-clockwise.

name: Black Heart
description: A heart shaded completely black. May be used to express morbidity, sorrow, or a form of dark humor, but despite the color remains most commonly used for love and affection.

name: Black Heart Suit
description:
A heart symbol emoji, used in card games for the hearts suit. In emoji form, this is most commonly used for love, affectiction, romance and positive intentions. Sometimes shown in a slightly darker shade of red than ‚ù§Ô∏è Red Heart.

Apple's design previously displayed the heart symbol on a white playing card.

Note: the Unicode Character Database (UCD) name “Black Heart Suit” pre-dates color emoji, when the term referred to a solid, black ♥ heart suit character. See the glossary for information on the term black in Unicode character names.

name: Black Large Square

A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing left.

description: A medium-small-sized square shaded completely black. Smaller than the ‚¨õ Black Large Square and ‚óæ Black Medium-Small Square but larger than the  ‚ñ™Ô∏è Black Small Square.

name: Black Medium Square
description: A medium-sized square shaded completely black. Smaller than the ‚¨õ Black Large Square and larger than the ‚óæ Black Medium-Small Square and the ‚ñ™Ô∏è Black Small Square.

name: Black Nib
description:
The silver nib of a fountain pen, which distributes ink onto a writing surface. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Like üñãÔ∏è Fountain Pen, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).

Several platforms, including Google, Microsoft, and Samsung, depict only a nib, sometimes ringed with gold. Other platforms, including Apple and Twitter, feature the same designs as their üñãÔ∏è Fountain Pen, but with their tips angled to the lower right.

name: Black Question Mark Ornament
description: A large red question mark (?) symbol emoji.

name: Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle
description: Two triangles pointing to the right. Most commonly used as a symbol¬†for fast forwarding¬†media such as¬†video tapes,¬†CDs, or digital audio and video.

name: Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle with Vertical Bar
description: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the next track (or scene). Shown as two triangles pointing right followed by a vertical bar.

name: Black Right-Pointing Triangle
description:
A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing right. Commonly used as a symbol for play.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Black Right-Pointing Triangle with Double Vertical Bar
description: A play-pause icon, showing a right-pointing triangle (play) next to a double vertical bar (pause).

name: Black Rightwards Arrow
description:
An arrow, pointing right.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Black Scissors
description:
A pair of scissors, as used to cut paper or hair. Generally shown open, blades down, with red handles. Commonly used for content concerning haircuts, fashion design, arts and crafts, and various senses of cutting.

WhatsApp’s design features green handles with blades pointed up.

See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names.

name: Black Small Square
description: A very small square shaded completely black. Notably smaller than the ‚¨õ Black Large Square, ‚óºÔ∏è Black Medium Square, and the ‚óæ Black Medium-Small Square.

name: Black Spade Suit
description:
A spade symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the spades suit.

Apple's design previously displayed the black spade symbol on a white playing card.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Black Square Button
description:
A square version of the üîò Radio Button emoji.

The inverse of the üî≥ White Square Button.

name: Black Square for Stop
description: A stop icon, displayed as a square.

name: Black Sun with Rays
description:
The sun, the star at the center of our solar system. Generally depicted as a golden-yellow disc radiating eight triangular rays, representing the sun’s heat and light.

Commonly used to represent sunny, warm, or hot weather, light, heat, energy, life, outer space, astronomy, and various positive and happy (sunny) feelings. As such, this emoji tends to spike in popularity during the summer months.

See also üåû Sun With Face. Not to be confused with üîÜ Bright Button or üîÖ Dim Button.

Google’s sun was once red, Samsung’s previously gray. See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names.

name: Black Telephone
description:
A classic telephone, as a landline home phone. Most platforms depict a red, push-button phone with the handset on the base. Some platforms feature designs with rotary dials.

Used for various content concerning literal and figurative phone calling. Also used as an icon before a phone number.

See glossary for the term black in Unicode character names.

name: Black Universal Recycling Symbol
description:
The universal recycling symbol, featuring three arrows pointing clockwise in a triangular formation.

The word “black” in the official name is due to this emoji existing as a unicode character before the current standardized emoji set.

name: Black Up-Pointing Double Triangle
description: Two triangles pointing up. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° clockwise.

name: Blossom
description:
A flower that has blossomed. Depicted as a flower with white or yellow petals, as a daisy, with a golden center.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such ideas as love, appreciation, and happiness. Also used as a yellow or white accent color.

Not to be confused with üåª Sunflower or üå∏ Cherry Blossom, though their applications may overlap.

Google's flower was once pink. Microsoft's was previously yellow, Samsung's white.

name: Blowfish
description:
A blowfish (puffer), which puffs up and becomes spiky when alarmed. Depicted as an orange or brown blowfish in full profile facing left, with small fins, a white underside, and a round, spiky body, as if inflated.

Called fugu in Japan, where it’s consumed as a delicacy.

May be to represent a variety of fish (saltwater or freshwater), fishing, metaphorical senses of fish, and fish as food, as consumed in the form of üç£ Sushi. Not to be confused with üêü Fish or üê† Tropical Fish, though their applications may overlap. See also üé£ Fishing Pole.

Google’s blowfish was previously blue, Microsoft’s yellow, and Facebook’s white.

name: Blue Book
description:
A closed, blue, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a blue accent color.

Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 3 by John Appleseed. Samsung’s design previously included the text Blue Book.

Note that in the U.S., this emoji may be associated with blue book exams and the Kelley Blue Book.

name: Blue Heart
description:
A blue heart emoji, commonly used by brands as a neutral heart color.

An early Google design of this emoji depicted the heart as if it were made out of gemstone.

name: Blueberries
description: A few ripe blueberries clustered together. Most platforms show three blueberries, and some show small green leaves coming out from behind the blueberries.

name: Boar
description:
A boar, a hairy, wild pig with tusks. Generally depicted as the face of a brown boar, either facing left or looking straight ahead, with prominent tusks projecting from its lower jaw.

Twitter's design feature a friendly, cartoon-styled face, as did an early Facebook design. WhatsApp’s design displays the animal in full, as Google, Microsoft, and Samsung previously did.

Not to be confused with üêñ Pig or üê∑ Pig Face, though their applications may overlap.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

name: Bomb
description:
A cartoon-styled bomb, depicted as a black ball with a burning fuse.

Commonly used for various figurative bombs or explosions, e.g., slang bomb, a “home run” in baseball or softball; "excellent" or "attractive." Sometimes applied in contexts of war, weapons, or violence.

Earlier designs from SoftBank and au by KDDI animated the bomb as exploding.

name: Bone
description:
A bone which may be used for a dog to chew on, or as a part of the human body. The type of bone is not specified.

May be used to represent the NSFW term "to bone".

name: Bookmark
description:
A bookmark, as used to mark one's place in a book. May also represent bookmarks on an internet browser. Appearance varies across platforms, but generally depicted at a 45° angle as a thin, white or red strip with a decorative tie and design, such as flower or star.

May be used for various content concerning reading, labeling, or tagging.

WhatsApp’s bookmark is purple. Twitter’s design shows a red bookmark in a closed book, similar to previous designs from Microsoft. Twitter and Google’s designs previously featured a blue bookmark.

Not to be confused with üè∑Ô∏è Label.

name: Bookmark Tabs
description:
Sheets of white, printed paper with variously colored tabs to bookmark important sections or indicate signature lines. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

The number of pages and tabs vary, with Microsoft and Twitter’s designs featuring one page with a single, purple-colored tab. Facebook’s is printed with NDA, or nondisclosure agreement. Most platforms indicate text with dark lines. Apple’s design features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:

Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.

Early designs from au by KDDI resemble üìÉ Page With Curl.

Not to be confused with üìÑ Page Facing Up or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

name: Books
description:
A loose stack of three of more different-colored, hardcover books. Commonly used for various content concerning reading and schooling. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but often shown with red, green, and blue covers.

Samsung’s design previously featured the easter egg initials MJ printed on the pages of its bottom book.

name: Boomerang
description:
A wooden boomerang with bright colors on its tips. Google and Twitter's designs show motion lines to illustrate the path of a boomerang.

Used literally to represent a boomerang. Also used to represent Aboriginal people or Australia in general. May be used to represent something that comes back or returns.

name: Bottle with Popping Cork
description: A green bottle of champagne or sparkling wine with label, its cork popping to shoot out its bubbly contents. Used for a range of celebratory occasions, such as New Year's Eve, birthdays, weddings, or other life accomplishments.

name: Bouquet
description:
A bouquet of brightly colored flowers. Generally depicted as a collection of pink and yellow flowers with green stems tied together. Positioned at various angles across platforms.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May also be more generally used to express such sentiments as love, appreciation, and happiness.

Google’s flowers were previously all yellow, Microsoft’s roses, and Samsung’s pink and white.

name: Bow and Arrow
description:
A bow and arrow used in the sport of archery. May also be used by cupid.

Can also be used to represent ‚ôê Sagittarius in the Western zodiac.

name: Bowl with Spoon
description:
A bowl with a silver spoon inside, as used to eat cereal or soup. Bowl color varies across platforms, as do contents, though most are empty.

WhatsApp's bowl contains tomato soup, while Google's previously contained breakfast cereal.

name: Bowling
description: Ten-pin bowling emoji, showing a bowling ball and pins.

name: Boxing Glove
description: A padded boxing glove, used in the sport of boxing. Usually red.

name: Boy
description:
The face of a boy, smiling.

Previously differentiated from üë® Man on Android by wearing a cap, and on iOS by the lack of any facial hair.

Variants include üë¶ Child and üëß Girl.

name: Brain
description:
A human brain, shown in pink on most platforms. Used to indicate thinking or the human mind.

On platforms such as TikTok an alternative meaning of this emoji is to represent 'giving head' (NSFW meanings).

name: Bread
description:
A loaf of white or wheat bread, as before it is sliced for toast or sandwiches. May also be used to denote financial success, as per the slang term "let's get this bread".

Microsoft's design previously resembled a ü•ñ Baguette.

name: Breast-Feeding
description:
A woman shown breastfeeding a baby, sometimes looking down to the infant and smiling.

This emoji supports skin tone modifiers, which apply to the mother. The head of the baby is recommended to be hidden to avoid a situation where the skin tone of the baby would only correlate to the skin tone of the mother.

See üßë‍üçº Person Feeding Baby for bottle feeding instead of breastfeeding.

name: Brick
description:
A red brick or bricks. Depicted in a loose stack, a single object with holes, or as built into wall, as of a house, school, or other structure.

Commonly used for various content concerning building and construction. May also be used for figurative bricks, e.g., slang brick, “extremely cold (weather).”

name: Bride with Veil
description: A person in traditional western wedding dress with a veil over their head.

name: Bridge at Night
description: A lit-up bridge,¬†shown at night.

name: Briefcase
description:
A place to store notes and other office materials. Primarily used by older people.

Generally shown as a brown case with a handle on top, and a silver or gold colored clasp on the front. Facebook shows two leather straps on the front.

name: Briefs
description:
Underwear or swim briefs. The swimming variety are often called 'Speedos' after the brand. This emoji is shown in different colors and styles across platforms. Some platforms depict this emoji as tighty whities with a visible fly, while others use a less specific design.

Related emojis include üëô Bikini, ü©≥ Shorts, and ü©± One-Piece Swimsuit.

name: Broccoli
description: A rich green, tree-like head or floret of broccoli.

name: Broken Heart
description: A love heart, broken in two. This emoji represents the aching one feels when they are missing the person they love.

name: Broom
description:
A traditional broom, as used for sweeping—or ridden by a witch. Shown at a 45° angle, with a wooden handle and yellow bristles at the lower left.

Commonly used for various content concerning cleaning, brushing, and figurative sweeps (e.g., in sports or awards). Not to be confused with üñåÔ∏è Paintbrush.

name: Brown Heart
description:
A brown heart, often used discuss topics related to racial identity üßëüèΩüßëüèæüßëüèø

The least used of the nine colored hearts (‚ù§Ô∏èüß°üíõüíöüíôüíúüñ§ü§çü§é).

name: Bubble Tea
description: Bubble tea is a tea-based drink invented in Taiwan which typically contain tea, flavored milk, and sugar. Commonly served with tapioca pearls, also known as boba, in a plastic cup with a wide straw.

name: Bubbles
description: A few floating bubbles. May be used to represent soap suds, carbonation, or an effervescent personality.

name: Bucket
description:
A blue or green bucket or pail. Used to talk about real or metaphorical buckets.

May be used to talk about bucket lists, kicking the bucket, making baskets in basketball, an abundance of something (like rain or money), and many other contexts.

name: Bug
description:
A bug, or insect, generally depicted as a caterpillar, which becomes a ü¶ã Butterfly. Shown in full profile facing left, inching up on the back of its green, segmented, and textured body. Often featuring black stripes or yellow dots and tentacles on its head.

May be used to represent various insects, worms, and related animals. May also be used for metaphorical senses of bug.

Twitter’s bug is purple. Apple’s bug is hairy with a red head and legs and black stripes on its body. Facebook’s bug also has a yellowish-orange head. Google and Microsoft’s bugs previously resembled an orange centipede or millipede, and Samsung’s had a cartoon-styled face with a purple nose.

name: Building Construction
description: A construction site generally depicted as a tower crane shown lifting steel or other building materials.

name: Burrito
description: A Mexican or Tex-Mex burrito, featuring a wrapped flour tortilla filled with such ingredients as beef, rice, beans, cheese, tomato, lettuce, and sour cream. Served in foil on several major platforms, suggesting a Mission burrito associated with San Francisco. Not to be confused with the Stuffed Flatbread.

name: Bus
description: A bus used for public transport in cities and towns. Could also be used as a school bus.

name: Bus Stop
description:
A sign indicating the location of a bus stop by the side of a road.

Some platforms display this as a red, white and blue sign which can be found in parts of Japan. This interpretation has a slight resemblance to the Pepsi Globe.

Other platforms base this emoji design on bus stop signage of other regions.

name: Bust in Silhouette
description: Generic profile of one person. Often used in interface design to represent a user.

name: Busts in Silhouette
description: Generic profile of two people. Often used in interface design to represent users.

name: Butter
description: A pale yellow stick of butter. Can be used to talk about cooking or eating. Might also be used in idioms or to reference something that is smooth.

name: Butterfly
description:
A butterfly, a beautiful winged insect whose larva is a caterpillar. Depicted with its wings outspread, as a blue-and-black morpho butterfly or orange-and-black monarch butterfly.

May be used to represent a moth and ideas of beauty and happiness.

Samsung’s butterfly previously resembled a monarch.

name: Cactus
description:
A cactus, a spiky plant that grows in very dry regions. Depicted as a light-green saguaro cactus with two side arms covered in spines.

May be used to represent various succulents, deserts, Southwestern culture, or the Wild West.

WhatsApp’s cactus is topped with three red flowers.

name: Calendar
description:
A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page torn off from a daily desk calendar, displaying month and day on a white, square page.

Like üìÜ Tear-Off Calendar and üóìÔ∏è Spiral Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally.

The date shown is July 17. This date was first used by Apple as a reference to when iCal for Mac premiered at MacWorld Expo in 2002. Since 2014 Emojipedia has celebrated World Emoji Day on July 17, because of this emoji.

Major platforms previously used a variety of dates on this calendar, but have changed in recent years to also show July 17, to avoid confusion on World Emoji Day. Some vendors still feature easter egg dates marking company founding or other milestones:


	üìÖ Apple: July 17 (Mac iCal announcement in 2002, later World Emoji Day)
	üìÖ Google: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a generic monthly calendar)
	üìÖ Microsoft: a generic month
	üìÖ Samsung: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a monthly calendar turned to May)
	üìÖ WhatsApp: Feb 24 (incorporation of WhatsApp in 2009)
	üìÖ Twitter/X: Jul 17  (changed from March 21 which was the founding date of Twitter in 2006; previously July 15, the date Twitter launched)
	üìÖ Facebook: May 14 (birthday of founder Mark Zuckerberg; previously a generic 3rd)
	üìÖ Huawei: September 15
	üìÖ JoyPixels: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
	üìÖ SerenityOS: 10


Discontinued:


	üìÖ Messenger: August (first release of Messenger apps in 2011)
	üìÖ LG: Mar 27 (unknown)
	üìÖ HTC: generic
	üìÖ Mozilla: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
	üìÖ emojidex: Tuesday, Jan 12 (unknown)
	üìÖ Softbank: generic
	üìÖ Docomo: 12 (suggesting the number of months in a year)  
	üìÖ au by KDDI: 12

name: Call Me Hand
description:
A hand with thumb and little (pinky) finger extended, making a traditional phone-like shape. May be used in conjunction with a face to suggest “call me” (please).

Not to be confused with the sign of the horn. Commonly used as a shaka sign, which is a similar gesture at a different orientation.

name: Camera
description:
A classic camera, as an SLR used to take pictures before camera phones. Generally depicted with a black and silver casing with lens and operating controls.

Commonly used for various content concerning photography as well as an icon for a picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.

See also üì∏ Camera With Flash.

name: Camera with Flash
description:
A classic camera, shown with its flash going off, as to illuminate a darker scene. Vendors implement the same design as üì∑ Camera with a burst of light, often resembling üí• Collision.

Commonly used for various content concerning photography as well as an icon for a picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.

name: Camping
description: A campsite featuring a tent and a tree, and perhaps a campfire. Similar to the tent emoji.

name: Cancer
description: The Cancer astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Crab.

name: Candle
description:
A burning candle, as lit when taking a bath or the power is out. Depicted as a white, pillar-shaped candle with a flame and wax dripping down its sides.

Used for a wide array of content, such as various senses of light, birthdays, remembrance, relaxation, and topics concerning Christmas, religion and Halloween. Notably featured in the Summoning Circle meme on Twitter.

Apple's candle is in a silver holder. Samsung’s candle was previously pink, perhaps as in a birthday cake.

name: Candy
description:
A small piece of candy wrapped in plastic or wax paper with twists on its ends. Shape and color vary widely by platform. Facebook’s design used to resemble a classic unwrapped red-and-white peppermint. May also be called sweets or lollies.

This emoji tends to spike in use around Halloween.

name: Canned Food
description: A can or tin of food, depicted as tomatoes or a generic green vegetable. May be also used to represent sauce or soup.

name: Canoe
description:
A narrow lightweight water vessel that is usually pointed on both ends and made of either wood or plastic.

Generally depicted with a paddle.

name: Capricorn
description: The Capricorn astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Goat.

name: Card File Box
description:
A black or gray box with a label holder, containing card index dividers with multicolored tabs, as used to organize and store files. Apple and Facebook’s designs include a lid.

Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work.

Microsoft’s design previously resembled a shoebox.

name: Card Index
description:
A card index, as a Rolodex, once used to organize and access cards containing the information of personal or business contacts. Depicted as a black or gray rotating device with a contact card displayed, including a graphic and text.

Occasionally used to represent contact details/information and business cards. Thanks to its appearance, this emoji is sometimes mistaken for such things as documents or word processing.

Apple’s design features a picture of its üë© Woman, identified as Jane Appleseed (previously John Appleseed) with the following contact details as an easter egg:

appleseed@me.com
125 Main St.
City Name, CA 95014
Work: (408) 123-4567
Home: (400) 765-4321

95014 is the zip code (postcode) for Apple’s corporate headquarters in Cupertino, California.

JoyPixels features its üë©‍‚öïÔ∏è Woman Health Care Worker. WhatsApp's design also shows the picture of a woman.

name: Card Index Dividers
description:
A set of tabbed dividers or file guides, as used to organize a card index or file box. Depicted with three or more multicolored tabs on manila paper.

Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work.

WhatsApp’s design features tabbed index cards. Samsung’s design previously suggested a blue, multi-tabbed file folder.

name: Carousel Horse
description:
A wooden painted horse, found on the carousel at a carnival. Faces to the left-of screen.

A previous version of Windows displayed the carousel horse facing right, which was changed to face left on Windows 10 for cross-platform consistency.

name: Carp Streamer
description:
Japanese koinobori, decorative, carp-shaped windsocks flown in celebration of Children’s Day on May 5 in Japan. Generally depicted as a blue and red stylized carp fish on a golden pole.

When not applied to Children’s Day, used for various idiosyncratic purposes. SoftBank’s design resembles more traditional koinobori.

name: Carpentry Saw
description: A long silver saw with a wooden handle. Used to represent construction, carpentry, renovation, or tools in general.

name: Carrot
description: A whole, bright orange carrot, topped with long green leaves, as if freshly plucked from the garden. Some platforms feature a longer, thinner carrot, others a shorter, more bulbous one.

name: Cat
description:
A domestic cat, beloved as a pet. Generally depicted as a light-orange cat with stripes, as a tabby, in full profile on all fours facing left, with its long tell held upright.

See also üê± Cat Face.

Google’s cat is cartoon-styled, shown sitting on its hind legs with a friendly expression and whiskers. Facebook’s cat is a gray tabby, though previously was orange. Microsoft and Samsung’s cats were previously gray, Twitter’s brown.

name: Cat Face
description:
Meow! A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a cat, looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a yellowish-orange cat face with pointed ears and whiskers.

May be used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied üêà Cat, though their applications generally overlap.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Vendors implement the same or similar cat in their üêà Cat as well as in their cat-faced variants of smileys:


	üòº Cat Face With Wry Smile
	üòπ Cat Face With Tears of Joy
	üôÄ Weary Cat Face
	üòæ Pouting Cat Face
	üòø Crying Cat Face
	üòª Smiling Cat Face With Heart-Eyes
	üò∫ Grinning Cat Face
	üò∏ Grinning Cat Face With Smiling Eyes
	üòΩ Kissing Cat Face


Google’s cat face was previously orange, Samsung’s gray, and Facebook’s once gray and white. Included in the earliest Japanese emoji sets from Softbank, Docomo, and au by KDDI.

name: Cat Face with Tears of Joy
description: A cartoon cat variant of üòÇ Face With Tears of Joy. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Cat Face with Wry Smile
description: A cartoon cat variant of üòè Smirking Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Chains
description:
Two parallel lengths of silver chain. Occasionally used as an icon before a hyperlink or for metaphorical connections or chains, e.g., slang off the chains.

Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white chains in a blue square, as a sign or icon for snow chains for winter driving.

Not to be confused with üîó Link, üìé Paperclip, üñáÔ∏è Linked Paperclips, or üß∑ Safety Pin.

name: Chair
description:
A simple wooden chair.

Distinct from üí∫ Seat, which is generally depicted as a fixed plane, train, or bus seat, as opposed to a chair which can be moved.

May have sexual connotations (e.g., sit on my face).

In 2021 this emoji was also used on TikTok to signify laughter or approval or to create confusion for people not in the know. Learn more here.

name: Chart with Downwards Trend
description:
A graph showing a colored trend line, often blue, decreasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of decrease, from numeral data to being metaphorically down. May also represent facts, figures, and charts more generally.

WhatsApp’s line is red, while Facebook’s orange. Google’s line was previously green.

While many western countries use red to indicate a negative result, Japan and other south east Asian countries use red in a positive context.

name: Chart with Upwards Trend
description:
A graph showing a red (or sometimes green) trend line increasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of increase, from numerical data to being metaphorically on the rise. May also represent trending content as well as facts, figures, and charts more generally.

Note: red is used to represent increases in stock prices in Japan, where this emoji originates.

name: Chart with Upwards Trend and Yen Sign
description: A graph showing the value of the Japanese Yen rising.

name: Cheering Megaphone
description:
A handheld megaphone, used to amplify a person's voice.

May also be known as a speaking trumpet, bullhorn, blowhorn, or loudhailer.

name: Cheese Wedge
description: A wedge of yellow-orange cheese with holes, like a Swiss, but used for the food in general. May be used for various cheese-related slang expressions (e.g., “cheesy,” “say cheese,” “big cheese”).

name: Chequered Flag
description: A flag with black and white squares shown in a checkerboard pattern. Used to signal the start or end of a motor car race, though most often used to indicate that the first vehicle within a race has crossed the finish line.

name: Cherries
description: Two rich red cherries with a green leaf and joined at their long stems. May be used to refer to breasts on TikTok and other social media platforms.

name: Cherry Blossom
description:
The pink flower of a cherry blossom tree. Depicted as a single, light-pink cherry blossom with five, notched petals and red-tipped stamens in a yellow or white center.

A traditional symbol in Japan, where the flower is called sakura and celebrated in annual viewings.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such ideas as love and beauty. Also used as a pink accent color.

Not to be confused with üíÆ White Flower and üå∫ Hibiscus, though their applications may overlap.

name: Chestnut
description:
The reddish-brown, acorn-shaped chestnut, tapering to a sharp tip from its light brown base on most platforms. A popular roasted snack associated with autumn and Christmas. 

May be used for other edible nuts (e.g., walnuts) or sexual slang.

name: Chicken
description:
A chicken, a bird used for its meat and eggs. Generally depicted as the white head of a chicken (hen or rooster) looking left, with a yellow beak, red comb on its head, and red wattle on its neck.

May be consumed in the form of üçó Poultry Leg. Not to be confused with the full-bodied üêì Rooster, though their applications overlap. Also may be used for metaphorical senses of chicken (e.g., “coward”).

See also üê£ Hatching Chick, üê§ Baby Chick, and üê• Front-Facing Baby Chick.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Twitter’s chicken head is looking straight ahead. Microsoft’s chicken was previously yellow, while Samsung’s faced forward; Facebook’s design once featured a full, brown bird, while Google’s design previously featured a full bodied chicken.

name: Child
description:
A child with no gender specified. This emoji may be used to talk about children in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üëß Girl and üë¶ Boy.

name: Children Crossing
description: A crossing sign for children, usually positioned near schools or other areas that drivers should be cautious of young children in the area.

name: Chipmunk
description:
A chipmunk, a small rodent with puffy cheeks. Depicted as a brown chipmunk in full profile facing left, sitting on its hind legs with a bushy tail and striped body. Generally holding an acorn or other nut in its hands.

May be used to represent a squirrel or related animals.

At one point, Google’s chipmunk was looking forward, squinting with a buck tooth. Microsoft’s previous black-and-white design could be mistaken for a skunk.

name: Chocolate Bar
description: A block of dark chocolate, usually shown in a red foil wrapper peeled back to show squares of the candy. WhatsApp displays the wrapper in purple, a color commonly associated with Cadbury chocolate.

name: Chopsticks
description: A pair of equal-length chopsticks, an eating utensil used throughout East Asia. Design and color vary widely by platform, though often red or wood-colored and with tips angled together. Featured in many platforms' Steaming Bowl of Food and Takeout Box. A counterpart to utensils such as Fork and Knife and Spoon.

name: Christmas Tree
description:
A classic Christmas tree, an evergreen tree decorated with lights and ornaments to celebrate Christmas.  Depicted with round, variously colored ornaments and topped with a yellow star.

Used for various content concerning the Christmas holiday and season as well as for wintertime more generally.

Not to be confused with üå≤ Evergreen Tree, though their applications may overlap.

Google and Samsung's trees were previously adorned with tinsel, Microsoft's previously lacked ornaments.

name: Church
description: A church building, generally associated with Christian denominations. In addition quiet prayer, churches hold regular worship services, weddings, baptisms and funerals.

name: Cinema
description: An emoji representing the cinema: a large screen showing the latest movies, available to the public. Displayed by most platforms as a film projector symbol, and previously by Google and Microsoft as a cinema screen with curtains.

name: Circled Ideograph Accept
description: The ÂèØ (ka) character means to allow, to permit, and to be able to in Japanese.

name: Circled Ideograph Advantage
description: Denotes a ‚Äúgood bargain‚Äù in Japanese.

name: Circled Ideograph Congratulation
description: Translated from Japanese, this means "congratulations" or "pray for happiness".

name: Circled Ideograph Secret
description: The Áßò character means secret or confidential in Japanese.

name: Circled Latin Capital Letter M
description: The letter M in a circle, commonly used in to identify a Metro (subway, underground train) station in a city area.

name: Circus Tent
description: A circular ‘big top’ circus tent, with a triangle flag on top.

name: Cityscape
description:
A cityscape showing a variety of highrise buildings during the daytime. Often featuring several clouds in the sky.

See also: üåÉ Night with Stars

name: Cityscape at Dusk
description: A view of city buildings as the last light disappears from the sky. An orange (or blue) glow lingers, before the stars of the night sky become visible.

name: Clapper Board
description:
A board which contains the scene name, number, and film. A person ‚Äòclaps‚Äô the board shut at the top while saying ‚ÄúAction‚Äù or ‚ÄúCut‚Äù to indicate the start and stop of a scene that is being filmed.
This is used to synchronise the audio of the clap with the visuals.

name: Clapping Hands Sign
description: Two hands clapping emoji, which when used multiple times can be used as a round of applause.

name: Classical Building
description: A building shown with columns in a classical style, sometimes used to represent a courthouse, town hall, post office or stock exchange.

name: Clinking Beer Mugs
description: Two frosty mugs of beer with frothy heads being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Several platforms include stylized lines to mark the clinking. See also ü•Ç Clinking Glasses.

name: Clinking Glasses
description:
Two flutes of champagne or sparkling wine being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). This emoji tends to spike in popularity during New Year's Eve. 

Samsung’s design suggests two glasses of white wine. Some platforms include stylized links to mark the clinking.

See also Clinking Beer Mugs—and Bottle With Popping Cork for a refill.

name: Clipboard
description:
A white piece of paper secured by a silver clip on a brown clipboard, as used as a writing surface when standing. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, especially in sports.

Many platforms indicate text with dark lines. WhatsApp’s design shows lined paper. Facebook’s features the easter egg of a table with first names and numbers, perhaps as birthdates:

Matt 3/28
Louie 4/30
Alexa 6/17
Brian 8/06

Apple’s design also features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:

Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.

name: Clock Face Eight O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as eight o’clock.

name: Clock Face Eight-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as eight-thirty.

name: Clock Face Eleven O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as eleven o'clock.

name: Clock Face Eleven-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as eleven-thirty.

name: Clock Face Five O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as five o’clock.

name: Clock Face Five-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as five-thirty.

name: Clock Face Four O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as four o’clock.

name: Clock Face Four-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as four-thirty.

name: Clock Face Nine O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as nine o’clock.

name: Clock Face Nine-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as nine-thirty.

name: Clock Face One O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as one o’clock.

name: Clock Face One-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as one-thirty.

name: Clock Face Seven O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as seven o’clock.

name: Clock Face Seven-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as seven-thirty.

name: Clock Face Six O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as six o’clock.

name: Clock Face Six-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as six-thirty.

name: Clock Face Ten O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as ten o’clock.

name: Clock Face Ten-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as ten-thirty.

name: Clock Face Three O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as three o’clock.

name: Clock Face Three-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as three-thirty.

name: Clock Face Twelve O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as twelve o’clock.

name: Clock Face Twelve-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as twelve-thirty.

name: Clock Face Two O‚ÄôClock
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as two o’clock.

name: Clock Face Two-Thirty
description: The face of an analog clock displaying the time as two-thirty.

name: Clockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows
description: Circular arrows pointing in an anticlockwise direction. Similar to symbols sometimes used for refresh or rotate.

name: Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows
description: Circular arrows pointing in a clockwise direction. Used in music player applications to loop a track or album continuously. Commonly used to repesent a retweet on Twitter.

name: Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows with Circled One Overlay
description: Arrows pointing in a clockwise direction, with a number 1 badge in the lower corner.¬†¬†Used in music player applications to¬†loop a track or album once.

name: Closed Book
description:
A closed, hardcover book depicted with a red cover on most platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a red accent color.

Apple’s cover features the easter egg “Vol. 1 by John Appleseed.” Apple’s original design for this emoji said “Vol. 3 by John Appleseed,” however now this title appears on Apple’s üìò Blue Book design.

Google’s design previously featured a brown cover with a red bookmark. Samsung’s artwork once featured a blue cover printed with the initials HYDM, though its latest design has a red cover.

name: Closed Lock with Key
description:
A locked (closed) padlock with an upright key at its right. Vendors implement the same designs as their üîí Locked and üîë Key.

May represent digital keys in public-key technology. May have similar applications as üîí Locked (privacy, security) and üîë Key (means of access, "crucial"). Sometimes used to represent a locket to symbolize romantic love and commitment.

Apple’s design previously featured the easter egg UM242 on its key, a reference to locks on Herman Miller office furniture. Facebook’s design once displayed a silver key, its head at the bottom.

This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Additionally, this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with private accounts on the platform. Learn more here.

name: Closed Mailbox with Lowered Flag
description:
A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag lowered. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

Indicates in the United States that no incoming mail (post) has been delivered. May also indicate that outgoing mail has been picked up.

Compare üì´ Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, üì≠ Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and üì¨ Open Mailbox With Raised Flag.

name: Closed Mailbox with Raised Flag
description:
A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag raised. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

Indicates in the United States that incoming mail (post) has been delivered. May also indicate that there is outgoing mail for pickup.

An early Apple design showed an open mailbox with an envelope, similar to its üì¨ Open Mailbox With Raised Flag design.

Compare üì™ Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, üì≠ Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and üì¨ Open Mailbox With Raised Flag.

name: Closed Umbrella
description:
An umbrella that is closed, likely as a result of collapsing it prior to going indoors.

Shows as purple on Apple and Samsung devices, as well as on Twitter. It is blue on Google devices and Facebook, and green on WhatsApp.

name: Cloud
description:
A fluffy, white cloud, as a cumulus. May be used as a weather icon to represent a cloudy or overcast day.

Twitter’s design features two clouds. Google’s cloud was previously bluish.

name: Cloud with Lightning
description:
A thundercloud. Depicted as a yellow lightning bolt flashing from a white cloud.

May be used as a weather icon to represent thunderstorms.

Not to be confused with ‚õàÔ∏è Cloud With Lightning and Rain, though their applications may overlap.

Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish with two lightning bolts.

name: Cloud with Rain
description:
A rain cloud. (Keep dry with ‚òî Umbrella With Rain Drops.) Depicted as blue raindrops falling from a white cloud. Most platforms depict the raindrops falling to the left.

May be used as a weather icon to represent rain showers or a rainy day.

Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish.

name: Cloud with Snow
description:
A snow cloud. Depicted as blue snowflakes falling from a white cloud.

May be used as a weather icon to represent snow showers or a snowy day.

Not to be confused with üåßÔ∏è Cloud With Rain.

name: Cloud with Tornado
description:
A tornado, a destructive column of air. Depicted as a gray, funnel-shaped cloud, rotating in contact with the ground.

May be used as a weather icon to represent a tornado. May also be used to represent a metaphorical tornado (e.g., a powerful force or violent outburst).

Google’s tornado was previously blue and white. Microsoft and Samsung’s designs previously depicted tornadoes defending from a cumulus cloud.

name: Clown Face
description:
A circus or birthday clown displayed with white face makeup, a red nose, exaggerated eyes and smile, and two tufts of hair (red or blue). Commonly used as comment on TikTok or other social media platforms to indicate that a person is foolish, idiotic and/or selfish.

May instead describe something that is creepy or scary. Sometimes used as an unflattering alias for Donald Trump.

name: Coat
description: A winter jacket, shown in a variety of colors and styles.

name: Cockroach
description:
A brown cockroach shown with antennae, six legs, and two sensory pads at its rear called cerci.

Can be used to talk about cockroaches or insects in general. May also be used metaphorically as an insult to call a person a pest, an annoyance, or to suggest they are subhuman.

name: Cocktail Glass
description: A stemmed glass with a cone-shaped bowl, used for serving cocktails. Depicted as a martini garnished with an olive. Might be gin or vodka, shaken or stirred. See also Tropical Drink.

name: Coconut
Coffin
description:
A traditional coffin, as used to bury the dead. Depicted at various angles as a closed, six-sided, wooden coffin, tapered at the head and foot with golden handles.

Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative death. May also be used for various content concerning funerals, horror, and Halloween.

Apple and Microsoft’s designs place flowers on their lids.

name: Coin
description:
A coin shown in silver or gold. Design varies by platform, with Google and Twitter showing a üèõÔ∏è Classical Building and Samsung showing the number one, similar to their ü•á 1st Place Medal design.

Apple’s coin has the text "The Crazy Ones," a reference to its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign and commonly used as placeholder text in Apple icons and emoji designs.

name: Collision Symbol
description:
A cartoon-styled representation of a collision. Depicted as a star-like, orange-and-yellow fiery burst, generally with one point extending to the bottom right, as if from the source of the collision.
