description: A decorative symbol that appears like a golden flower, but found in all manner of logos, symbols, and patterns. This symbol forms part of the World Scout Emblem, amongst other uses.

name: Flexed Biceps
description: An arm flexing to show its biceps muscle. Represents strength, or working out.

name: Floppy Disk
description:
A 3.5-inch floppy disk, a data storage format popular in the 1980–90s but largely preserved as a Save icon in computer programs. Shown with its silver shutter positioned up and in a black housing with a white label, accented with blue or red.

Occasionally used for various content concerning computers, including nostalgia for old technology, as well as to represent electronic saving.

name: Flower Playing Cards
description:
A type of cards known as hanafuda cards in Japan which are used for a range of different games that require associating pictures (there are no numbers on the cards).

The artwork for this emoji shows the Full Moon with Red Sky card, but could theoretically display any of the available cards.

name: Flushed Face
description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows, a small, closed mouth, wide, white eyes staring straight ahead, and blushing cheeks. Intended to depict such feelings as embarrassment, but meaning very widely varies. Other senses include flattery, surprise, disbelief, admiration, affection, and excitement.

Google's design previously featured a more bashful expression and Samsung, a more ashamed one. An early Microsoft design featured an awkward smile.

name: Flute
description: A simple yellow flute made of bamboo, plastic, or metal.

name: Fly
description:
A fly with a dark or iridescent green body, six legs, and two translucent wings. On most platforms, its eyes are red.

Can be used to talk about the insect or flight in general. May also be used metaphorically as an adjective meaning "cool."

name: Flying Disc
description: A flying disc, more commonly known as a frisbee. Used in the sport of Ultimate or disc golf.

name: Flying Saucer
description: A flying saucer, sometimes referred to as an Unidentified Flying Object (UFO). Previously shown on some platforms with an alien at the controls and/or a beam of light emitting from the base.

name: Fog
description:
Fog, as obscures visibility. Generally depicted as a square of a gray, hazy, cloud-like mass.

May be used as a weather icon to represent foggy conditions. May also be used to represent metaphorical fog (e.g., a daze).

Not to be confused with üåÅ Foggy, though their applications may overlap.

Microsoft’s design was previously a stylized depiction of fog, featuring three, wavy lines, as was Google’s previous design. Samsung’s fog previously resembled three clouds. Twitter’s design previously resembled its üåÅ Foggy emoji, showing fog obscuring the Golden Gate Bridge.

name: Foggy
description: Foggy weather displayed as fog covering a bridge or cityscape, depending on the platform. For platforms that show a bridge, the red Golden Gate Bridge is generally displayed.

name: Folding Hand Fan
description:
A brightly colored folding hand fan.

Can be used to talk about fans, both manual and electric. Can also be used to reference various dances involving fans including the Korean dance of Buchaechum, the Japanese dance of Nihon-buy≈ç, and the Maranao dance of the Singkil.

May be used to refer to a person who is a fan (or admirer) of someone or something.

May also be used along with the phrases fan the flames or when shit hits the fan.

name: Fondue
description: A red fondue pot. Most platforms show cheese fondue with fondue forks sticking out of the pot.

name: Foot
description: A human foot shown with five toes and may include part or all of the ankle. Shown on Apple platforms as the sole of a foot.

name: Footprints
description: Two human footsteps,  showing the outline of both feet, including all five toes.

name: Fork and Knife
description: A silver fork to the left of a knife, silverware or cutlery used to eat a meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon or used with Fork and Knife With Plate.

name: Fork and Knife with Plate
description:
A silver fork and knife on either side of a white plate, as set for dinner or another meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity on Thanksgiving.

name: Fortune Cookie
description: A golden-brown, crescent-shaped, vanilla-flavored fortune cookie. Usually depicted with a strip of paper—on which a wise saying, lucky numbers, or Chinese vocabulary is written—peaking out of its hollow shell. Given at the end of meals at Chinese restaurants in the West.

name: Fountain
description: A water fountain, found in a park or other public space. Used for decorative purposes. A variety of styles of fountain are shown across different platforms.

name: Four Leaf Clover
description:
A four-leaf clover, a symbol of good luck. Depicted as a bright green sprig of clover, with four, heart-shaped leaves.

Not to be confused with the three-leaf ‚òòÔ∏è Shamrock, though this emoji does tend to spike in popularity on St Patrick’s Day.

name: Fox Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled faced of a fox, the cunning canine, looking straight ahead. Depicted as an orange fox  face with a black nose, pointed ears, and shaggy, white cheeks.

Often used with an affectionate or playful tone (e.g., slang, foxy). Does not have a full-bodied fox emoji counterpart.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

name: Frame with Picture
description:
A framed picture of a painting or photograph, as displayed in a gallery or on a household wall. Vendors feature various scenes, though generally a lush, sunny landscape of hills and mountains, in a gold frame.

Commonly used for various content concerning art, museums, and interior design and decor. May also be used as an icon for a picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.

Microsoft’s design previously showed Ninja Cat. An earlier Microsoft design featured the Mona Lisa, as did a previous Samsung design. Google's design previously displayed the scene depicted in its üèûÔ∏è National Park emoji.

name: Freezing Face
description:
An icy-blue face with gritted teeth usually depicted with icicles clinging to its cheeks or jaw, as if frozen from extreme cold. May also represent unfriendliness (slang, cold) or excellence (slang, cool or chill).

Apple’s design features the same expression as its üò¨ Grimacing Face. Huawei's design has a chipped ü¶∑ Tooth.

name: French Fries
description: Thin-cut, golden-brown French fries, served in a red carton, as at McDonald’s. Apple features Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes on its carton.

name: Fried Shrimp
description: A prawn or shrimp breaded and deep-fried golden-brown. Known as ebi furai in Japan but commonly called shrimp tempura and served in a bento box. Not to be confused with the Shrimp.

name: Frog Face
description:
The face of a frog, the hopping amphibian. Generally depicted as a friendly, cartoon-styled, light-green frog looking straight ahead, with large eyes, slightly open mouth, and nostrils.

Popularly paired with ‚òïÔ∏è Hot Beverage to represent the But That’s None of My Business meme (used for gossip or sarcasm) or Pepe the Frog (associated with trolling and the alt-right).

Facebook’s design previously resembled Kermit the Frog.

name: Front-Facing Baby Chick
description:
A baby chicken (chick), shown as if flapping its wings. Depicted as a yellow chick with an orange beak in full profile standing on its legs, generally with its wings raised.

Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry, eggs), spring, Easter, or slang senses of chick.

Not to be confused with üê§ Baby Chick or üê£ Hatching Chick (still in its egg), though their applications overlap. See also üêî Chicken and üêì Rooster.

Facebook's design previously featured only a chick head facing forward.

name: Frowning Face with Open Mouth
description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes and an open frown. Samsung’s design shows upper teeth and tongue. Meaning widely varies, but may convey mild sadness, disappointment, concern, and amazement.

An early Microsoft design showed a face with its eyebrows contorted in anger.

name: Fuel Pump
description:
A fuel pump, used to fill up a vehicle with gas / petrol.

Shown as red or orange on most platforms. Apple's artwork shows a droplet icon and the numbers 00322 but previously displayed the letter G on the front.

name: Full Moon Symbol
description:
A full moon, the fifth phase of the eight phases of the moon, when it is completely lit. Depicts the moon as a full, gold or silver, cratered disc, completely illuminated by the sun.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. Commonly used during Halloween, associated with werewolves and Friday the 13th.

See also üåù Full Moon Face. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a full moon in a night sky with stars.

name: Full Moon with Face
description:
A full moon with a smiling face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts the moon as a dark disc with a slightly smiling human face and nose.

See also üåï Full Moon. May be used to represent the moon more generally. Commonly used a smiley. Occasionally used for irony and sarcasm.

Apple and WhatsApp’s eyes are looking left, as if giving the side-eye. Samsung and Facebook’s faces are looking straight ahead. Google’s facial expression resembles üòè Smirking Face, Twitter’s üôÇ Slightly Smiling Face.

Google’s face previously evoked Lenny Face, Microsoft’s eyes appeared to be closed, Twitter’s resembled its üåö New Moon Face, and Facebook’s face was a simple, yellow smiley.

name: Funeral Urn
description:
An urn, as used to hold the cremated ashes of the dead. Appearance varies, but generally depicted as a covered, bronze container with a rounded body and tapered foot.

May be used for various content concerning death and funerals. May also be used for other types of vessels, such as pots or vases.

Not to be confused with üè∫ Amphora.

name: Game Die
description:
A six-sided die, used in a range of board and turn-based games. Commonly called dice which refers to the plural of die.

Most other platforms display this emoji as a single game die in white or red. LG showed two game dice in this emoji.

name: Garlic
description: A single white or light brown bulb of garlic. Can be used to talk about cooking, eating, or vampire protection.

name: Gear
description:
A round metal gear with teeth.

Used to talk about tools and engineering (both hardware and software). Also commonly used to indicate settings on user interfaces. May also represent hard work, e.g., grinding in sports.

Samsung’s design originally featured a white gear icon on a green square.

name: Gem Stone
description:
A jewel or gem, as set into a ring. Depicted in the shape of a classic diamond but in the bright blue color of an aquamarine.

Commonly used for various content concerning jewelry, as upon an engagement or marriage. May also convey various literal and figurative senses of beauty, wealth, sophistication, preciousness, and sparkling.

Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here.

name: Gemini
description: The Gemini astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents Twins.

name: Genie
description:
A supernatural being, which is generally shown to be imprisoned within a bottle or lamp. May be capable of granting wishes when summoned. Variations exist for a female genie or male genie.

Several vendors' design for this emoji is highly reminiscent of The Genie character from Disney's Aladdin films.

name: Ghost
description:
Boo! A white, cartoon ghost making a silly face. Its tongue is stuck out and arms are outstretched, as if trying to scare someone in a friendly way. Several platforms feature one larger, bulging eye, while others show the ghost winking.

Resembles a classic ghost costume for Halloween. May also be used to convey something or someone is fun or goofy. Thanks to its raised arms, some use this emoji as a way of expressing an excited Yay!

May also be used to refer to the slang term "ghosting", where a personal relationship is ended suddenly without explanation by one person withdrawing from all communication with another.

Samsung's design previously depicted this as a smiley in a ghost costume.

name: Ginger
description:
A segment of ginger root with light brown skin and a yellowish core.

Can be used to talk about ginger root or roots in general. Can also be used to talk about spice, flavor, cooking, or baking. May also be also be used to talk redheads.

name: Giraffe Face
description:
A giraffe, the tallest animal on Earth, with spots and a long neck. Generally depicted in yellow or tan in full profile on all fours facing left, with distinctive brown spots and small, horn-like structures.

Samsung’s designs feature a giraffe face looking straight ahead. Facebook’s design previously featured only a giraffe face, as did Microsoft's.

name: Girl
description:
The face of a girl, smiling. Most platforms feature the girl's hair in pigtails.

Variants include üë¶ Child and üë¶ Boy.

name: Glass of Milk
description: A tall glass of white milk, as from a cow but also other mammals, nuts, or plants. Most platforms depict a glass filled near to the brim, but some show a glass half-full—or half-empty.

name: Globe with Meridians
description:
A stylized globe, with blue meridians (longitudes) and latitude. Depicted with light-blue grid of lines on a white, blue, or empty circle.

May be used as a symbol of the internet or world wide web, global communications, international affairs, connectivity and networks, time zones, coordinates, or the world more generally.

May appear as an icon on Apple devices to change (language) keyboards.

See also üåé Globe Showing Americas, üåç Globe Showing Europe-Africa, and üåè Globe Showing Asia-Australia.

name: Gloves
description: A pair of knitted wool gloves, generally worn for warmth. The colors vary across different vendors.

name: Glowing Star
description:
A glowing, five-point gold star. Depicted as ‚≠ê Star with stylized bursts in between its points, representing glowing or twinkling.

Commonly used to represent various senses of glowing as well for as for a sense of flourish. Not to be confused with üí´ Dizzy, ‚≠ê Star, üå† Shooting Star, or ‚ú® Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.

On Snapchat, this emoji displays next to a contact who has had their snaps replayed in the past 24 hours.

Microsoft’s bursts were previously blue lines, Apple’s star previously resembled its ‚≠ê Star emoji, and Samsung’s star previously displayed a burst radiating out from its center.

name: Goal Net
description: A goal net where players score points in competitive sporting events. Generally depicted as a goal net used in either field hockey or ice hockey.

name: Goat
description:
A goat, a sturdy, hoofed animal raised for its meat and milk. Depicted as a light brown, white, or multicored goat in full profile on all fours facing left, a scraggly beard, upright tail, and brown or yellow horns curving back.

Frequently used as a visual shorthand for the slang expression GOAT, or the Great of All Time, often said of athletes and in particular the late Kobe Bryant.

Often considered one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Also often used to represent ‚ôë Capricorn in the Western zodiac.

Apple, Google, and Samsung’s goats were previously white, as a Saanen goat. Facebook’s design previously featured only a goat face.

name: Goggles
description: Clear safety goggles. When this emoji was approved in 2018 it was implied to be safety goggles rather than swimming goggles. A year later ü§ø Diving Mask, which is similar in design but used to represent swimming goggles rather than safety goggles, was approved.

name: Golfer
description: A person swinging a golf club, attempting to hit a golf ball toward the flag on the green.

name: Goose
description:
A white goose in full profile. 

Can be used to talk about the actual animal. Can also be used in the context of idioms including silly goose, wild goose chase, or what's good for the goose is good for the gander. Can also be used to talk about goosebumps or goose pimples. 

Might be used in reference to the children's game duck duck goose.

name: Gorilla
description:
A gorilla, the powerful, black-haired great ape. Variously depicted in full profile on all fours facing left or as a friendly, cartoon-styled gorilla face looking straight ahead.

Most platforms' designs depict a full gorilla, as a silverback, with strong shoulders and reddish forehead. Twitter’s designs feature a black and gray gorilla face with a neutral expression and prominent forehead and jaw.

Google, Samsung, and Facebook’s designs previously featured only a gorilla face.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Graduation Cap
description:
A graduation cap, worn on the head of students graduating from college or university. Known in some locations as a mortar board with tassel.

An early Apple design displayed a graduation shirt instead of a graduation cap.

name: Grapes
description:
A grape bunch, as cut from the vine and used to make wine. Depicted as red (purple-colored) grapes.

During 2024 this emoji began to be used on Tiktok to reference a phonetically similar term for a serious form of assault.

name: Green Apple
description: A common green apple, tarter counterpart to the Red Apple. Displayed with a stem and single, green leaf on major platforms.

name: Green Book
description:
A closed, green, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a green accent color.

Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 2 by John Appleseed. Samsung’s previously included the text Green Book.

name: Green Heart
description:
A green heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts. Frequently used on Twitter in reference to Korean boy band NCT.

Shown with beads of sweat on an orange and pink heart in previous versions of Android.

name: Green Salad
description:
An undressed garden salad in a bowl with leafy-green lettuce and other ingredients such as tomato, red onion, and black olives. Commonly associated with healthy eating and living.

Google previously displayed a hard-boiled egg, removed in 2018 to make the salad vegan-friendly.

name: Grey Heart
description: A grey heart, frequently used alongside other hearts. Used to represent love, friendship, feelings of warmth, and the color grey.

name: Grimacing Face
description:
A yellow face with simple open eyes showing clenched teeth. May represent a range of negative or tense emotions, especially nervousness, embarrassment, or awkwardness (e.g., Eek!).

Resembled üòÅ Beaming Face With Smiling Eyes on Apple iOS prior to 2016. Apple’s design for ü•∂ Cold Face features the same mouth. Samsung's design previously featured more puckered-looking lips. 

On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you send the most snaps to the same person that they do., i.e., you share a #1 Best Friend.

name: Grinning Cat Face with Smiling Eyes
description: A cartoon cat variant of üòÑ Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Grinning Face
description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth and tongue on some platforms. Often conveys general pleasure and good cheer or humor.

Not to be confused with üòÉ Grinning Face With Big Eyes or üòÑ Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes, which have the same smiles but more expressive eye shapes. 

This emoji has a cat variant, üò∫ Grinning Cat Face.

name: Grinning Face with One Large and One Small Eye
description:
A yellow face with its head tilted, its tongue hanging out of a big grin, and wide eyes in a wild, cockeyed expression. Generally used to express silliness.

Commonly represents acting goofy, having fun, and partying and is usually used in a positive manner. May be used in reference to someone or something that is off-kilter.

Microsoft, and WhatsApp previously displayed a full-toothed grin instead of an open mouth with a protruding tongue, which appeared less silly and more menacing. Google's design used to show the mouth in a grimace, which also read as more disturbing than silly.

name: Grinning Face with Smiling Eyes
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and full-toothed grin, as if saying Cheese! for the camera. Teeth may be smoothed-over or crosshatched. Often expresses a radiant, gratified happiness. Tone varies, including warm, silly, amused, or proud.

Prior to 2017, Apple's design resembled its üò¨ Grimacing Face.

name: Grinning Face with Star Eyes
description: A yellow face with a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth on most platforms, with stars for eyes, as if seeing a beloved celebrity. Color of stars widely varies by platform, though commonly gold or red. May express that someone or something is amazing, fascinating, impressive, or exciting.

name: Growing Heart
description:
A pink heart, inside a slightly larger pink heart, inside a larger-again pink heart. Intended to give the impression of a heart increasing in size.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity on Valentine's Day.

An early Apple design displayed as a plain Pink Heart.

name: Guardsman
description: A British guardsman, known as a foot guard. Wears a tall black hat with a yellow chin-strap. Must look straight ahead at all times, even when tourists attempt to distract them.

name: Guide Dog
description:
A guide (or Seeing Eye) dog, trained to help lead a person who is blind or visually impaired. Generally depicted as a yellowish-brown Labrador Retriever on all fours facing left, equipped with a harness and handle. Many platforms additionally include a collar.

Not to be confused with üêï‍ü¶∫ Service Dog, though their popular applications may overlap.

Twitter implements the same dog as its üêï Dog. Samsung and Twitter’s guide dogs have green harnesses.

name: Guitar
description:
A guitar, which most platforms display as a red electric guitar.

Discontinued emoji sets or such as LG and HTC displayed this as an acoustic guitar, as did previous version of Windows and Twemoji.

name: Hair Pick
description:
A hair pick with a handle and several long teeth. Used to style hair, especially thick, curly hair. May be used as a symbol of Black culture or Black pride. 

May also be used to talk about grooming or self-care in general.

May be used metaphorically to refer to the verb comb, meaning "to carefully search."

name: Haircut
description:
A person in the process of getting their hair cut, with scissors shown open next to the hair on their head.

While no gender is specified, many early designs displayed this emoji as a woman.

Windows previously displayed this emoji as a comb and scissors, instead of a person having their hair cut.

name: Hamburger
description:
A burger with a beef patty, usually depicted on a sesame bun with cheese, lettuce, and tomato—making it a cheeseburger, though officially called Hamburger by Unicode.

Platforms stack the ingredients in various orders. Google previously placed the cheese under the patty, a "controversy" CEO Sundar Pichai addressed in 2018.

name: Hammer
description:
A claw hammer, as used for driving or removing nails. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.

Commonly used for content concerning tools, building, and construction as well as various senses of breaking or smashing. May also represent hard work or be applied to hammer-related expressions, e.g., nailed it.

Apple and Facebook’s designs previously displayed a gavel, Softbank’s a mallet. Not to be confused with ‚õèÔ∏è Pick or ü™ì Axe.

name: Hammer and Pick
description:
A hammer and pick, as used for breaking up rocks in mining, crossed in an X shape. Generally depicted as metal, mallet- and chisel-styled hammers with wooden handles. The heads of the tools face up, with the pick usually at the right. Often used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction.

Facebook implements the same designs as for its üî® Hammer and ‚õèÔ∏è Pick. Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white tools on a green square, as a sign or icon of a mine.

name: Hammer and Wrench
description:
A hammer and wrench, as kept in a toolbox, crossed in an X shape. Depicted with metal tools facing up, the hammer positioned at the upper left. Most vendors implement the same design as for their üî® Hammer and üîß Wrench.

Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, construction, and work, both manual and digital.

name: Hamsa
description:
A blue hand with an eye in the center of the palm.

The hamsa is an ancient symbol important to multiple religions including Islam, Judaism, Buddhism, and Christianity. It represents luck, protection, guidance, feminine power, and faith, among other meanings.

name: Hamster Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a hamster—a small rodent often kept as a pet—looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a brown-and-white faced hamster with whiskers, a pink nose, puffy cheeks, and large, round, pink ears, sometimes with a buck tooth.

Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent a gerbil, guinea pig, chinchilla, or related animals. Does not have a full-bodied hamster emoji counterpart.

Not to be confused with üê≠ Mouse Face.

Microsoft’s hamster was previously gray.

name: Hand with Index Finger and Thumb Crossed
description:
A hand with the index finger and thumb crossed and the rest of the fingers making a fist. Can be used in various contexts to represent the fingers snapping, love, or money.

In this emoji, the index finger and the thumb form a small heart shape. This gesture, used to express love or affection, is known as a finger heart and was popularized in the 2010s by South Korean celebrities, including actors, K-pop stars, and comedians.

The same gesture may be used in the context of money to indicate a luxury or an expensive item, a lack of money, or a request to be paid.

name: Hand with Index and Middle Fingers Crossed
description:
A fingers crossed emoji which displays the index (first) finger crossed over the middle (second) finger. Commonly used as a gesture indicating luck, or to show desire of a favorable outcome.

This emoji was previously displayed with an additional finger on Samsung devices.

name: Handbag
description:
A bag or purse, used to carry personal items, often doubling as a fashion accessory.

The design of this emoji varies, with most platforms opting for leather-looking styles in brown or orange. Samsung’s design used to be pink, but is now light brown. Twitter’s purple design stands out among the other platforms.

Not to be confused with the smaller and handleless pouch emoji sometimes referred to as üëù Clutch Bag.

name: Handball
description: A person playing the sport of handball, shown jumping in the air about to throw the ball. Apple's design is shown wearing protective goggles.

name: Handshake
description:
Two hands performing a handshake gesture, indicating a cordial greeting between friends or associates.

As of late 2021's Emoji 14.0 recommendations, this emoji design has multiple skin tone modifier options. Certain platforms did, however, support a small number of single skin tone options for the handshake emoji prior to 2021 (e.g. both Google and Samsung in 2017). View all handshake emojis.

name: Happy Person Raising One Hand
description:
A person with its hand in the air, as if it wants to ask or answer a question.

Generally displayed as a woman, but is not defined as one particular gender. Previously showed a blob-like gender-inclusive character in the Google artwork.

name: Hatching Chick
description:
A baby chicken (chick), hatching from an egg and seeing the world for the first time. Depicted as a yellow chick with an orange beak facing forward in the cracked, bottom half of a white egg, generally shown flapping its wings with a cute facial expression.

Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry, eggs), spring, Easter, or slang senses of chick.

Not to be confused with üê§ Baby Chick or üê•Front-Facing Baby Chick (out of its egg), though their applications overlap. See also üêî Chicken and üêì Rooster.

Twitter and Facebook's designs do not include wings. Google's design previously featured motion lines around the chick's wings, indicating flapping. Facebook's design previously showed part of the egg atop the chick's head.

name: Headphone
description:
Headphones, used to listen to music or other forms audio, such as podcasts. Most platforms display this emoji with large over-ear headphones in shades of black, blue, and gray.

Apple previously displayed this emoji as iconic iPod white earbuds, followed by black Beats headphones in 2016, and in 2021 switched to display white AirPods Max.

name: Headstone
description:
A headstone or tombstone, used to mark graves. Appearance varies from platform to platform, with different shapes and inscriptions.

Used to talk about death — literally, metaphorically, and metaphysically.

Often paired with other death-related emoji like ‚ö∞Ô∏è Coffin and ‚ò†Ô∏è Skull and Crossbones.

name: Health Worker
description: A person working in the field of health care. This may be used to represent a doctor, nurse, or pharmacist.

name: Hear-No-Evil Monkey
description:
The hear no evil monkey, called Kikazaru (Japanese for “hear not”), one of the Three Wise Monkeys. Depicted as the brown üêµ Monkey Face with hands covering its ears.

The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil, frequently interpreted as a call for discretion or willful ignorance.

Often used as a playful way to convey I can’t believe what I’m hearing! or, more generally, to express astonishment or disbelief.

See also üôà See-No-Evil Monkey and üôä Speak-No-Evil Monkey.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Heart Decoration
description:
A decorative heart that generally displays as a white heart-shaped cutout in a pink or purple roundrect.

Google previously displayed a pink heart with yellow dots around it, Samsung’s was a pink patterned heart, and Microsoft’s had corner stitches.

name: Heart Hands
description:
Two hands forming a heart shape. Used to express love and support.

This emoji currently showns the heart being made through two hands being curved into a C-shape with their thumbs touching. This is stereotypically referred to as the "Millennial Hand Heart".

name: Heart on Fire
description: A heart shown on fire, for extreme or passionate forms of love or lust. Most representative of desire or lust, this emoji may also indicate a sense of burning a past love and moving on.

name: Heart with Arrow
description:
A heart emoji with an arrow through the center, like the arrow that cupid shoots for love.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity on Valentine's Day.

name: Heart with Ribbon
description: A heart-shaped box, tied with a ribbon. May be a gift box, box of chocolates, or a jewellery box.

name: Heavy Black Heart
description:
A classic red love heart emoji.

The red heart ideograph is traditionally used for expressions of love and romance across many cultures, with this being amongst the most frequence use cases for this emoji.

However, the Red Heart emoji is also often used to express non-romantic positive sentiments, in part thanks to its use as one of the default reaction emoji options across many social messaging platforms (e.g. Instagram, Slack, WhatsApp).

This is historically the most popular heart emoji by a considerable distance and is amongst the most popular emojis of all time. 

A similar emoji exists for the heart suit in a deck of playing cards.

On Snapchat, this emoji displays next to a friend when you have been #1 BFs with each other for two consecutive weeks.

Note: the Unicode Character Database (UCD) name “Heavy Black Heart” pre-dates color emoji, when the term referred to a solid, black ‚ù§Ô∏é heart character. See the glossary for information on the term black in historic Unicode character names.

name: Heavy Division Sign
description: A large division symbol, as used in mathematics.

name: Heavy Dollar Sign
description: A large dollar sign ($), which can be used to represent various international currencies. Generally depicted in either black or green.

name: Heavy Equals Sign
description: An equals sign in the style of the already existing set of mathematical symbols ‚úñÔ∏è Multiply, ‚ûï Plus, ‚ûñ Minus, and ‚ûó Divide.

name: Heavy Exclamation Mark Symbol
description: A large red exclamation mark (!) symbol emoji.

name: Heavy Heart Exclamation Mark Ornament
description: A decorative exclamation mark, where a heart forms the top part of the symbol, and a circle the lower part. Similar to the way to the man in business suit levitating also creates a similar shape.

name: Heavy Large Circle
description: Used as an alternative to a check (tick) in Japan for a something that is correct. The opposite of an X (cross mark) for something wrong.

name: Heavy Minus Sign
description: A large minus symbol, as used in mathematics.

name: Heavy Plus Sign
description: A large plus / addition symbol, as used in mathematics.

name: Hedgehog
description:
A hedgehog. A small, spiny mammal sometimes kept as a pet. Generally depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a round, brown body covered with spines and a light-brown face and underside.

Sometimes used to represent a porcupine or echidna.

Twitter's design has always been a hedgehog facing forward. Google's design originally featured a hedgehog facing forward, though it was changed to full profile with Android 11.0. Facebook’s design previously featured a hedgehog on its back, rolled up in a ball.

name: Helicopter
description: A helicopter, which can hover in the air. Often seen in emergency circumstances such as transporting patients to a hospital, or for police or fire-fighting activity.

name: Helmet with White Cross
description:
A construction helmet, which is worn by the construction worker emoji in some emoji sets.

The cross on the helmet (shown in the Apple version of this emoji) is used in Japan as a safety reminder in construction zones. It is also commonly seen on the Met helmet in the game Mega Man.

name: Herb
description:
An herb, a plant used in cooking or medicine. Depicted as a green sprig, as of basil, sage, or oregano, generally with five or seven leaves.

May be used for various content concerning cooking, herbal medicine, and plant life more generally. Occasionally used as slang for marijuana.

Not to be confused with üå± Seedling, though their applications may overlap.

name: Hibiscus
description:
A pink hibiscus, a flower that grows in warm climates. Depicted as a single, deep-pink hibiscus flower with green leaves and prominent, yellow stamen.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a pink accent color and in association with Hawaii and other Polynesian places and cultures.

Google and Samsung's hibiscus flowers were previously orange.

name: High Brightness Symbol
description: An icon of a outlined sun, used when increasing¬†the brightness of a screen. Appears larger than the¬†Low Brightness Symbol.

name: High Voltage Sign
description:
A symbol for high voltage, as warns against injury from electricity. Depicted as a jagged yellow bolt.

Commonly used to represent lightning, electricity, and various flashes. Also used to represent metaphorical energy and signal attention online.

Samsung’s bolt was previously white on a blue square, as an icon for high voltage.

name: High-Heeled Shoe
description:
A high-heeled shoe, primarily worn by women. Generally found in a context which requires formal dress, such as social occasions, or some work places.

Displayed in red on most platforms, though the color may vary.

name: High-Speed Train
description: A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed.

name: High-Speed Train with Bullet Nose
description: A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed. Also features a streamlined bullet nose, often used in reference to the Shinkansen in Japan.

name: Hiking Boot
description: A style of boot commonly worn on long walks or for hiking. Generally distinct from other footwear-related emojis by the considerable grip on the sole of the shoe.

name: Hindu Temple
description: A Hindu temple or mandir; a place of worship for followers of Hinduism. Depicted on most platforms as a red, orange, or golden building with a tall spire.

name: Hippopotamus
description:
A hippopotamus, a squat water mammal with huge jaws. Generally depicted in gray or tan in full profile facing left.

Google’s design used to feature a purple, cartoon-styled hippopotamus face. Facebook’s hippopotamus is opening massive jaws, revealing tusks.

name: Hocho
description:
A knife with a long steel blade, as a chef uses to slice meat or vegetables. Depicted with a black or brown handle and positioned at a 45° angle, often with its point at the lower right.

May be used for content concerning cooking and food preparation, but often represents various senses of cutting and stabbing. Its Unicode name, Hocho, means “kitchen knife” in Japanese and refers to a variety of knives used in Japan.

Not to be confused with üó°Ô∏è Dagger or ‚öîÔ∏è Crossed Swords.

name: Hole
description: A round, black, cartoon-styled hole, as a manhole or a hole (cup) in golf. May be used to represent various types of literal or figurative holes, e.g., black holes, rabbit holes.

name: Honey Pot
description:
A golden-yellow pot of honey, as made by bees and desired by bears. Shown with the sweet substance oozing down its sides, often with a honey dipper inside the small vessel. 

May be used figuratively, as the term of endearment “honey.”

name: Honeybee
description:
A honey bee, a busy, flying insect that lives in a hive and makes honey. Depicted as a black-and-yellow bee with clear or white wings and a stinger. Variously facing left in full profile or shown from above.

May be used to represent various types of bees (e.g., bumblebee) and wasps (e.g., hornets, yellow jackets). May also be used to accent black-and-yellow colors or patterns. Popularly used in connection with singer and superstar Beyoncé (nicknamed Queen Bey) or for metaphorical queen bees. Can also be used to refer to the city of Manchester in the United Kingdom, as the worker bee is the symbol of the city.

name: Hook
description:
A gold or silver hook. Can be used to represent literal hooks like the kinds you use to crochet or catch fish.

Also use metaphorically to talk about boxing or punching, music (the catchy part of a song), or in phrases like hook me up, hook up, getting hooked (on something), or hook, line, and sinker.

name: Horizontal Traffic Light
description:
A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. Less¬†common than the¬†vertical¬†traffic light.
Similar in appearance to the¬†traffic light controls in the upper-left of every OS X windows.

name: Horse
description:
A horse, a hoofed mammal used for riding and racing. Depicted as a brown horse in full profile galloping to the left, with a dark, flowing mane and tail.

May be used to represent various types of horses and their metaphorical senses (e.g., mustang, stallion).

May also be used as a compliment to an attractive person.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.a

Not to be confused with üê¥ Horse Face, üé† Carousel Horse, and üèá Horse Racing, which features a jockey on its back.

Apple’s horse is wearing a green saddle blanket, Facebook’s a blue blanket with saddle. SoftBank’s design previously featured a racing horse with a jockey.

name: Horse Face
description:
The face of a horse, generally facing left. Depicted as a light or reddish-brown horse with a dark brown or black mane, and, on many platforms, a light-colored muzzle.

Not to be confused with the full-bodied üêé Horse or üèá Horse Racing, though their applications may overlap. Some vendors implement a similar design in ü¶Ñ Unicorn Face and ü¶ì Zebra.

WhatsApp’s horse is facing left, as Facebook’s previously was. Microsoft’s horse was previously looking straight ahead, as was Samsung’s, shown with a goofy, full-toothed grin. Softbank previously featured a full-bodied horse.

name: Horse Racing
description: A jockey riding a horse in a horse race. Shown riding to the left of screen on all major platforms. Emoji modifiers change the skin tone of the jockey on some platforms, which can be difficult to discern at small sizes.

name: Hospital
description: A place where people are taken to receive medical care. This hospital has a large red cross on the front, often used as a symbol for health care.

name: Hot Beverage
description:
A cup of a steaming-hot beverage, usually taken as coffee or tea. Sometimes shown on a saucer.

Samsung's design previously featured a foamy-white tulip latte art design.

May be paired with the Frog Face to represent the snarky But That's None of My Business meme. Relatedly, can also be used alone to represent "tea" as per the slang phrase "spill the tea", used to request the sharing of gossip, news, or personal information. More recently, it can also be used to refer to a person's physical attractiveness, as per the slang phrase "your body is tea."

name: Hot Dog
description: The cooked sausage of a hot dog in a sliced bun and drizzled with yellow mustard, as eaten at a baseball game.

name: Hot Pepper
description: A bright red Mexican chili pepper, slightly curled and with a green stem. May be used to represent something “hot and spicy,” figuratively or literally, as a dish on a restaurant menu.

name: Hot Springs
description: Representation of hot springs with steam rising from a circular tub. This is the common symbol used to represent an onsen on maps in Japan.

name: Hotel
description:
A hotel building, displayed on most platforms as a building with many windows and a letter H on the front.

Can be easily confused with the Love Hotel, or Hospital emoji. Microsoft previously depicted this emoji as a bed.

name: Hourglass
description:
A classic hourglass, all of its sand having flowed into the bottom bulb. Indicates time has passed. Color varies across platforms.

Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with ‚è≥ Hourglass Not Done, whose sand is still flowing.

Used on Snapchat to indicate a Snapstreak is soon to end.

name: Hourglass with Flowing Sand
description:
A classic hourglass, its sand still flowing from the top to bottom bulb. Indicates time is still passing—but life is short. Color varies across platforms.

Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with ‚åõ Hourglass Done, whose sand has stopped flowing.

name: House Building
description:
A house, otherwise known as a home when someone is living in it. Suitable for a couple or larger family, other perhaps housemates.

Distinct from an apartment building due to its detached form, this house is likely in the suburbs of a city or a rural area.

name: House Buildings
description: Multiple houses.

name: House with Garden
description: A suburban-looking house, with a tree, flower, or shrubs around it in the garden.

name: Hugging Face
description:
A yellow face smiling with open hands, as if giving a hug. May be used to offer thanks and support, show love and care, or express warm, positive feelings more generally.

Due to its hand gesture, often used to represent jazz hands, indicating such feelings as excitement, enthusiasm, or a sense of flourish or accomplishment.

Joins ü§î Thinking Face, ü§´ Shushing Face, and ü§≠ Face With Hand Over Mouth as one of the few smileys featuring hands. For a more obvious hug, see ü´Ç People Hugging (new in 2020).

name: Hundred Points Symbol
description:
100 emoji: the number one-hundred, written in red, underlined twice for emphasis.

Originating from the number 100 written on a school exam or paper to indicate a perfect score of 100 out of 100.  Teachers in Japan may also use a stamp in addition to the 100 mark, to indicate that a student has performed very well.

This 100 emoji is commonly used as a shorthand for 100%, with the usage meaning “keep it real” or a similar sentiment. A 100 emoji can be used to express pride or general acceptance of an idea.

In Snapchat, the 100 emoji appearing next to a fire emoji indicates a 100 day Snapstreak.

name: Hushed Face
description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes, raised eyebrows, and a small, open mouth, as if it has been hushed by concern or correction. Meaning widely varies, but its expression is commonly taken as surprise, embarrassment, or mild excitement.

Similar to üò≤ Astonished Face, which features larger eyes and mouth. Google previously interpreted hushed as "silenced," depicting the emoji with a zipper mouth until Android 6.0.1. An early Microsoft design featured a face with closed eyes and a flat, closed mouth.

name: Hut
description: A round hut with a thatched roof. Used to talk about huts, cottages, yurts, or homes in general.

name: Hyacinth
description:
A hyacinth with purple blossoms and a green stem.

Can be used to talk about the actual flower, flowers in general, or the color purple. Can also be used in reference to springtime. May be used as part of the symbolic table setting for Nowruz, the Persian New Year.

name: I Love You Hand Sign
description: The gesture for “I love you” in American Sign Language, shown as a raised pinky (little) finger, index finger, and an extended thumb.

name: Ice Cream
description: One or more scoops of ice cream in a dessert bowl, variously topped with sprinkles, wafer rolls, or cherry and syrup. Flavors vary from vanilla, chocolate, and/or strawberry across platforms.

name: Ice Cube
description: A blue cube of ice. Can be used to talk about ice or cold temperatures in general. This emoji can also be used metaphorically to talk about something that is cool or chill.

name: Ice Hockey Stick and Puck
description: A hockey stick and puck, used in the sport of ice hockey. Not to be confused with the field hockey stick and ball.

name: Ice Skate
description:
A single ice skate used for ice skating. Shown in white and facing right on most platforms.

In the sport of figure skating, a white ice skate is traditionally worn by women, and a black ice skate worn by men. This emoji doesn't define the color to be used, but no major vendor currently displays this as black.

name: Identification Card
description: An identification card with a portrait and words. May be used to remind people to bring or show an id. May also be used in the context of a fake id.

name: Imp
description:
A face, usually purple, with two devil horns, frowning mouth and eyes, and eyebrows scrunched downwards in anger. Bears the same expression as üò† Angry Face and üò° Pouting Face on most platforms. Google’s design is red and Facebook’s has black horns, green eyes, and clenched teeth.

Its Unicode name, Imp, alludes to a small demon in folklore, though the smiley is commonly used to represent devils and devilish behavior, especially around Halloween. It is also used to convey various sentiments of anger or ideas of evil. More menacing than its counterpart, üòà Smiling Face With Horns.

Samsung previously depicted a childlike character with red hair and horns, fangs, and black wings. Earlier designs from Google featured an orangish-red character with blue hair and wings.

name: Inbox Tray
description:
A paper tray with a down arrow on top, as a symbol for an email inbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden try with a red arrow. Samsung and Twitter's arrows are green, WhatsApp's gray.

May be used for various digital activity, including downloading, messaging, and emailing.

Facebook's design contains paper, as did an earlier Google design. 

See also üì§ Outbox Tray.

name: Incoming Envelope
description:
The back of an envelope, shown coming into an inbox or arriving with motion lines.

Commonly used as an icon for an email address. May also represent posting mail or sending messages more generally.

Apple and WhatsApp’s designs include an inbox tray. Facebook’s designs feature a yellow envelope angled forward and trailed by three, blue lines, indicating sending. Google's design also previously displayed as a yellow envelope.

Apple’s design previously featured three red motion lines, Microsoft’s a rightwards arrow.

name: Index Pointing at the Viewer
description:
A hand with the index finger pointing straight forward at the person viewing the emoji. Used to represent the word and concept of 'you,' the second-person singular and plural pronoun.

This symbol is seen in art, advertisements, and military recruitment posters as a way to draw the viewer into the image they're looking at.

This hand shape is also used in multiple sign languages from around the world.

name: Information Desk Person
description:
A person tipping their hand by their shoulder as if they’re carrying a tray of drinks or flipping their hair. Originally called Information Desk Person.

This emoji is commonly used to express sassiness or sarcasm.

While no gender is specified, many early designs displayed this emoji as a woman. Google’s 2014 design shows a blob wearing white gloves and a pillbox hat. Microsoft’s 2015 design shows a woman doing this gesture while winking, a facial expression that further reinforces the sassy and sarcastic uses of this emoji.

name: Information Source
description:
A lowercase letter i, enclosed in a rounded square or circle. Implemented in apps or websites to indicate that help or further information is available.

May be used as a logo for tourist information signage in a town or city.

name: Input Symbol for Latin Capital Letters
description: A symbol showing the capital letters A, B, C and D. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle capital letter input.

name: Input Symbol for Latin Letters
description: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable alphabetical input, as opposed to numeric or symbol input.

name: Input Symbol for Latin Small Letters
description: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen¬†to¬†toggle lowercase¬†letter input.

name: Input Symbol for Numbers
description: A symbol showing the numbers 1, 2, 3 and 4. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable numeric input, as opposed to alphabetical or symbol input.

name: Input Symbol for Symbols
description:
A symbol showing the following¬†glyphs:¬†„Äí (Japanese postal mark), ùÖòùÖ•ùÖÆ (music note), & (ampersand, or sometimes an @ symbol)¬†and % (percentage sign).
Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable symbol¬†input, as opposed to¬†alphabetical¬†or¬†numeric¬†input.

name: Izakaya Lantern
description:
A red paper lantern, as hangs outside an izakaya, a Japanese bar that serves drinks and casual food. Generally depicted as cylindrical with a black top and base and soft, orange glow.

May be used to represent various lights and lanterns as well as for its red color.

name: Jack-O-Lantern
description: An orange pumpkin carved into the shape of a face and commonly known as a Jack-o’-lantern. See also Halloween.

name: Japanese Castle
description: A traditional Japanese Castle (Âüé, shiro or j≈ç), usually made from stone and wood.

name: Japanese Dolls
description:
Ornamental Japanese Emperor and Empress dolls, as displayed in celebration of Hinamatsuri on March 3 in Japan (Girls’ or Dolls’ Day).

Generally depicted as a Japanese Emperor (left, in blue, holding a scepter) and Empress (right, in red, holding a fan) in ceremonial court dress and seated on a tatami.

When not applied to Hinamatsuri, sometimes used to represent Japan, dolls, a pair of people (as a couple or two friends), and for various idiosyncratic purposes.

name: Japanese Goblin
description:
A menacing, red mask featuring a grotesquely long nose, angry eyes, and bushy eyebrows and mustache. Depicts a tengu, a proud trickster figure in Japanese folklore.

May popularly denote evil, anger, cruel or mischievous behavior, and sexual suggestion, due to the phallic appearance of its nose. May also represent supernatural or figurative trolls, goblins, and other such beings.

name: Japanese Ogre
description:
A grotesque, red face with horns, wide eyes, a large nose, crooked fangs, and a fringe of shaggy hair. Depicts an oni, a kind of hideous ogre in Japanese folklore.

On New Year’s Eve in some parts of Japan, men may wear oni masks and straw coats to dress up as namahage, another mythic being, to chide naughty children or ward off evil. May popularly denote supernatural or figurative beasts and demons.

name: Japanese Post Office
description:
A Japanese post office, featuring the „Äí Japanese postal mark on the front of the building.

Microsoft's design previously displayed this mark on its own instead of being featured on the building.

name: Japanese Symbol for Beginner
description:
A yellow and green shield symbol, called a Shoshinsha Mark. Must be displayed by drivers in Japan for one year after they receive their drivers licence.

Similar to L-Plates used to identify learner drivers in other countries.

name: Jar
description:
An empty glass jar.

May be used to talk about jars or anything that comes in jars, from pickles to condiments to jellies to sauces.

name: Jeans
description: Denim jeans, worn by men or women. A popular form of casual trousers worn by the runner emoji in Apple's emoji artwork

name: Jellyfish
description: A brightly colored jellyfish with a domed bell and dangling tentacles.

name: Jigsaw Puzzle Piece
description:
A single piece of a jigsaw puzzle, shown with two tabs and two blanks.

Usually shown as a plain green puzzle piece, though color and imagery does vary.

name: Joystick
description:
A joystick, as used in playing classic arcade, computer, or video games. Generally depicted with a black base, red-knobbed control stick, and one or more red buttons.

Commonly used for content concerning various types of gaming; occasionaly applied to aviation and aircraft.

Google's base was previously blue, and Microsoft previously featured a more modern design.

name: Judge
description: A person who presides over court proceedings, wearing the traditional black gown and wielding a gavel.

name: Juggling
description:
A person juggling between three and five colored balls. The person shown in this emoji wears a hat on most major platforms.

Early Twitter and Facebook designs previously displayed this emoji as a pair of disembodied hands juggling three colored balls.

name: Kaaba
description: A cube-shaped building located at the centre of the Al-Masjid al-Haram Mosque in Mecca.

name: Kangaroo
description:
A kangaroo, a marsupial with a large tail and legs. Depicted in yellowish-brown in full profile facing left with large, pointed ears, shown either resting on its hind legs and tail or jumping.

Commonly used in connection with Australia, where the animal is found.

name: Key
description:
A key, as opens a door or lock. Depicted at a 45° angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of key, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial").

DJ Khaled uses the emoji to indicate his Snapchat stories are official (verified). Apple’s design previously resembled a gold üóùÔ∏è Old Key, which emoji has similar applications.

May also represent digital keys in public-key technology. This may explain why the emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

name: Keyboard
description:
A keyboard, as used to type on a computer. Generally depicted as a gray device with white or black keys. Used for various content concerning computers, typing, and writing.

Apple’s design resembles the company’s Magic Keyboard. Microsoft's design was previously blue.

Not to be confused with üéπ Musical Keyboard.

name: Keycap Asterisk
description: The asterisk symbol (*) on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Eight
description: The number 8 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Five
description: The number 5 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Four
description: The number 4 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Nine
description: The number 9 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit One
description: The number 1 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Seven
description: The number 7 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Six
description: The number 6 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Three
description: The number 3 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Two
description: The number 2 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Digit Zero
description: The number 0 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Keycap Number Sign
description: A hash key, sometimes referred to as a pound key in the United States. Most commonly used online to make a hashtag (or hash flag) on social media sites.

name: Keycap Ten
description: The number 10 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

name: Khanda
description: The Khanda, the symbol of the Sikhism.

name: Kimono
description: A traditional Japanese robe that can be worn by women or men.

name: Kiss
description:
A kissing gesture, shown with a pink love heart floating in the air between two people. No gender is specified for the two people, and as such this may be used to represent the concept of a couple broadly, and/or as a means of showing two non-binary people.

Previously shown with the same appearance as üë©‍‚ù§Ô∏è‍üíã‍üë® Kiss: Woman, Man, but now displays two people with an ambiguous gender appearance.

name: Kiss Mark
description: The mark left after a firm kiss is placed with bright lipstick. Used in place of ‘xxx’ (kisses), or to send a kiss to someone. More seductive than the kiss emoji.

name: Kiss: Man, Man
description: Two men displayed kissing, or gesturing a kiss toward each other. At small sizes this may be difficult to discern from the two women kissing.

name: Kiss: Woman, Man
description: A woman and a man displayed kissing, or gesturing a kiss toward each other.

name: Kiss: Woman, Woman
description: Two women displayed kissing, or gesturing a kiss toward each other. At small sizes this may be difficult to discern from two men kissing.

name: Kissing Cat Face with Closed Eyes
description: A cartoon cat variant of üòö Kissing Face With Closed Eyes. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Kissing Face
description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and puckered lips giving a kiss. Commonly conveys sentiments of love and affection.

Like üòô Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes, this emoji is sometimes taken to represent whistling, especially when paired with a musical note. May convey such feelings as surprise, admiration, contempt, or feigned innocence, as a person casually whistling after wrongdoing saying, Nothing to look at here.

Similar to üòô Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes and üòö Kissing Face With Closed Eyes but with less intimate eyes.

name: Kissing Face with Closed Eyes
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes, rosy cheeks, and puckered lips giving a kiss. Commonly conveys sentiments of romantic love and affection. Several platforms, including Apple, feature the same eyes and cheeks as their ‚ò∫Ô∏è Smiling Face.

With its closed eyes, features an expression more intimate than üòô Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes’s and üòó Kissing Face’s.

This emoji has a cat variant, üòΩ Kissing Cat Face.

name: Kissing Face with Smiling Eyes
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and puckered lips giving a kiss. Commonly conveys sentiments of love and affection.

Like üòó Kissing Face, this emoji is sometimes taken to represent whistling, especially when paired with a musical note. May convey such feelings as surprise, admiration, contempt, or feigned innocence, as a person with hands in pocket casually whistling after wrongdoing, as if saying Nothing to look at here.

With its smiling eyes, this emoji generally features an expression fonder than üòó Kissing Face's but less intimate than üòö Kissing Face With Closed Eyes's. Expect for on Huawei devices, where this emoji's lips are plump and red like the üíã Kiss Mark emoji.

name: Kite
description:
A kite. Usually diamond-shaped with a tail, this emoji appears in various colors across platforms.

Unlike other vendors, Huawei's design is shaped like a bird of prey.

name: Kiwifruit
description:
A kiwifruit, or Chinese gooseberry, with its fuzzy, brown skin sliced open to show its light-green flesh, white core, and black seeds. 

May be associated with New Zealand, whose residents are nicknamed Kiwis, after the bird.

name: Kneeling Person
description: A person kneeling down on one or both knees. May be used to represent someone in prayer, or a person resting on the floor.

name: Knot
description:
Brightly colored rope forming a knot. Knot type varies across platform, with most designs showing a square knot, a figure eight knot, or a carrick bend. Samsung's design appears to be a carrick bend, but upon closer inspection, it is not correctly tied and would fall apart with a gentle tug. 

Used to talk about rope or knots in general. Sometimes used in the context of marriage alongside the idiom tying the knot. Also used in the kink community to talk about bondage. May be used as a stand-in for the word 'not' in emoji rebus puzzles.

name: Koala
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a koala—a bear-like marsupial known for eating eucalyptus and sleeping—looking straight ahead. Depicted as a gray face with round, fluffy ears and a large, black nose.

Often used with an affectionate tone and in association with Australia, where the animal is found.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Google previously depicted a full-bodied koala climbing a tree, Softbank’s koala previously had brown fur.

name: Lab Coat
description: A white coat worn in a science laboratory.

name: Label
description:
A light-brown or yellow rectangular tag, as labelled and attached to a key. Depicted at various angles punched with a hole, generally with a metal ring or loop of string.

Commonly used to represent a price tag or metadata tag as well as for various senses of label.

WhatsApp's is white. Apple removed its ring from earlier designs. Samsung previously featured the easter egg initials HMJ, while Google's design previously featured two tags.

name: Lacrosse Stick and Ball
description: A stick and ball used in the sport of lacrosse. The ball is usually depicted as either orange or white, while the stick's color varies across emoji designs.

name: Ladder
description:
A wooden ladder with four or five rungs.

Used to represent ladders or the action of climbing. Also used metaphorically to represent systems through which you can climb, for example the corporate ladder or social ladder.

name: Lady Beetle
description:
A ladybug (ladybird, lady beetle), a beetle with a round, red shell with black spots. Generally depicted as a seven- or nine-spotted ladybug shown from above on its six legs, with antennae and its distinctively red-and-black, halved shell.

May be used a symbol of good luck.

Facebook’s ladybug is shown on its legs facing forward.

name: Large Blue Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of blue. May be used to represent anything blue.

name: Large Blue Diamond
description:
A large version of the small blue diamond emoji.

Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here.

name: Large Blue Square
description: A square shown in the color of blue. May be used to represent anything blue.

name: Large Brown Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of brown. May be used to represent anything brown.

name: Large Brown Square
description: A square shown in the color of brown. May be used to represent anything brown.

name: Large Green Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of green. May be used to represent anything green.

name: Large Green Square
description:
A square shown in the color of green. May be used to represent anything green.

May 2021: Sometimes shown in Twitter names in support of Taproot, a Bitcoin fork (potential feature change) that would allow additional privacy measures for transactions.

name: Large Orange Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of orange. May be used to represent anything orange.

name: Large Orange Diamond
description: A larger version of the small orange diamond emoji.

name: Large Orange Square
description: A square shown in the color of orange. May be used to represent anything orange.

name: Large Purple Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of purple. May be used to represent anything purple.

name: Large Purple Square
description: A square shown in the color of purple. May be used to represent anything purple.

name: Large Red Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of red. May be used to represent anything red.

name: Large Red Square
description: A square shown in the color red. May be used to represent anything red, including a red penalty card in football (soccer).

name: Large Yellow Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of yellow. May be used to represent anything yellow.

name: Large Yellow Square
description: A square shown in the color yellow. May be used to represent anything yellow, including a yellow penalty card in football (soccer).

name: Last Quarter Moon Symbol
description:
A last quarter moon, the seventh of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its left side half illuminated in gold or silver, its remainder dark.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.

See also üåú Last Quarter Moon Face. Not to be confused with üåì First Quarter Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a last quarter moon in a night sky with stars.

name: Last Quarter Moon with Face
description:
A last quarter moon with a human face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts a wide, golden crescent moon with the profile of slightly smiling human face with a nose, facing right.

May be used to represent the moon more generally and saying good night.

See also üåó Last Quarter Moon and üåô Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with üåõ First Quarter Moon Face, though their applications may overlap.

WhatsApp’s eyes are looking back. Facebook’s moon is silver but was previously golden; Twitter’s was previously silver. Google’s eyes were previously closed.

name: Latin Cross
description: A latin cross, otherwise known as a Christian cross. This cross symbol is often used as a symbol of Christianity. Similar in appearance to the Orthodox cross.

name: Leaf Fluttering in Wind
description:
Leaves, as fluttering in a spring or summer breeze. Depicted as one or two green, almond-shaped leaves, with gray or blue motion lines, as if swirling in the air or as the wind blowing through the trees.

May be used to represent the season of fall/autumn, trees, and nature more generally.

Not to be confused with üçÇ Fallen Leaf, though their applications may overlap.

name: Leafy Green
description: A head of a rich green leaf vegetable, usually shown with white stalks. May be used to represent a variety of greens, including romaine lettuce, chard, and Chinese cabbage like bok choy, as commonly cooked in Asian cuisines.

name: Ledger
description:
A spiral-bound, yellow, hardcover notebook. Intended to depict a financial ledger, as used in accounting.

Commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, reading, and schooling. May also be used as a yellow accent color.

Google and Samsung’s designs were previously blue.

name: Left Luggage
description:
An icon representing a place to leave luggage. Most commonly found at Japanese train stations to signify coin lockers where bags can be stored for a daily fee.

This emoji displays a suitcase with a key above or below it, ususually in blue.

name: Left Right Arrow
description: A horizontal line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing left and right.

name: Left Speech Bubble
description: A left-facing speech bubble, which was included in Unicode 7.0, but not considered a standard addition for the purposes of emoji presentation.

name: Left-Facing Fist
description: A fist pointing left, which may be used in conjunction with the right-facing fist to complete a fist-bump gesture.

name: Left-Pointing Magnifying Glass
description:
A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed left. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper left.

Associated with detectives and search or zoom icons on computers. Like üîé Magnifying Glass Titled Right, commonly used for various senses of searching, looking, inspecting, etc.

name: Leftwards Arrow with Hook
description: An arrow pointing to the left, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a reply icon in an email application.

name: Leftwards Black Arrow
description:
An arrow, pointing left.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Leftwards Hand
description:
An open right hand facing left, so as to show the palm of the hand with the thumb on the top and the pinky on the bottom.

This emoji was developed along with ü´± Rightwards Hand to allow for the creation of ZWJ Sequences that depict ü§ù Handshake with two different skin tone modifiers applied, one to each hand.

name: Leftwards Pushing Hand
description:
A profile of an open hand pushing or positioned with the palm toward the left. 

May be used to show a hand pushing something away or to represent rejection of something in general. May also be used with with ü´∏ Rightwards Pushing Hand to show hands high fiving or holding, pressing, or squishing something.

name: Leg
description: A human leg, shown detached from a human body. Displayed from the thigh and may include the foot.

name: Lemon
description:
The sour, yellow-colored citrus fruit of the lemon, usually with a stem and green leaf or leaves.

Spiked in use thanks to Beyoncé’s 2016 album, Lemonade.

name: Leo
description: The Leo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Lion.

name: Leopard
description:
A leopard, a large cat with a yellowish-brown coat and black-and-gold spots. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long tail and its distinctive pattern.

Sometimes used to represent jaguars, panthers, cheetahs, and related cats. May also be used to indicate leopard prints in fashion. Not to be confused with üêÖ Tiger.

Google’s design is noticeably more cartoon-styled. Microsoft’s design was previously solid yellowish-brown in color, resembling a cougar or mountain lion.

name: Level Slider
description:
A level slider, as adjusts volume on a mixing console. Most platforms depict a silver and black channel fader with scale markings, set to various levels. Apple and Google's go up to eleven.

Commonly used for various content concerning audio recording and production as well as music more generally. May also be used for figurative senses of level, e.g., next level.

Thanks to its appearance, some may use the emoji to represent a Christian cross.

name: Libra
description: The Libra astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents weighing scales.

name: Light Blue Heart
description: A light blue heart, frequently used alongside other hearts. Used to represent love, friendship, feelings of warmth, and the color blue.

name: Light Rail
description:
A form of public transport similar to a tram, but running on a track or network separated from cars and other types of traffic.

Difficult to discern from a train at small sizes.

name: Link Symbol
description:
Two links of a silver chain, positioned at a 45° angle. Used as an icon for a hyperlink on computers and the internet. May also be used for metaphorical connections.

Not to be confused with ‚õìÔ∏èChains, üìé Paperclip, üñáÔ∏è Linked Paperclips, or üß∑ Safety Pin.

name: Linked Paperclips
description:
Two or more silver paper clips linked together, generally forming an inverted V. Microsoft’s design displays three paper clips.

Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies or metaphorical connections. Also sometimes used as an icon before a hyperlink.

Not to be confused with üîó Link or ‚õìÔ∏è Chains.

name: Lion Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a lion—the large cat and king of the jungle—looking straight ahead. Depicted as a golden-yellow lion face with a light- or dark-brown mane, white muzzle, and neutral expression.

Often used with an affectionate tone. Does not have a full-bodied lion emoji counterpart. A lion is represented as ‚ôå Leo in the Western zodiac.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Apple's lion previously featured a timid-looking expression.

name: Lipstick
description: Lipstick shown with the lid removed. Displays in a shade of red on most platforms, except WhatsApp and Twitter which have a more a pinkish color.

name: Lizard
description:
A lizard, a scaly reptile with a long tail. Depicted as a light-green lizard on all fours from above, generally looking left with large eyes, a lightly textured or colored back, and toes outspread, as a gecko.

May be used for a variety of wild and pet lizards.

Google’s lizard was previously brown.

name: Llama
description:
A llama, a long-necked, camel-like animal, native to South America and used for transport and wool. Depicted as a shaggy white, light-brown, or multicolored llama in full profile on all fours facing left.

May be used to represent an alpaca or related animals.

name: Lobster
description:
A lobster, a large crustacean with a prominent tail and pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange lobster (as cooked) from above, with a long body and tail, short, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top of which are very large pincers.

Often used to represent lobster as food as well as in connection to the US state of Maine.

In its release year of 2018, Emojipedia’s original sample image was criticized as anatomically incorrect but was shortly after resolved. That year, the transgender community embraced the lobster as a symbol for their efforts for Transgender Flag emoji.

Samsung, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s lobsters are depicted at an angle.

name: Lock
description:
A locked (closed) padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a secure internet connection, private account, or locked device. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle. WhatsApp’s design is silver.

Commonly used for content concerning safety, security, privacy, and protection as well as various senses of lock, e.g., locked in/down.

This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Additionally, this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with private accounts on the platform. Learn more here.

See also: üîè Locked With Pen and üîê Locked With Key.

name: Lock with Ink Pen
description:
A locked (closed) padlock with a fountain pen or nib positioned at various angles in front of it. Vendors implement the same design as their üîí Locked and the same or similar design as their üñãÔ∏è Fountain Pen or ‚úíÔ∏è Black Nib.

May represent digital certificates in public-key technology. May also have similar applications as üîí Locked (privacy, security) and üñãÔ∏è Fountain Pen or ‚úíÔ∏è Black Nib (writing, signing).

Apple’s design previously displayed a nib, as did Google’s.

This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Additionally, this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with private accounts on the platform. Learn more here.

name: Lollipop
description:
A colorful lollipop made of swirled hard candy attached to a stick. Colors vary by platform, though most designs show rainbow colors or pinks and reds.

This emoji tends to spike in use around Halloween.

Samsung, Microsoft, and Facebook all used to have pink and red designs, but have since opted for rainbow colors.

name: Long Drum
description:
A long drum with a tall body and a cylindrical or hourglass shell. Can be used to represent various drums found around the world from Africa to the Caribbean to Latin America to Asia. Types of long drum include (but are not limited to) djembe, talking drum, conga, bongo, tumbadora, atabaque, and dhol.

Can also be used to talk about drums, music, or beats in general.

name: Lotion Bottle
description:
A bottle of lotion for the skin, such as moisturizer or sunscreen (sunblock). May be used for other hygienic liquids, including shampoo and body wash, as well as beauty products.

Appearance varies across platforms, but commonly depicted in white and gold colors. Some designs also include a droplet icon on the bottle.
