Most platforms feature a bottle with a pump, though others previously displayed a cylinder with a cap.

name: Lotus
description:
A pink lotus flower in full bloom.

May be used to represent beauty, purity, calmness, or serenity. 

May also be used along with üßò Person in Lotus Position to represent yoga or meditation.

name: Loudly Crying Face
description:
A yellow face with an open mouth wailing and streams of heavy tears flowing from closed eyes. May convey inconsolable grief but also other intense feelings, such as uncontrollable laughter, pride or overwhelming joy.

In March 2021, üò≠ Loudly Crying Face became the most popular emoji on Twitter. It held this position until January 2022, when üòÇ Face with Tears of Joy returned as the top emoji on the platform.

name: Love Hotel
description:
A love hotel is a hotel that can be hired by the hour instead of as accommodation for the evening.

Sometimes mistaken for a get well soon emoji due to the similarity in appearance to the hospital. The Microsoft version of this emoji previously displaying a bed with a heart above it.

name: Love Letter
description:
The back of an envelope, generally shown in white and sealed with a red heart. Represents a love letter or note, valentine, or affectionate greeting card. Commonly used to convey various feelings or messages of love and happiness.

Facebook’s envelope is pink, while Microsoft’s envelope was previously open.

name: Low Battery
description: A battery with a minimal amount of power remaining, indicated by the color red. Used to show low power or energy and the need to be plugged in or recharged.

name: Low Brightness Symbol
description: An icon of a outlined sun, used when decreasing¬†the brightness of a screen.¬†Appears smaller¬†than the¬†High¬†Brightness Symbol.

name: Lower Left Ballpoint Pen
description:
A blue or black ballpoint pen, as used for everyday writing. Depicted with its cap removed onto its end or as retractable pen. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning writing (e.g., creative, professional) as well as signing (deals, laws, in sports).

Google's design previously featured a brown-colored pen. Not to be confused with ‚úíÔ∏è Black Nib or üñãÔ∏è Fountain Pen, though their applications often overlap.

name: Lower Left Crayon
description:
A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling a Crayola crayon. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning drawing, colors, arts and crafts, and schooling.

WhatsApp’s crayon is green while Facebook’s is orange.

name: Lower Left Fountain Pen
description:
A black fountain pen with a silver nib, as used for signing important documents. Often depicted with gold hardware. Positioned at a 45° angle with its tip at the lower left. Like ‚úíÔ∏è Black Nib, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).

Apple and Twitter feature the same designs as their ‚úíÔ∏è Black Nib, but with their tips angled to the lower left.

name: Lower Left Paintbrush
description:
A thin, artist's paintbrush, as used to paint a picture. Often depicted with reddish paint on its pointed bristles. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left.

Commonly used for various content concerning the art of painting or fine art more generally. Often paired with üé® Artist Palette.

name: Luggage
description:
A suitcase or bag, as used for traveling. Most platforms depict gray or blue rolling luggage with an extended handle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling or taking trips, whether for business or leisure.

Apple’s design features an old-fashioned, leather, trunk-styled case with graphic luggage labels/stickers, not to be confused with üíº Briefcase or üëú Handbag. Google and Facebook also include such stickers.

May be stored in a üõÖ Coin Locker or inspected at üõÉ Customs.

name: Lungs
description: Pink anatomical lungs and trachea, shown with bronchial tubes on some platforms. Used in medical contexts to talk about lung health. Sometimes used in reference to taking deep breaths, hyperventilating, or breathing in general. Also used in the context of smoking or vaping.

name: Lying Face
description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows, enlarged eyes, slight frown, and long nose, indicating it’s telling a lie in the manner of Pinocchio. Like that character, Facebook's design features a wooden nose. 

May represent lying, a liar, and other concepts of deceit and dishonesty to varying degrees of intensity. Sometimes used to convey disbelief (e.g., You must be kidding) or feeling abashed (e.g., as if caught in the act of lying).

name: Mage
description: A person who wields magical powers derived from supernatural or occult sources.

name: Magic Wand
description: A wand with sparkles (‚ú®magic‚ú®) coming out of its end. Most platforms show a classic magician-style magic wand that's black with white tips. WhatsApp shows a golden magic wand tipped with a star, similar to the wand that Glenda the Good Witch uses in the 1939 film The Wizard of Oz.

name: Magnet
description:
A horseshoe magnet, as used to pick up iron. Depicted at various angles in red with silver-tipped poles.

Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative magnetism and attraction. May also be used in various science-related contexts more generally.

Twitter’s design features two electric bolts coming from its poles. WhatsApp’s horseshoe is half blue, denoting an opposite magnetic pole.

name: Mahjong Tile Red Dragon
description: The red dragon tile in the game of Japanese Mahjong. White, with red ‰∏≠ character printed on it.

name: Male Sign
description: A circle shown with a diagonal arrow pointing out the top-right, used as a representation for men.

name: Male with Stroke and Male and Female Sign
description:
A symbol commonly used to represent those in the transgender community. Used within the draft emoji sequence for the Transgender Flag emoji, and also given emoji presentation on Samsung devices.

Shows as a plain text character on other platforms.

name: Mammoth
description: A brown wooly mammoth with large curved tusks. Can also be used to represent a mastodon.

name: Man
description: The male version of üßë Person.

name: Man Artist
description: A man engaged in the visual art of painting, shown holding a palette and paintbrush.

name: Man Astronaut
description: A male astronaut or cosmonaut shown wearing a space suit and helmet.

name: Man Biking
description: The male version of the üö¥ Bicyclist emoji.

name: Man Bouncing Ball
description: The male version of the ‚õπ Person With Ball emoji.

name: Man Bowing
description: The male version of the üôá Person Bowing Deeply emoji.

name: Man Cartwheeling
description: A man doing a cartwheel, representing the sport of gymnastics.

name: Man Climbing
description:
A male rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope.

Variations exist for üßó‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman Climbing and üßó Person Climbing.

name: Man Construction Worker
description: The male version of the üë∑ Construction Worker emoji.

name: Man Cook
description:
A man responsible for food preparation wearing a white buttoned chef jacket and toque hat.

Usually shown with either a wooden spoon or a skillet frying an egg, though WhatsApp's design is holding a spatula.

name: Man Dancing
description: A man dancing, added as a gender pair for the üíÉ Woman Dancing. Shown on most platforms in a 70s-era suit, and one hand in the air in a disco-dancing style.

name: Man Detective
description: The male version of the üïµ Sleuth or Spy emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.

name: Man Elf
description: A male creature with pointed ears and a human-like face.

name: Man Facepalming
description: A hand shown pressing against the head of a man, commonly written as facepalm. Used to display frustration or embarrassment at the ineptitude of a person or situation.

name: Man Factory Worker
description: A man working in a factory setting, depicted as wearing overalls and protective headgear while holding an active welding gun.

name: Man Fairy
description: A magical male creature found in myths and fantasy stories. Generally depicted as having insect-inspired wings, it can also be assumed to be quite diminutive in size.

name: Man Farmer
description: A man engaged in agriculture, raising living organisms for food or raw materials. Generally depicted as wearing a wide-brimmed hat and holding a crop (such as carrots or corn) or a pitchfork.

name: Man Feeding Baby
description:
A man feeding a baby with a bottle, sometimes looking down to the infant and smiling.

This emoji supports skin tone modifiers, which apply to the adult. The head of the baby is recommended to be hidden to avoid a situation where the skin tone of the baby would only correlate to the skin tone of the adult.

Variants include üßë‍üçº Person Feeding Baby and üë©‍üçº Woman Feeding Baby. See also ü§± Breast-Feeding.

name: Man Firefighter
description: A man professionally tasked with controlling and extinguishing fires.

name: Man Frowning
description: The male version of the üôç Person Frowning emoji.

name: Man Genie
description: A supernatural male being, which is generally shown to be imprisoned within a bottle or lamp. May be capable of granting wishes when summoned.

name: Man Gesturing No
description: A woman with arms crossed forming an ‘X’ to indicate ‘no’ or ‘no good’. This motion is used on the TV game show Deal or No Deal to indicate ‘No Deal’. Intended to be gender-neutral but shown as a woman on most platforms.

name: Man Gesturing OK
description: The male version of the üôÜ Face With OK Gesture emoji.

name: Man Getting Haircut
description: The male version of the üíá Haircut emoji.

name: Man Getting Massage
description: The male version of the üíÜ Face Massage emoji.

name: Man Golfing
description: The male version of the üèå Golfer emoji.

name: Man Guard
description: The male version of the üíÇ Guardsman emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.

name: Man Health Worker
description:
A man working in the field of health care. This may be used to represent a doctor, nurse, or pharmacist.

See also: üë©‍‚öïÔ∏è Female Health Worker

name: Man Judge
description: A man who presides over court proceedings, wearing the traditional black gown and wielding a gavel.

name: Man Juggling
description: A man juggling between three and five colored balls. The person shown in this emoji wears a hat on most major platforms.

name: Man Kneeling
description: A man kneeling down on one or both knees. May be used to represent someone in prayer, or a person resting on the floor.

name: Man Lifting Weights
description: The male version of the üèã Weight Lifter emoji.

name: Man Mage
description:
A man who wields magical powers derived from supernatural or occult sources.

May also be referred to as a wizard, warlock, or sorcerer.

name: Man Mechanic
description: A man engaged in the construction, maintenance, or repair of machinery. Depicted wearing overalls and holding a wrench. Frequently also shown wearing a billed cap.

name: Man Mountain Biking
description: The male version of the üöµ Mountain Bicyclist emoji.

name: Man Office Worker
description: A man wearing business attire. This may include items such as a shirt, tie, jacket, or headset.

name: Man Pilot
description: A man tasked with flying an aircraft, such as an ‚úàÔ∏è Airplane or a üöÅ Helicopter, shown wearing a traditional airline pilot uniform.

name: Man Playing Handball
description: A man playing the sport of handball, shown jumping in the air about to throw the ball. Apple's design is shown wearing protective goggles.

name: Man Playing Water Polo
description: A man shown in water with a ball, playing the sport of water polo.

name: Man Police Officer
description: The male version of the üëÆ Police Officer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.

name: Man Pouting
description: The male version of the üôé Person With Pouting Face emoji.

name: Man Raising Hand
description: The man version of the üôã Happy Person Raising One Hand emoji.

name: Man Rowing Boat
description: The male version of the üö£ Rowboat emoji.

name: Man Running
description: The male version of the üèÉ Runner emoji.

name: Man Scientist
description: A man who is studying or has expert knowledge of one or more of the natural or physical sciences. Generally depicted wearing safety goggles and a white lab coat while holding a test tube filled with colorful liquid.

name: Man Shrugging
description: A man shrugging his shoulders to indicate a lack of knowledge about a particular topic, or a lack of care about the result of a situation. ¯\_(„ÉÑ)_/¯

name: Man Singer
description:
A man singer or rock star generally displayed with a microphone, and sometimes musical notes.

iOS and Android display this emoji as a Bowie-esque figure while WhatsApp appears heavily inspired by Prince.

name: Man Standing
description:
A man standing upright. Commonly used to convey awkwardness, particularly on TikTok.

Similar in appearance to üö∂‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man Walking, but shown facing forward and without any motion implied.

name: Man Student
description: A man who is engaged in education. Generally depicted wearing a black graduation gown and cap, and occasionally holding a degree certificate or diploma.

name: Man Superhero
description:
A man who wields abilities beyond those of ordinary people and is dedicated to protecting the public. Generally depicted as wearing a colorful domino mask and a cape.

The Supervillain is the nemesis of this emoji.

name: Man Supervillain
description:
A man who wields abilities beyond those of ordinary people who, unlike their nemesis the Superhero, uses their powers for evil. 

Google's design is similar to that of Mr. Sinister from the X-Men Marvel comics.

name: Man Surfing
description: The male version of the üèÑ Surfer emoji.

name: Man Swimming
description: The male version of the üèä Swimmer emoji.

name: Man Teacher
description: A man standing in front of a chalkboard (aka blackboard) with the intention of teaching a class. Often shown holding a üìï Closed Book or a pointer.

name: Man Technologist
description:
A man behind a computer screen, working in the field of technology.

See also: üë©‍üíª Female Technologist

name: Man Tipping Hand
description:
A man tipping his hand by his shoulder as if he’s carrying a tray of drinks or flipping his hair.

This emoji is commonly used to express sassiness or sarcasm.

name: Man Vampire
description: A male vampire shown wearing a dark cape, and with pointed fangs.

name: Man Walking
description: The male version of the üö∂ Person Walking emoji.

name: Man Wearing Turban
description: The male version of the üë≥‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman Wearing Turban emoji.

name: Man Zombie
description: A reanimated human man, often found in works of horror fiction.

name: Man and Woman Holding Hands
description: A woman and man holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

name: Man in Lotus Position
description:
A sitting man with their eyes closed and their legs crossed in the lotus position. 

Can be used to broadly represent yoga, meditation, relaxation, or calmness.

name: Man in Manual Wheelchair
description: A man using a manual wheelchair as a mobility aid.

name: Man in Motorized Wheelchair
description: A man using a motorized wheelchair as a mobility aid.

name: Man in Steamy Room
description: A man in a sauna, usually with a towel or robe and sometimes holding a ladle for pouring water on hot stones to create the steamy environment.

name: Man in Tuxedo
description: A man dressed for a formal occasion, wearing a tuxedo.

name: Man with Gua Pi Mao
description: A person wearing a gua pi mao; a type of Chinese hat. Sometimes referred to as a skullcap.

name: Man with Turban
description: A man wearing a turban; a form of customary headwear worn by Sikhs or Muslims.

name: Man with Veil
description: A man wearing a traditional Western wedding dress with a veil over their head.

name: Man with White Cane
description: A man using a white cane as a mobility aid, presumably due to them being blind or visually impaired.

name: Man: Bald
description: The male version of üßë‍ü¶≤ Bald Person.

name: Man: Beard
description:
A man shown with long hair and a beard.

Note that as of late 2021, Samsung's design displays this emoji with a more gender-neutral design than that used for their üßî Person with Beard emoji.

name: Man: Blond Hair
description: The male version of üë± Person with Blond Hair.

name: Man: Curly Hair
description: The male version of üßë‍ü¶± Person with Curly Hair.

name: Man: Red Hair
description: The male version of üßë‍ü¶∞ Person with Red Hair.

name: Man: White Hair
description: The male version of üßë‍ü¶≥ Person with White Hair.

name: Mango
description: The ripe fruit of a tropical mango. Variously depicted in shades of yellow, red, orange, and green with a single, green leaf and stem.

name: Mans Shoe
description: A shoe worn by a man, to work, dinner, or another occasion that requires footwear. Unlike womens shoes, this shoe is likely to be comfortable.

name: Mantelpiece Clock
description:
An antique-styled mantel clock with a flat base and rounded case, as made of wood and brass and placed above a fireplace.

Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also suggest a traditional home or old-time environment. 

Samsung’s design previously featured a more modern-looking, blue clock.

name: Manual Wheelchair
description:
A manual wheelchair. Most platforms show a red and black or blue and black wheelchair. Distinct from ‚ôø Wheelchair Symbol, which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also üë©‍ü¶ΩWoman in Manual Wheelchair or üë®‍ü¶ΩMan in Manual Wheelchair.

ü¶º Motorized Wheelchair was approved at the same time as this emoji.

name: Maple Leaf
description:
The distinctive, star-shaped leaf of the maple tree. Depicted as a reddish-orange maple leaf, as has changed color in the fall/autumn, with five pointed segments.

Used as an emblem of Canada, featured on the üá®üá¶ Flag of Canada. Also used to represent trees and the season of fall/autumn more generally.

Microsoft's leaf was previously yellow.

name: Maracas
description: A set of maracas with a colorful motif painted on them.

name: Martial Arts Uniform
description: A white uniform used in marital arts such as judo or karate. Held together using a material belt. Known as keikogi in Japanese.

name: Mate Drink
description:
Mate is a caffeinated beverage popular in many South American countries. Green in color (from a key ingredient: the dried leaves of yerba mate) and consumed via a metal straw.

This drink is commonly referred to as yerba mate in English, and sometimes spelled maté (to distinguish from a mate, as in friend).

name: Meat on Bone
description:
A hunk of unspecified meat on a white bone, as associated with cartoon cavepersons or food in anime and manga (Japanese ano niku, “that meat”).

This emoji was shown as a steak in Android 4.4.

name: Mechanic
description: A person engaged in the construction, maintenance, or repair of machinery. Depicted wearing overalls and holding a wrench. Frequently also shown wearing a billed cap.

name: Mechanical Arm
description: A mechanical or prosthetic arm.

name: Mechanical Leg
description: A mechanical or prosthetic leg.

name: Medium Black Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of black. May be used to represent anything black.

name: Medium White Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of white. May be used to represent anything white.

name: Melon
description: A melon fruit in a light greenish-brown rind. Depicted as a cantaloupe by most platforms, but can resemble a honeydew at a distance.

name: Melting Face
description:
A yellow smiley face melting into a puddle. 

The eyes and mouth slip down the face, yet still maintain a distorted smile. This quality lends this emoji to sarcasm.

Can be used literally to talk about extreme heat. Can also be used metaphorically to talk about embarrassment, shame, a slowly sinking sense of dread, or feeling overwhelmed in some way.

name: Memo
Men Wrestling
description: Two men engaged in the sport of wrestling.

name: Men with Bunny Ears
description: The male version of the üëØ Woman With Bunny Ears emoji.

name: Mending Heart
description: A heart shown with a bandage across one side; the opposite of a broken heart. May be used to indicate the process of healing, recovery, or to express sympathy for someone going through a difficult time.

name: Menorah with Nine Branches
description: A menorah showing nine lit candles, used on the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah.

name: Mens Symbol
description: A stick-figure icon of a man, generally used to indicate a male restroom. The female equivalent is the Womens Symbol emoji.

name: Mermaid
description: The female version of the üßú Merperson emoji.

name: Merman
description: The male version of the üßú Merperson emoji.

name: Merperson
description:
A merperson who may be referred to as merfolk or merpeople in plural. May be used for the display of a mermaid, mergirl, merwoman, or merman.

Occasional shown wielding a trident.

name: Metro
description:
A metro: frequent underground train found in built-up areas with high populations.

This emoji is generally displayed as a forward-facing train, with some platforms also displaying a tunnel as a circle surrounding the train. Apple's artwork shows the characters IL2 which may be a reference to one of the more locked-down buildings at Apple's Infinite Loop Headquarters during iPhone development (IL2 = Infinite Loop 2).

name: Microbe
description:
A microbe, as a bacterium grown in a üß´ Petri Dish or observed under a üî¨ Microscope. Generally depicted as a squiggly, single-celled microorganism with prominent cilia. Color, shape, and position vary across platforms. Commonly used to represent bacteria, viruses, and germs and disease more generally.

In 2020, this emoji became primarily used in reference to Coronavirus / COVID-19.

Apple's version of this emoji most closely represents a virus, while others from Samsung, Microsoft and Twitter appear as bright green bacteria. Other versions of this emoji also appear mainly as bacteria: Facebook's is indigo, and WhatsApp’s purple. Google’s design previously displayed five microbes in different, bright colors.

name: Microphone
description:
A microphone, used to amplify a person’s voice when speaking or singing.

Previously shown with music notes on most platforms, implying it to be used for a singer / singing. Today only Twitter's design retains these notes.

name: Microscope
description:
A microscope, as used in science laboratories to magnify small objects, such as cells or insects. Depicted as a compound opitical microscope with an adjustable eyepiece, lens, arm, and slide stage mounted on a base. Generally shown as metal with the viewing apparatus facing left.

Commonly used for various content concerning science and research. May also be used for various senses of inspection (e.g., taking a closer took).

Google’s design was previously shown in red.

name: Military Helmet
description: A round military helmet with a chinstrap. All platforms depict a green helmet, with some designs featuring a green camouflage pattern.

name: Military Medal
description: A ribbon and medallion generally awarded to a person in the military for heroic acts.

name: Milky Way
description:
The Milky Way – a galaxy of billions of stars that includes our own solar system and planet earth.

Shown by many platforms as a night sky, with silhouettes of mountains or hills in the foreground.

name: Minibus
description: A small bus or minivan designed to carry fewer people than a full-sized bus. Displayed in white on most platforms (green on Facebook).

name: Minidisc
description:
A minidisc, depicted as a small, silver or gold optical disc housed in a square cartridge, its shutter positioned to the right.

Discontinued as an audio and data storage format in 2013 due to the success of CD and MP3 technology, though the emoji is commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, and related film and music content, especially albums.

Samsung’s design previously featured a silver disc labeled MD, for minidisc. Early designs from au by KDDI showed an angled üíæ Floppy Disk, perhaps as being inserted or ejected into a computer drive.

See also üíø Optical Disc and üìÄ DVD.

name: Mirror
description:
A mirror with an ornate gold or silver frame. The shape and style of the mirror varies from platform to platform.

Used to talk about mirrors, reflection, or self-reflection.

name: Mirror Ball
description: A mirror ball, also called a disco ball. A hanging sphere made up of a bunch of tiny mirrors, which reflect spots of light around a room, creating a party atmosphere.

name: Mobile Phone
description:
A mobile phone (cell phone), as used to text, check social media, or take selfies. Depicted as a black or gray smartphone with a generic blue screen or multicolored app icons. Commonly used for various content concerning mobile phones, technology, and communication.

The designs from Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Samsung resemble phones offered by their respective companies, e.g., iPhone. WhatsApp’s design features a night sky as its wallpaper, displaying the time as 9:34.

Early designs for the mobile phone emoji from au by KDDI resembled a traditional telephone receiver, and vice versa, before having their codepoints swapped in later releases.

See also üì≤ Mobile Phone With Arrow.

name: Mobile Phone Off
description:
A sign indicating that mobile phones should be turned off. Used in situations such as a cinema or live performance.

Displayed as a mobile phone with the word OFF. Previously shown with a cross instead of the word OFF on Windows.

name: Mobile Phone with Rightwards Arrow at Left
description:
A mobile phone (cell phone) with a rightward arrow pointed at it from the left. Intended to indicate an incoming call or message, but used to represent mobile phones, technology, and communication more generally.

Arrow color varies, but is often blue. Vendors implement the same design as üì± Mobile Phone.

name: Money Bag
description:
A bag full of money. Depicted as a sack, usually tan, tied off and displaying a dollar sign. May be filled with coins, as most platforms show a rounded bag.

Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money.

name: Money with Wings
description: A banded stack of U.S. dollar bills with feather wings, as if flying. Its flight may represent losing, transferring, or earning money, but commonly used for wealth, money, and success more generally, often with a flourish or sense of flair.

name: Money-Mouth Face
description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows, currency symbols for eyes (usually dollar signs), and an open smile sticking out a tongue (usually colored green with a dollar sign, echoing a dollar banknote).

Facebook's design shows this emoji's dollar sign eyes over a gray coin shape, while Huawei's emoji design has yen-shaped eyes instead of dollar signs.

Used for a wide range of content dealing with money, including making money, loving wealth, being or feeling rich, and concepts of success and excellence (e.g., on the money).

name: Monkey
description:
A monkey, a small primate with long limbs and tail for climbing trees. Generally depicted as a cartoon-styled, brown monkey with a cheeky facial expression, shown in full profile facing left, sitting on its hind legs with a long, curled tail and round ears.

As with üêµ Monkey Face, often used with a playful tone or for metaphorical senses of monkey.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.

WhatsApp’s monkey is facing right, Facebook’s has shaggy hair.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Monkey Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a monkey, looking straight ahead. Depicted as a brown-haired monkey with a tan or pinkish face, round ears, nostrils, and open-mouthed grin.

As with the full-bodied üêí Monkey, often used with a playful tone or for metaphorical senses of monkey.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Available as an Apple Animoji.

Vendors implement the same or similar monkey face in their Three Wise Monkeys emojis: üôà See-No-Evil Monkey, üôâ Hear-No-Evil Monkey, and üôä Speak-No-Evil Monkey.

Facebook’s monkey previously resembled üêª Bear Face.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Monorail
description: Similar to a train, but running on a single track.¬†Monorails are often found at theme parks, or other tourist destinations.

name: Moon Cake
description: The round, golden-brown pastry of a Chinese mooncake, a traditional delicacy and lunar symbol of the Mid-Autumn Festival. Many platforms feature a design or character imprinted on the crust, and depict a slice cut out to show a brown paste with a duck egg yolk inside. Twitter displays the Chinese character for “fall/autumn” or “harvest” (Áßã) on top.

name: Moon Viewing Ceremony
description:
Moon Viewing Ceremonies (called Tsukimi in Japan) are held each year in autumn to celebrate the full moon and waxing moon in¬†Japan.
This symbol¬†shows Japanese pampas grass and dango (sweet dessert food) which are used in the ceremony, as well as the moon in the background.

name: Moose
description:
A moose head with large antlers.

Can be used to talk about the actual animal. Can also be used to represent countries including Canada and Sweden, where the moose is considered a national symbol. Can also be used alongside the phrase "cool as a moose."

Google’s Moose is facing left, while Twitter displays a full-bodied moose

name: Mosque
description: A mosque building, a place of worship for followers of Islam. Shown with a domed roof and a minaret.

name: Mosquito
description:
A mosquito, a type of bloodsucking fly. Depicted as a brown or black mosquito on its six, long legs, with wings, long abdomen, and needle-like mouth. Variously shown from above or facing left.

May be used to represent various insects, other bugs and bug bites, and insect-borne diseases (e.g., malaria). May also be used for metaphorical pests.

Facebook’s mosquito has a red abdomen, as if filled with blood.

name: Mother Christmas
description: Mother Christmas, more commonly known as Mrs. Claus, is the wife of Santa Claus. Displayed as an older woman with glasses and a festive red and white bonnet. See also: Christmas emoji list.

name: Motor Boat
description: A small boat powered by an engine. Also known as a speedboat or powerboat.

name: Motor Scooter
description: A motor scooter, which may be displayed as any type of motorbike with or without a step-through frame. Distinct from the racing motorcycle, which is used for sport, not transport.

name: Motorized Wheelchair
description:
A motorized wheelchair. Most platforms show a red and black or blue and black wheelchair. Distinct from ‚ôø Wheelchair Symbol which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also üë©‍ü¶ºWoman in Motorized Wheelchair or üë®‍ü¶ºMan in Motorized Wheelchair.

ü¶Ω Manual Wheelchair was approved at the same time as this emoji.

name: Motorway
description: A wide road shown from a first person perspective. Apple's artwork displays a road sign to Curpertino.

name: Mount Fuji
description:
Mount Fuji (called Fuji-san in Japan) is the largest mountain in Japan. Often seen with snow on the peak in colder months of the year.

It is considered lucky in Japan to dream of Mt Fuji in the first dream of the new year.

name: Mountain
description: A mountain shown with two peaks and blue sky. Similar to the snow capped mountain emoji.

name: Mountain Bicyclist
description: A person (cyclist) who rides a mountain bike: a type of off-road bicycle. Intended to be gender-neutral.

name: Mountain Cableway
description: A cable car transportation system allowing users to swiftly ascend up a mountain. Can also be used as a tourist attraction, or as a form of public transport.

name: Mountain Railway
description:
A train and railway in the mountains.

Previously displayed as a funicular in Microsoft’s artwork. Android also previously displayed this train as front-facing and leaving a tunnel, which appeared similarly to the metro emoji at small sizes.

name: Mouse
description:
Eek! A mouse, a small rodent with large ears and a long tail. Generally depicted in white in full profile on all fours facing left, with pink ears, feet, and tail, often with reddish eyes.

See also üê≠ Mouse Face. Not to be confused with üêÄ Rat or üñ±Ô∏è Computer Mouse.

Facebook’s mouse is sitting on its hind legs. Google’s design was previously more cartoon-styled, standing on its hind legs and facing forward with a buck tooth. Microsoft’s mouse was previously brown.

name: Mouse Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a mouse, looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a gray or white mouse face with large, round ears, a pink, pointed nose, and whiskers.

Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied üêÅ Mouse. Not to be confused with üêπ Hamster Face.

Google and Facebook’s designs feature a mouse with buck teeth. Microsoft’s design was previously brown.

name: Mouse Trap
description:
A trap used to catch a mouse, rat, or other unwanted rodent. Metaphorically used in emoji form to suggest any kind of trap or entrapment.

The style of trap shown on major platforms has a box held high with a single stick. A wedge of cheese is used to lure a mouse into the box, knocking the stick away and trapping — but not killing — the mouse.

This is distinct from other traps which kill or injure upon capture.

name: Mouth
description:
A human mouth which is generally displayed as a pair of lips and a top row of teeth, instead of the inside of the mouth.

May be used to indicate the spoken word or as an alternative to Kiss Mark.

Notably used alongside two eye emojis to create the "It is what it is" emoji face: üëÅÔ∏èüëÑüëÅÔ∏è. Learn more here.

name: Movie Camera
description:
A classic movie camera. Depicted as a black camera with two mounted reels of film, viewfinder, and lens pointed left or right.

Commonly used for various content concerning movies, film, and video as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit. May also be used in relation to the 2017 Emoji Movie.

Facebook’s design previously resembled a video camera mounted on a tripod.

Not to be confused with üìΩÔ∏è Film Projector.

name: Moyai
description:
A moai, one of the famed, giant stone statues of human figures on Easter Island. Depicted as a gray stone carving of a stylized human head with a prominent brow and nose, most often facing left.

Sometimes used for various idiosyncratic purposes, such as conveying a stoic, deadpan, or silly expression. For example, this emoji is often used to represent various "sigma" or "chad" memes due to its chiselled emotionaless features.

Its official Unicode name of Moyai and inclusion in early Japanese emoji sets, such as from au by KDDI, suggest the emoji may represent the Moyai Statue near Shibuya Station in Tokyo, Japan; previous designs from Google and Microsoft resemble the Tokyo statue. Other Tokyo landmarks are represented in üóº Tokyo Tower and, formerly, Shibuya 109.

name: Mrs. Claus
description: This version of the  Mrs. Claus emoji has the  Dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Black Skin Tone on supported platforms. C http://emojipedia.org/mother-christmas-type-6/

name: Mrs. Claus
description: This version of the  Mrs. Claus emoji has the  Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms. C http://emojipedia.org/mother-christmas-type-1-2/

name: Mrs. Claus
description: This version of the  Mrs. Claus emoji has the  Medium-dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Dark Brown Skin Tone on supported  http://emojipedia.org/mother-christmas-type-5/

name: Mrs. Claus
description: This version of the  Mrs. Claus emoji has the  Medium-light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Cream White Skin Tone on supporte http://emojipedia.org/mother-christmas-type-3/

name: Mrs. Claus
description: This version of the  Mrs. Claus emoji has the  Medium Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Moderate Brown Skin Tone on supported p http://emojipedia.org/mother-christmas-type-4/

name: Multiple Musical Notes
description: Three eighth notes (quavers in British English), used to represent music or singing. Sometimes inserted next to quoted lyrics, to make it clear that they are part of a song.

name: Mushroom
description: The edible fungus of the mushroom, depicted as a toadstool with a white-spotted red cap and stem.

name: Musical Keyboard
description:
A small section of a music keyboard, which differs from a computer keyboard.

Showing white and black keys, this keyboard is played by a pianist to make music. Commonly used as a piano emoji.

name: Musical Note
description:
A music note emoji, which can denote song lyrics, or other music related topics.

Displays as two eighth-notes (quavers in British English) connected with a beam. A single eight-note (quaver) was previously used in Microsoft and Google’s emoji designs.

name: Musical Score
description: A staff (or stave) showing a treble clef and five horizontal lines.

name: Mx Claus
description:
A person, generally depicted as being older with gray hair, wearing a red Christmas (aka "Santa") hat. Does not represent any specific character in folklore. Mx Claus provides a gender inclusive alternative to üéÖ Santa Claus or ü§∂ Mrs. Claus.

Apple depicts Mx Claus as wearing glasses, while other vendors do not.

Mx is an honorific that does not indicate gender.

name: Nail Polish
description:
Colored nail polish being applied to finger nails, often used to display an air of nonchalance or indifference.

Shown as red, pink or purple nail polish on most platforms, the color rarely changes the meaning of this emoji. Previously displayed as a single bottle of nail polish on Android and on Windows.

name: Name Badge
description:
A name badge, used to identify oneself in a location that others may not know your name, such as a school trip, or a work conference.

This tulip-shaped name badge is one of many designs commonly found at kindergartens in Japan.

name: National Park
description: A national park, generally displayed with mountains, a river or stream, and trees.

name: Nauseated Face
description:
A sickly-green face with concerned eyes and puffed, often red cheeks, as if holding back vomit. May represent physical illness or general disgust. Not to be confused with ü§Æ Face Vomiting.

Differs from other smileys conveying sickness, including ü§í Face With Thermometer (used especially for colds and flus) and ü§ï Face With Head-Bandage (physical injury).

name: Nazar Amulet
description:
A nazar, an eye-shaped amulet believed to protect against the evil eye, especially in Turkish culture. Depicted as a rich blue, circular bead with a black dot in the center ringed with white and light blue, resembling an eye.

Commonly used to represent eyes, various senses of looking, various senses of charms, envy and jealousy, and Turkey and Turkish culture. Also used for its blue color more generally.

WhatsApp, Facebook, and Huawei's designs include a small hole, as for threading the amulet on a string or chain.

Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here.

name: Necktie
description:
A necktie commonly worn at work or formal occasions, usually shown being worn with a shirt.

Colors and patterns for both the necktie and the shirt vary by platform.

Previous designs from Google, Facebook, and Samsung displayed a necktie on its own.

name: Negative Squared AB
description: A symbol representing Blood Type AB. Displayed as the letters AB on a red background.

name: Negative Squared Cross Mark
description: A cross mark that displays with a white outlined appearance. Shows on most platforms with a bright green rounded rectangle or circle surrounding it.

name: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter A
description: A symbol representing Blood Type A. Displayed as the letter A on a red background.

name: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter B
description:
A symbol representing Blood Type B. Displayed as the letter B on a red background.

Sometimes used online to replace the letter C at the start of words in reference to the Bloods street gang's practice of turning words like cool into bool. This has expanded in some instances to starting any word with the letter B, or more specifically, this emoji which makes it more üÖ±Ô∏èlear that a letter has been replaced.

name: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter O
description: A symbol representing Blood Type O. Displayed as the letter O on a red background.

name: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter P
description:
Depicted by major emoji vendors as blue square with a white letter 'P' contained within it. Most often to represent a parking space or parking lot.

As of early 2022 this emoji has frequently been used as a positive response on social media - "that's üÖøÔ∏è". This is due to an association with the song 'Pushing P' by American rapper Gunna.

name: Nerd Face
description:
A smiling yellow face with glasses, often with teeth showing, originally buck teeth on most platforms.

While this emoji is often used by people calling themselves nerds in a self-deprecating way, the nerdy glasses paired with buck teeth can, and often does, evoke anti-Asian stereotypes. The fact that the default color of emoji faces is yellow further pushes this emoji into racist "yellowface" territory.

Some platforms have redesigned nerd face over time to not have buck teeth, perhaps in acknowledgement of the harm this imagery may cause. Google, Facebook, WhatsApp, and JoyPixels originally featured designs with buck teeth but have since changed (or completely removed) the teeth on nerd face.

Apple, Twitter, Microsoft, Samsung, and other platforms still use designs for this emoji that include buck teeth.

name: Nest with Eggs
description:
A bird's nest with eggs inside.

May be used to talk about actual nests or birds. May also be used to talk about home in general or to represent phrases like nest egg or empty nest.

ü™π Empty Nest was approved at the same time as Nest with Eggs.

name: Nesting Dolls
description: Nesting dolls, also called matryoshka dolls or Russian dolls, decorated with bright colors including red, yellow, blue, and green. All platforms depict the nesting dolls as open, revealing smaller dolls within the bases of larger dolls. Dolls are all decorated with women wearing headscarfs. Some platforms show a flower motif on the women's dresses or aprons.

name: Neutral Face
description: A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a flat, closed mouth. Intended to depict a neutral sentiment but often used to convey mild irritation and concern or a deadpan sense of humor.

name: New Moon Symbol
description:
A new moon, the first of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a full, bluish- or grayish-black, cratered disc, not illuminated by the sun.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.

See also üåö New Moon Face. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Google’s new moon was previously a gray circle with a yellow outline. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a new moon in a night sky with stars.

name: New Moon with Face
description:
A new moon with a smiling face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts the moon as a dark disc with a slightly smiling human face and nose.

See also üåë New Moon. May be used to represent the moon more generally. Popularly perceived as creepy, used to throw shade (express disapproval), or convey various suggestive or ironic sentiments.

Apple and WhatsApp’s eyes are looking left, as if giving the side-eye. Samsung and Facebook’s faces are looking straight ahead. Google’s facial expression resembles üòè Smirking Face, Twitter’s üôÇ Slightly Smiling Face.

Google’s face previously evoked Lenny Face, Microsoft’s eyes appeared closed, and Facebook’s face was a simple smiley.

name: Newspaper
description:
The front page of a newspaper, as people once read the news before the internet. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.

Most platforms depict a nondescript masthead, images, and columns of text. Apple’s newspaper is called The Apple Times, featuring a logo based on its ü¶Ö Eagle and a picture of its üåã Volcano. Facebook’s is called Daily Feed, with a headline “El Capitan” and picture of that famous rock formation in Yosemite National Park. WhatsApp’s paper reads Daily News with a picture of a map.

See also üóûÔ∏è Rolled-Up Newspaper.

name: Night with Stars
description: A night sky with stars, depicted on major platforms as a cityscape at night.

name: Ninja
description:
A person dressed as a ninja with a black hood, a mask covering the lower half of their face, and the hilt of a knife or sword emerging from behind their shoulder.

The now-discontinued Microsoft ZWJ sequence üê±‍üë§ Ninja Cat did not include the ninja emoji at all as it was developed several years before ninja was approved. It combined üê± Cat Face and üë§ Bust in Silhouette and was only available from Microsoft prior to the debut of the Fluent emoji set in November 2021.

name: No Bicycles
description:
A bicycle with a red stroke through it, indicating that bikes are prohibited from this location.

May be seen in pedestrian malls with a bicycle restriction or crossing train tracks in some countries.

name: No Entry
description: A red circle with a straight horizontal line across its center. Used on signs to indicate that entry into the area where the sign is displayed is forbidden.

name: No Entry Sign
description:
A red circle with a diagonal line through the middle, from top-left to bottom right, used to indicate that something is not permitted

Commonly shown in conjunction with other symbols to indicate No Smoking, No Bikes, or similar.

name: No Mobile Phones
description: A mobile phone with a red stroke through it, indicating that mobile phones should not be present. Often seen in restricted areas, such as Customs or Passport Control.

name: No One Under Eighteen Symbol
description:
The number eighteen with a red stroke through it, indicating a location where a person must be aged 18 or above to enter. Often used online to indicate adult or NSFW content.

Google's design includes the text "under" above the number eighteen.

The Samsung version of this emoji previously displayed the number 19. This may have been due to the practice of counting the first year of life as one instead of zero in parts of East Asia such as South Korea (the location of the Samsung Headquarters).

name: No Pedestrians
description:
A pedestrian symbol with a red stroke through it, indicating that pedestrians are prohibited from this location.

May be seen in dedicated bike lanes, highways, or other areas not suitable to be on-foot.

name: No Smoking Symbol
description: A lit cigarette with a red stroke through it, indicating that smoking is prohibited in this location.

name: Non-Potable Water Symbol
description:
A water tap with a red stroke through it, indicating that water is not safe for drinking (non-potable).

May be used at a camp site or other area that has water suitable for cleaning or other non-drinking purposes.

name: North East Arrow
description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-right, or north-east direction.

name: North West Arrow
description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-left, or north-west direction.

name: Nose
description: A human nose. May be used to indicate smelling, or something that smells.

name: Notebook
description:
A dark-colored, hardcover notebook, as used to write or take notes in school. Commonly used for various content concerning writing and schooling.

Several platforms, including Apple, feature a cover with black-and-white marbling, evoking a classic composition book used in the U.S. Apple's design displays Notes on its cover. Google, Microsoft, and Samsung’s covers were previously yellow or brown.

name: Notebook with Decorative Cover
description:
A closed, hardcover notebook, as used for journaling or sketching. Appearance varies across platforms, with most designs featuring relatively plain covers. Commonly used for content concerning writing and schooling.

Apple's cover is tan and labelled Notes. Facebook’s design is most decorative, pink with a flower pattern.

Google’s design was previously gray and features different-colored tabs, while Samsung's previously displayed the easter egg initials SJST.

name: Nut and Bolt
description:
A metal bolt with a nut threaded around it, as by a wrench. Often positioned at a 45° angle, the head of the bolt at the upper left. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction. May also be used for other hardware, including screws.

Apple’s bolt previously resembled a screw, Google’s a dumbbell; Microsoft’s design previously featured the nut and bolt separately.

name: OK Hand Sign
description:
A gesture showing the index finger and thumb touching to make an open circle. Represents “I’m okay” or “yes, that’s correct / good”.

In American Sign Language (ASL), the number nine is represented with this gesture. The same hand sign can be seen as offensive in some cultures, including in parts of Europe, the Middle East, and South America.

This can also be used as a symbol of White Supremacy, depending on context.

name: OK hand
description: This version of the  OK Hand emoji has the  Dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Black Skin Tone on supported platforms. Copy http://emojipedia.org/ok-hand-sign-type-6/

name: OK hand
description: This version of the  OK Hand emoji has the  Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms. Copy http://emojipedia.org/ok-hand-sign-type-1-2/

name: OK hand
description: This version of the  OK Hand emoji has the  Medium-dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Dark Brown Skin Tone on supported pla http://emojipedia.org/ok-hand-sign-type-5/

name: OK hand
description: This version of the  OK Hand emoji has the  Medium-light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Cream White Skin Tone on supported p http://emojipedia.org/ok-hand-sign-type-3/

name: OK hand
description: This version of the  OK Hand emoji has the  Medium Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Moderate Brown Skin Tone on supported plat http://emojipedia.org/ok-hand-sign-type-4/

name: Octagonal Sign
description:
A red, octagonal sign, often but not always shown with a white or grey rim. Used in many countries as a stop sign.

Unlike other platforms, Huawei's design for this emoji displays the word "STOP".

name: Octopus
description:
An octopus, a sea animal with eight legs, known to change color and release ink. Generally depicted as a pink or orange octopus facing forward, with a large, round head, prominent eyes, and its tentacle-like arms raised at its sides. Platforms vary in the number of arms shown, ranging from four to the full eight, with several designs featuring suckers on them.

Not to be confused with ü¶ë Squid, though their applications may overlap.

Twitter’s octopus is purple. Apple’s has a friendly, cartoon-styled appearance. Google and Samsung’s octopuses previously looked surprised, while Microsoft's suggested an üëæ Alien Monster.

name: Oden
description: A skewer of three bites of Japanese oden, a winter dish made with fishcakes, tofu, konnyaku, and a variety of other ingredients, including boiled eggs. Often served as a stew or skewered and dipped into soy sauce. Resembles the Dango and may be used for other skewered foods (e.g., shish kebab, roasting marshmallows) or spears.

name: Office Building
description:
A generic, high-rise office building. Generally found in cities, and most active during business hours.

The office building shown in Twemoji 2.0 is of Twitter HQ in San Fransisco.

name: Office Worker
description: A person wearing business attire. This may include items such as a shirt, tie, jacket, or headset.

name: Oil Drum
description:
A barrel for transporting bulk liquids, such as oil. Generally depicted as a red or blue metal drum with holes or a stopper on its lid. Commonly used for various content concerning petroleum or hazardous waste.

Google’s design previously displayed a yellow oil drop symbol, while Samsung's design previously featured a yellow hazard sign.

name: Old Key
description:
An old-fashioned key, as opens an antique chest or wardrobe. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a tarnished, silver skeleton key with an ornate, bowed head and two-toothed bit at the bottom left.

Like üîë Key, often used figuratively, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial"). May also be applied to antiques.

Microsoft’s design is gold, with the head at the upper left. Samsung and Facebook’s keys were previously gold.

name: Older Adult
description:
An older adult with no gender specified. This emoji may be used to talk about older adults in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üë¥ Older Man or üëµ Older Woman. See also üßë‍ü¶≥ Person with White Hair, which is similar, though is shown with white hair and without wrinkles on most platforms.

name: Older Man
description: An elderly man gray (grey) hair, and visible wrinkles. Balding in many versions of this artwork, such as Apple and Microsoft designs.

name: Older Woman
description: An elderly woman with gray (grey) hair, and visible wrinkles. Wears glasses on some platforms.

name: Olive
description:
One, two, or three green olives, either pitted or sprouting from a branch. Some platforms show a solitary pitted green olive stuffed with a piece of a pimento pepper.

Can be used to talk about olives or the color green.

name: Om Symbol
description: A symbol often used in relation to the religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism.

name: On with Exclamation Mark with Left Right Arrow Above
description: The capitalized word "on" followed by an exclamation mark (!) with a double-sided arrow above it.

name: Oncoming Automobile
description:
A car being shown from the front. The windscreen and hood (bonnet in British English) of the car can be seen facing forward.

This car shows in red or blue on most platforms. It was previously silver on Android.

name: Oncoming Bus
description: The front of a bus, showing the windscreen,¬†as well as wing mirrors in some versions of this emoji.

name: Oncoming Police Car
description:
A¬†police¬†car, shown with an¬†emergency light¬†on the top.
This emoji is displayed from the front, as opposed to the¬†police car¬†emoji, which is shown¬†from the side.

name: Oncoming Taxi
description: A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the front, as opposed to the taxi emoji which displays the side of the vehicle.

name: One-Piece Swimsuit
description:
A sporty one-piece swimsuit shown in a variety of colors and patterns across different platforms.

Related emojis include üëô Bikini, ü©≥ Shorts, and ü©≤ Briefs.

name: Onion
description: A round yellow onion. Can be used to talk about cooking, eating, or crying. Sometimes used in metaphors about layers. Might also be used in computing contexts in reference to onion routing.

name: Open Book
description:
An open, hardcover book, depicted with a blue cover on most platforms. Some platforms include a bookmark. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling.

Apple’s design displays text from its 1997–2002 Think Different ad campaign:

Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes.The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. And they have no respect for the status quo. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is…

Google’s design previously featured a brown cover with a red bookmark, similar to an early design for üìï Closed Book.

name: Open File Folder
description:
A slightly open tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for an opened folder when using a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.

Commonly used for various content concerning filing, organization, and work, especially at an office.

Apple’s folder is gray, Twitter’s is blue. Google’s design features multiple tabs, Microsoft’s a red tab.

Nearly identical in appearance and use to üìÅ File Folder, which is closed.

name: Open Hands Sign
description: Two open hands, representing openness. Sometimes used as a hug, or as a display of jazz hands.

name: Open Lock
description:
An unlocked padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a non-secure connection or open access online. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle, as an open üîí Locked.

May be used to represent a lack of or concerns about privacy and security. May also be used for figurative senses of unlocking, e.g., achievement unlocked.

WhatsApp’s design is silver, its shackle turned to the right, as Samsung’s previously was.

This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Additionally, this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with private accounts on the platform. Learn more here.

name: Open Mailbox with Lowered Flag
description:
A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag lowered and its slot empty. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

Indicates in the United States that outgoing mail has been picked up. May also indicate that no incoming mail has been delivered.

Compare üì´ Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, üì™ Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and üì¨ Open Mailbox With Raised Flag.

name: Open Mailbox with Raised Flag
description:
An open, curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag raised and a letter in its open slot. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag and white envelope, though Google's envelope was previously yellow. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

Indicates in the United States that there is outgoing mail (post) for pickup. May also indicate that incoming mail has been delivered.

Compare üì´ Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, üì™ Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and üì≠ Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag.

name: Ophiuchus
description: Ophiuchus is used by some as a 13th sign in the Zodiac. The symbol for ophiuchus appears a U shape with a wavy line through it.

name: Optical Disc
description:
A silver optical disc, as a CD or DVD, used to play music or movies before the rise of streaming technology. Commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, Blu-rays, and related film and music content, especially albums.

See also üíΩ Computer Disk and üìÄ DVD.

name: Orange Book
description:
A closed, orange, hardcover book—similar to the Emojipedia logo üìôüòÉ. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as an orange accent color.

Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 4 by John Appleseed. It was previously purple and the third volume. Samsung’s design previously included the text Orange Book.

name: Orange Heart
description: An orange heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts.

name: Orangutan
description:
An orangutan, the orange-haired ape with long arms. Depicted facing forward, with a long broad face and sitting with its legs bent. Occasionally shown scratching its head. Color varies across platforms, ranging from orange to light brown.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Orthodox Cross
description: An orthodox cross symbol, also known as a Russian Orthodox cross or Byzantine cross.

name: Otter
description:
An otter, the playful water mammal in the weasel family. Depicted as a light-brown otter on its back, with its forepaws held together and whiskered face to the left, generally with its long tail curled up.

May be used to refer to certain members of the LGBTQ community, a la the slang term "otter".

Apple’s otter is in water, holding a stone, as is Microsoft’s.

name: Outbox Tray
description:
A paper tray with an up arrow on top, as a symbol for an email outbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden tray with a red arrow pointing upwards. Facebook's design contains paper.

May be used for various digital activity, including uploading, messaging, emailing, ordering, and sharing.

Google’s design previously featured a blue arrow and contained paper. Samsung’s arrow was previously green.

Compare üì• Inbox Tray.

name: Overheated Face
description:
A reddish-orange face with furrowed eyebrows, tongue stuck out, and beads of sweat, as if overheated from high temperatures. Number and position of sweat droplets vary by platforms. May also represent physical attractiveness (slang, hot).

Most platforms feature expressions that are variations on üò∞ Anxious Face With Sweat or üò• Sad but Relieved Face.

name: Owl
description:
An owl, the hooting, large-eyed bird. Depicted as a brown owl with its head facing forward. Shown with large, round, gold-rimmed eyes, talons, tucked wings, and horn-like tufts of feathers.

May be used to represent wisdom. Once popularly used in connection with the hip-hop artist Drake.

Microsoft’s owl previously resembled a barn owl, Samsung’s was purple.

name: Ox
description:
An ox, a bovine used as a draft animal. Depicted in brown in full profile on all fours facing left, with a tail and short horns.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Often used to represent ‚ôâ Taurus (the Bull) in the Western zodiac. 2021 is Year of the Ox.

Often used to represent a bull and occasionally paired with üí© Pile of Poo to stand in for slang terms. Not to be confused with üêÉ Water Buffalo.

name: Oyster
description: Half of an opened oyster shell with gray, pink, or orange flesh inside. Many platforms also include a pearl in the shell.

name: Package
description:
A package (parcel), as contains items ordered online. Depicted at various angles as a light-brown, cardboard box, with a shipping label and its top taped shut.

Commonly used for content concerning shipping, delivery, and moving as well as for boxes more generally.

Apple’s design features an image of a wine glass, indicating fragile contents, and “this way up” orientation arrows. It was briefly identical to its üéÅ Wrapped Gift.

name: Page Facing Up
description:
A white piece of paper, its top right corner curled or dog-eared, with text printed on it, as a business letter or icon for a document on a computer. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

Most platforms indicate text with dark lines. Apple’s design features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:

Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.

Early designs from au by KDDI show a slanted document, suggesting this emoji may have been originally intended to represent a digital document being sent electronically.

Not to be confused with üìÉ Page With Curl or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

name: Page with Curl
description:
A white piece of paper, curled up at the bottom to the left or right, with text printed on it, as a business letter. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

Most platforms indicate text with dark lines. Apple’s design features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie with text from its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:

Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They're not fond of rules. And they have no respect for the status quo. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can't do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward…

Samsung’s design is addressed Dear Samsung. Early designs from au by KDDI resemble üìÑ Page Facing Up, suggesting this emoji may have been originally intended to represent documents on a computer.

Not to be confused with üìÑ Page Facing Up or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

name: Pager
description:
A pager, as worn on the waist to alert a person to a phone call or short text message. Popular in the 1980–90s before mobile phones, though still used by some medical and emergency personnel. Very occasionally used to represent alerts, digital communication, or nostalgia for old technology.

Depicted as a black device with operating buttons and a green screen displaying various numbers across platforms, including:


	Apple: 555-3215 (555 is commonly used for fake numbers in the US)
	Google: 1998 (the year Google was founded; previously showed 8888, the Google DNS IP address)
	Microsoft: [indecipherable]
	Samsung: 954-5684 (unknown origin; previously showed SUNMOON)
	WhatsApp: 867-5309 (an allusion to the 1980s hit song "867-5309/Jenny")
	Twitter: 40404 (Twitter's discontinued SMS number)
	Facebook: 543-4800 (Facebook Inc phone number; previously showed 02 04 20 04, referring to the company's launch date)

name: Palm Down Hand
description:
A hand in profile with the palm facing down.

Can be used to represent the action of dropping or reaching for something. May also be used in a variety of culture-specific contexts including dismissal, negotiation, or as a beckoning gesture.

The design is a mirror image of ü´¥ Palm Up Hand.

name: Palm Tree
description:
A palm tree, a tree-like plant, as grows by the sea. Depicted as a palm tree with long, green, feather-like leaves and a tall, brown, segmented trunk.

May be used to represent beaches, tropical climates and cultures, summer fun, and vacations (holidays). As such, this emoji tends to spike in popularity during the summer months.

Vendors implement a similar tree in their üèùÔ∏è Desert Island.

Microsoft’s palm tree bears coconuts, as Samsung’s previously did. Apple’s palm tree previously had more erect palms.

During the summer of 2024 this emoji became associated with then-Vice President of the Untied States Kamala Harris, referencing a viral clip of a speech made in May 2023 where she stated: "You think you just fell out of a coconut tree? You exist in the context of all in which you live and what came before you.”

name: Palm Up Hand
description:
A hand in profile with the palm facing up.

Can be used to represent the action of lifting, offering, demanding, or beckoning. May also be used to express a question or lack of knowledge.

The design is a mirror image of ü´¥ Palm Down Hand. The hand position is similar to the one in üíÅ Person Tipping Hand.

name: Palms Up Together
description:
Two hands held out together with open palms facing up, in a slightly cupped manner, as if expecting an object to be placed within them.

May also be used to represent an open book in American Sign Language (ASL), or the gesture used by followers of Islam when praying.

name: Pancakes
description:
A stack of breakfast pancakes, topped with a pad of butter and maple syrup oozing down its golden-brown sides, onto a plate on some platforms. 

Especially popular on Pancake Tuesday.

An alternative use for this emoji on TikTok and other platforms: to represent that someone has a flat bottom ('flat as a pancake').

name: Panda Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a panda—a bear-like mammal known for eating bamboo—looking straight ahead. Depicted as a white panda face with black ears and black circles around its eyes.

Often used with an affectionate tone and in association with China, where the animal is found. Sometimes used to represent a red panda. Does not have a full-bodied panda emoji counterpart.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Google and Facebook’s pandas are shown smiling with an open mouth and tongue.

name: Paperclip
description:
A silver paper clip, as used to hold together sheets of paper—or remove a SIM card from a mobile phone. Shown positioned at various angles.

Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies. Also sometimes used as an icon before a hyperlink. Displays as Microsoft mascot Clippy on Windows 11.

Not to be confused with üîó Link, üñáÔ∏è Linked Paperclips, ‚õìÔ∏è Chains, or üß∑ Safety Pin.

name: Parachute
description: An open parachute floating through the air with a human steering. Most platforms feature a ram-air design. Colors vary across platforms.

name: Parrot
description:
A parrot, a brightly colored bird known for its ability to mimic speech. Depicted in full profile facing left. Resembles a green lovebird with red and yellow wings on some platforms and a scarlet macaw with blue and yellow wings on others.

Can be used to represent various parrots or birds in general. May also be used to talk about mimicking.

Facebook’s parrot is orange with blue-tipped wings. Google's parrot was previously a scarlet macaw perched on a branch.

name: Part Alternation Mark
description:
Used in traditional Japanese music such as Noh or Renga, to indicate the start of a song. More specifically, the part alternation mark is displayed where the singer’s part begins.

This symbol looks sort of like a lopsided capital M; or a rollercoaster track showing a dip, and then a drop off to the right.

name: Party Popper
description:
A party popper, as explodes in a shower of confetti and streamers at a celebration. Generally depicted as a gold party hat, striped on some platforms, at a 45° angle, with multicolored confetti and streamers coming from its opening at the upper right. Twitter’s cone is red.

Like üéä Confetti Ball, commonly used to convey congratulations and celebration, as on New Year’s Eve, birthdays, wedding days, graduations, and other special occasions or good times more generally.

name: Passenger Ship
description: A large boat designed to carry passengers across a body of water.

name: Passport Control
description: A person checking passports at an international border.

name: Paw Prints
description:
A pair of paw prints, as left by a pet üêà cat or üêï dog. Generally depicted as two, staggered, dark-colored paw prints, each showing four toes and a pad.

Commonly used for various content concerning pet cats and dogs. Occasionally applied to other quadruped mammals. See also üë£ Footprints.

Apple, Google and Facebook’s prints were previously red, while Microsoft’s were orange. Facebook's earliest design originally displayed human footprints.

name: Pea Pod
description:
A green pea pod split to reveal a row of peas inside.

Can be used to talk about actual pea pods or peas, pods or vegetables in general, or the color green. May be used along with the phrase two peas in a pod.

name: Peace Symbol
description: A circular symbol, commonly used as a representation of peace. Alternatives include the Victory Hand, or the Dove of Peace.

name: Peach
description:
The fleshy, pinkish-orange fruit of the fuzzy peach, shown with green leaves and sometimes a stem.

Thanks to its distinctive cleft, the emoji is most commonly used for “buttocks.” In certain contexts, the peach emoji may refer to impeachment.

In 2016 Apple unveiled a new design for the peach emoji during the iOS 10.2 beta period. This change would have deemphasized its distinctive cleft, leading to criticism from Apple users. Ultimately this change was not implemented.

name: Peacock
description:
A peacock, the male bird that displays a large, fan-like, iridescent tale. Depicted facing forward standing on its legs, with a blue body and green tail feathers outspread.

Sometimes used to suggest something is beautiful or proud. Also sometimes used to accent a peacock-like color or pattern.

name: Peanuts
description:
The pod of the peanut, shown in its rounded, grooved, light-brown shell. Apple depicts a pair.

May be used for peanut butter as well as other edible nuts (e.g., almonds) or metaphorical ones, including slang for “crazy”, “testicle”, or to nut (ejaculate).

name: Pear
description:
A light-green variety of a common pear, shown with a stem and sometimes green leaf.

May be used for its namesake expression, pear-shaped (“prominent hips” or “failure”).

In 2023 this emoji was coopted by the company Pear and its customers to note within their social media profiles that they are not in a relationship and are open to meeting a new romantic partner.

name: Pedestrian
description:
A person going for a walk. Taking a slow-medium pace, this person would be a runner if they picked up their speed.

This emoji does not specify a gender, but was previously shown as a man on most major platforms.

name: Pencil
description:
A classic yellow pencil. Depicted as a graphite pencil, like a U.S. #2 or European HB, with a sharpened tip and pink eraser. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and schooling.

Samsung’s pencil was previously red, Google’s green.

name: Penguin
description:
A penguin, a flightless bird adapted to water and ice. Variously depicted as a full, black-bodied penguin with a white belly and orange bill or as a penguin head.

Often used with an affectionate or playful tone or in association with the cold. Occasionally used to represent a puffin.

Apple and WhatsApp’s designs feature a penguin head, with Apple’s bearing a yellow patch on its head, as an emperor penguin. Other major platforms feature a penguin standing in full profile, facing forward or left.

name: Pensive Face
description:
A pensive, remorseful face. Saddened by life. Quietly considering where things all went wrong. Depicted as a yellow face with sad, closed eyes, furrowed eyebrows, and a slight, flat mouth.

May convey a variety of sad emotions, including feeling disappointed, hurt, or lonely. Less intense than other sad emojis like üò≠ Loudly Crying Face and more introspective.

Microsoft's design previously featured a more neutral, bored expression. Samsung’s design previously looked more guilty or worried. Not to be confused with üòå Relieved Face, which has similarly shaped eyes but in a happier expression.

name: People Holding Hands
description:
Two people holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

No gender is specified for these two people, meaning they are likely to be shown with a gender inclusive design.

name: People Hugging
description:
Two people hugging, shown as faceless blue forms on most platforms. Details of each person are not distinct and thus no options are available to customize the gender or skin tone of either individual.

Not to be confused with ü§ó Hugging Face, which is less clearly a representation of hugging and sometimes used as jazz hands or to express excitement.

name: Performing Arts
description:
Two masks often used on maps to indicate a theatre, these originate in Greek Theatre as masks of tragedy and comedy.

One mask frowns, the other smiles.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity around the Academy Awards (Oscars) ceremony.

name: Permanent Paper Sign
description:
The symbol for infinity enclosed within a circle or square.

Originally encoded as a symbol to represent acid-free paper, this permanent paper sign was later given emoji presentation to form an infinity emoji.

May also be used by members of the autism rights movement to represent neurodiversity.

Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here.

name: Persevering Face
description: A yellow face with a slight frown, furrowed eyebrows, and scrunched eyes, as if holding back tears or exerting great effort. May convey various degrees and tones of frustration, sadness, helplessness, and struggle. Facebook’s design features a light-purple forehead.

name: Person
description:
An adult with no gender specified. This emoji may be used to talk about adults in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üë© Woman and üë® Man.

name: Person Bowing Deeply
description:
A person bowing deeply which is known as dogeza in Japan. Used to express a sincere apology, or to request a large favour.

Many variations of this emoji are misinterpreted as a person doing push-ups, lying down to have a massage, or doing a cute "head resting on hands" gesture.

name: Person Climbing
description:
A rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet and/or rope. The Emojipedia Sample image was created with assistance from World Champion Rock Climber Sasha DiGiulian.

Variations exist for üßó‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman Climbing and üßó‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man Climbing.

name: Person Doing Cartwheel
description:
A person doing a cartwheel, representing the sport of gymnastics.

In June 2023 this emoji was at the center of a viral trend (Ba’t ü§∏ malungkot ü§∏ ang ü§∏ beshy ü§∏ ko?) based on a scene from an episode of the Philippine television drama anthology show Magpakailanman.

name: Person Feeding Baby
description:
A person feeding a baby with a bottle, sometimes looking down to the infant and smiling.

This emoji supports skin tone modifiers, which apply to the adult. The head of the baby is recommended to be hidden to avoid a situation where the skin tone of the baby would only correlate to the skin tone of the adult.

Variants include üë©‍üçº Woman Feeding Baby and üë®‍üçº Man Feeding Baby. See also ü§± Breast-Feeding.

name: Person Frowning
description:
An upset person, frowning with dismay. Gender is not specified, but generally shown as a woman.
