Previously displayed as a man on Samsung and Microsoft platforms.

name: Person Raising Both Hands in Celebration
description:
Two hands raised in the air, celebrating success or another joyous event.

Originally animated to show hands being raised, as might be done along with the the exclamation Banzai! in Japan. Now more commonly only shows the hands in the air.

name: Person in Lotus Position
description:
A sitting person with their eyes closed and their legs crossed in the lotus position. 

Can be used to broadly represent yoga, meditation, relaxation, or calmness.

name: Person in Manual Wheelchair
description: A person using a manual wheelchair as a mobility aid.

name: Person in Motorized Wheelchair
description: A person using a motorized wheelchair as a mobility aid.

name: Person in Steamy Room
description:
A person in a sauna, usually with a towel or robe and sometimes holding a ladle for pouring water on hot stones to create the steamy environment.

Popular in Finland, where people sauna in the nude.

name: Person with Ball
description: A person with a ball, which is generally displayed as a basketballer running and dribbling (bouncing) the basketball.

name: Person with Blond Hair
description:
A person with blond hair. This emoji maintains blond hair no matter which skin tone is chosen. This emoji may be used to talk about blonds in a gender-inclusive way.

Previously displayed as a man with blond hair on all platforms, though shown as a woman with blond hair in earliest Google, Microsoft, and Samsung designs.

Variants include üë±‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman with Blond Hair and üë±‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man with Blond Hair.

name: Person with Crown
description:
A person wearing a crown.

üë∏ Princess and ü§¥ Prince were added in 2015 and 2016, respectively. Person With Crown was created to represent royalty without being overly specific about gender.

name: Person with Folded Hands
description:
Two hands placed firmly together, meaning please or thank you in Japanese culture. A common alternative use for this emoji is for prayer, using the same gesture as praying hands. It can also represent a respectful greeting or show of adoration many in Southeast Asian religions and cultures, such as the Hindu namaste or Buddhist añjali mudra.

Rarely used as a high-five, despite often being suggested as one by emoji keyboard search features. More about this emoji and its possible meanings.

A previous version of this emoji displayed a yellow burst of light behind the two hands on iOS. Android once showed a blob-character with closed eyes and folded hands.

name: Person with Pouting Face
description:
A person with a serious expression, showing mild displeasure with the situation. Could be considered to be reserved or stoic in response, as this person is not visible angry.

Quite different to the Pouting Face Emoji which conveys a more aggressive tone, and is a smiley. Pouting Cat Face is a cat.

name: Person with White Cane
description: A person using a white cane as a mobility aid, presumably due to them being blind or visually impaired.

name: Person: Bald
description:
A person with a bald head. Can be used to represent a bald person or a person with a shaved head. May also be used to represent a person experiencing hair loss from chemotherapy, alopecia, or other medical treatments or conditions. 

This emoji may be used to talk about bald people in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üë©‍ü¶≤ Bald Woman and üë®‍ü¶≤ Bald Man.

name: Person: Curly Hair
description:
A person with curly hair. This emoji may be used to talk about people with curly hair in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üë©‍ü¶± Woman with Curly Hair and üë®‍ü¶± Man with Curly Hair.

name: Person: Red Hair
description:
A person with red hair. This emoji maintains red hair no matter which skin tone is chosen. This emoji may be used to talk about redheads in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üë©‍ü¶∞ Woman with Red Hair and üë®‍ü¶∞ Man with Red Hair.

name: Person: White Hair
description:
A person with white hair. This emoji maintains white hair no matter which skin tone is chosen. This emoji may be used to talk about people with white hair in a gender-inclusive way.

Variants include üë©‍ü¶≥ Woman with White Hair and üë®‍ü¶≥ Man with White Hair. See also üßì Older Person, which is similar, though is shown with wrinkles and gray hair on most platforms.

name: Personal Computer
description:
A laptop personal computer. Depicted as a black or gray device, opened to show a dark or blue screen, keyboard, and touchpad.

Commonly used for various content concerning computer technology, work, and activity.

Previous designs resembled a desktop computer (e.g., iMac) on many platforms, hence its Unicode name of Personal Computer. Apple’s design now resembles a MacBook.

name: Petri Dish
description:
A petri dish, as used to culture microbes. Depicted as a clear, shallow cylinder with a red, blue, or green growth medium, such as agar, with splotches of variously colored cells, like bacteria.

May be used for various content concerning biology and science more generally. May also be used to represent germs and other microorganisms.

Samsung’s design features a lid, while Google’s design previously featured a dropper.

name: Pick
description:
A pickaxe, a tool with a curved spike for breaking up rocks in mining. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.

May be used for various content concerning building, construction, digging, mining, or rock climbing. Not to be confused with üî® Hammer or Axe.

name: Pickup Truck
description: A red or turquoise pickup truck. Used to talk about trucks or modes of transportation in general.

name: Pie
description:
A baked dish with a pastry crust, filled with sweet or savory ingredients. Appearance widely varies by platform.

Apple depicts a whole pie in a tin, its crimped crust scored to let out steam. WhatsApp and Twitter's designs depict a slice of cherry pie. 

Google's design previously showed a slice of pumpkin pie, as served at Thanksgiving.

name: Pig
description:
A pig, a plump animal farmed for its meat, such as bacon. Depicted in light pink in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long snout and short, curly tail.

May be used to represent the animal, its food products, or various metaphorical senses of pig.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac; 2019 is the Year of the Pig. See also üê∑ Pig Face, üêΩ Pig Nose, and üêó Boar.

WhatsApp’s design previously featured a wide grin.

name: Pig Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a pig looking straight ahead. Depicted as a pink face with a neutral expression, pointed or floppy ears, and distinctive pig nose.

Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied üêñ Pig. Available as an Apple Animoji.

Apple’s face bears a slight grin and previously featured floppy ears.

name: Pig Nose
description:
The snout of a pig. Depicted as a pink oval or slightly pear-shaped nose with two black nostrils.

See also üêñ Pig and üê∑ Pig Face.

Previously displayed as a cute pig character on Google Gmail.

name: Pile of Poo
description:
A swirl of brown poop, shaped like soft-serve ice cream with large, excited eyes and frequently a big, friendly smile.

Widely agreed to have been inspired by the various poop-shaped characters within the Dr. Slump manga series by Akira Toriyama.

May be used to represent feces and other bathroom topics as well as stand in for their many related slang terms. It also enjoys a wide range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of whimsy or silliness, given its fun, happy expression.

Microsoft and Google previously depicted a literal pile of feces, Google’s design featuring stink lines and flies hovering above it.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

name: Pill
description:
A capsule of medicine. Generally depicted at a 45° angle, half red, half yellow. Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well various types of drugs.

Samsung’s design previously featured a blue-and-white capsule with two round pills, one orange, the other white. Google and Microsoft’s designs previously featured blue in their capsules.

name: Pilot
description: A person tasked with flying an aircraft, such as an ‚úàÔ∏è Airplane or a üöÅ Helicopter, shown wearing a traditional airline pilot uniform.

name: Pinata
description:
A colorful decorated container that comes in many shapes, a piñata is filled with candy or toys. Hit to break open for celebrations such as Cinco de Mayo, this is generally associated with Mexico.

Displayed as a donkey on some platforms, and as a three-dimensional star with 6–9 points on others.

name: Pinched Fingers
description:
An emoji showing the fingers held together in a vertical orientation, often referred to as the Italian hand gesture ma che vuoi, sometimes called the "finger purse." In Italy this gesture tends to be used in disagreement, frustration, or disbelief and can mean “What do you want?” or “What are you saying?” Outside Italy anyone performing a caricature of an Italian person, regardless of context or tone, might use this gesture.

Pinched Fingers has a variety of other culturally specific uses. In Israeli culture it can mean “hold on,” “relax,” or “be patient.” The K-Pop star Yuri uses it as a signature gesture to represent a dumpling and a general warm sentiment. It can also be used to represent the act of fisting.

Not to be confused with ü§è Pinching Hand, which has overlapping senses. Both are used to represent precision when someone is making a sharp point with accompanying speech.

name: Pinching Hand
description: A hand with thumb and index finger in close proximity. Used to suggest that something is small, or to gesture a small amount.

name: Pine Decoration
description:
A Japanese kadomatsu, composed of pine leaves and bamboo shoots. Traditionally placed outside homes in Japan around the New Year to welcome spirits for a plentiful, happy year ahead.

Depicted as three shoots of bamboo, arranged vertically at different heights in a wooden container, arrayed with pine leaves.

Often used to represent various plants or as a green accent color.

WhatsApp’s kadomatsu is adorned with red berries, as is Facebook’s, which also includes pink cherry blossoms.

name: Pineapple
description: The tropical fruit of a pineapple, shown in spiky, golden-brown skin and with a pointed, green crown. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle.

name: Pink Heart
description:
A plain pink heart, expected to be frequently used alongside other hearts. Used to represent love, friendship, and feelings of warmth, and the color pink.

For many years before its introduction in 2022, the plain pink heart was one of the world's most frequently requested emojis.

On several platforms, pink hearts are used in the design of other emojis. These emoji include: Sparkling Heart üíñ, Two Hearts üíï, Growing Heart üíó, Beating Heart üíì, Revolving Heart üíû, Heart with Arrow üíò, Heart with Ribbon üíù, and Kiss üíè.

name: Pirate Flag
description: A skull and crossbones displayed on a black flag, used on pirate ships, also known as a Jolly Roger.

name: Pisces
description: The¬†Pisces astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Fish.

name: Pistol
description:
A squirt gun (water pistol), as used to spray water for fun.

On major platforms, depicted as a green or orange toy gun with an orange tip and barrel pointed left. Google and Facebook’s designs include mounted reservoirs.

Originally depicted as a classic handgun, as a revolver or other pistol. In 2016, Apple switched its design from weapon to toy; other major vendors followed suit by 2018. Deprecated emoji sets or smaller platforms still display the emoji as a handgun. 

In July 2024, X / Twitter updated this emoji's design to once again show a real firearm. In August 2024 the firearm's design was changed, and also made available for iOS platforms.

Microsoft initially displayed the emoji as a toy ray gun before switching to a revolver, then squirt gun. Google once featured a blunderbuss.

name: Placard
description:
A sign on a post, commonly used to promote ideas, causes, or make announcements. Often used used in the context of politics to represent a lawn sign or a poster brought to a protest. Also seen in commercial advertising.

Shown with indiscernible writing or not writing at all, this emoji is flexible in its use. WhatsApp shows a peace sign, which tilts the meaning away from commercial use.

name: Place of Worship
description:
A building used for worship by people of any faith or religion. Examples include a church, mosque, or synagogue. A person is shown on their knees praying, in this symbol.

Multi-faith places of worship are commonly found at airports.

name: Playground Slide
description:
A slide with a ladder, as seen in children's playgrounds.

May be used to talk about children, parks, or playtime. May also be used metaphorically to talk about a smooth movement or action like the popular dance the electric slide or sliding into someone's DMs, usually for the purpose of flirting.

Additionally may be used in reference to something with a downward descent.

name: Playing Card Black Joker
description: The joker in a deck of cards, usually appearing like a court jester.

name: Plunger
description:
A toilet plunger with a wooden handle and red flange and cup.

Used to talk about toilets and clogged pipes. Also used metaphorically to talk about a mess or something that's disgusting.

name: Polar Bear
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of polar bear, looking straight ahead. Depicted as the face of a white bear with round ears.

WhatsApp previously showed the full body of the bear.

name: Police Car
description:
A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top.
This emoji is displayed from the side, as opposed to the oncoming police car emoji, which is shown¬†from the front.

name: Police Cars Revolving Light
description: A revolving red light seen on top of a police car. Often used in emergency circumstances in addition to a siren making a loud warning sound.

name: Police Officer
description:
A police officer wearing a blue hat with a gold badge or shield in the middle.

See also üëÆ‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman Police Officer or üëÆ‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man Police Officer

name: Poodle
description:
A poodle, a popular dog breed with curly hair, often groomed in an ornamental pattern.

Generally depicted as a grayish-white poodle in full profile on all fours facing left, with a shaved torso, legs, and face with fuller, pom-pom-like hair on its head, ears, chest, feet, and tip of tail (as the Continental Clip).

Like üêï Dog, may be used to represent a variety of dog breeds (often fluffy or long-haired). See also üê∂ Dog Face.

Google, Samsung, and Facebook’s designs previously featured pink poodles.

name: Popcorn
description:
The buttery-white snack of popcorn brimming in a classic red-and-white-striped carton, as enjoyed at a movie theater. 

May be used to express engagement (“edge of one’s seat”).

name: Postal Horn
description:
A postal horn (post horn). Depicted as a coiled, valveless, brass horn, like a bugle or trumpet, with two red tassels. Sometimes used to mark announcements as well as for various content concerning brass instruments, music, or mail.

In the 18–19th centuries, post horns signaled the arrival of and cleared the way for mail coaches, like a modern-day siren. Used today as a symbol on postboxes (mailboxes) and by many European postal services, as seen featured in üè§ European Post Office.

name: Postbox
description:
A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with a letter in its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled after public postboxes in Japan. May also evoke postboxes in the United Kingdom.

Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Microsoft’s design was previously blue, after U.S. mail collection boxes.

name: Pot of Food
description:
A pot, as a casserole dish, filled with a warm and hearty beef or vegetable stew on most platforms. Generally used for eating and cooking (“a meal”), and commonly associated with soup or Japanese nabe.

Samsung’s design previously resembled a bowl of ramen or other noodle dish, with chopsticks.

name: Potable Water Symbol
description:
A symbol for potable (drinkable) water, usually shown with a faucet filling a drinking glass. Commonly used for various content concerning water, drinking, thirst, and dripping.

Some platforms, including Apple and WhatsApp, depict the emoji as an object while others feature a stylized, white faucet on a blue square, as a sign or icon of water that is safe to drink. Compare üö± Non-Potable Water, which indicates water that is not safe to drink.

Apple's design previously featured a blue symbol design, Microsoft's a cup filled with water.

name: Potato
description: A whole potato—such as a russet, used for baking, mashing, or frying—shown with a few eyes on its golden-brown skin. Not to be confused with the roasted sweet potato.

name: Potted Plant
description: A leafy green plant in pot. Plant type varies by platform.

name: Pouch
description: A small pouch, somewhere between the size of a handbag, and a purse.

name: Poultry Leg
description: A crispy brown leg (drumstick) of chicken, duck, turkey, or other poultry on the bone, as roasted at Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner or fried at fast-food restaurants.

name: Pouring Liquid
description:
A glass pouring liquid.

May be used to represent the literal act of pouring. May also be used to represent ritual libations or to honor the dead by pouring out a drink in a person's memory.

name: Pouting Cat Face
description:
A cartoon cat variant of üò° Pouting Face. Also resembles üò† Angry Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms. Sometimes used to represent the internet meme and celebrity Grumpy Cat.

Apple’s design previously displayed the face in profile, as did Twitter's. Microsoft's design previously more closely resembled the üòü Worried Face than the üò† Angry Face.

name: Pouting Face
description:
A red face with an angry expression: frowning mouth with eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward. Bears the same expression as üò† Angry Face on most platforms and may convey more intense degrees of anger, e.g., hate or rage.

Samsung’s design previously featured a yellow face with the üí¢ Anger Symbol on its forehead. Microsoft’s design previously featured a yellow face with a more hurt expression.

Not to be confused with üôé Person With Pouting Face. This emoji also has a cat variant, üòæ Pouting Cat Face.

name: Prayer Beads
description:
A string of beads, as used in prayer or meditation in many religious traditions. Generally depicted as red, wooden beads with a gold, decorative center bead and tassel.

Commonly used to represent various religious sentiments, jewelry, and magic.

Samsung previously featured a Latin cross, suggesting a Christian rosary, though now joins other vendor designs in resembling an Islamic misbaha or Buddhist mala.

name: Pregnant Man
description:
A pregnant man holding his round stomach. Sometimes used in jest to represent feeling too full after overeating, as in a "food baby."

Variants include ü´Ñ Pregnant Person and ü´É Pregnant Woman.

This emoji was approved to make the emoji keyboard more consistent and gender inclusive.

name: Pregnant Person
description:
A pregnant person holding their round stomach. Sometimes used in jest to represent feeling too full after overeating, as in a "food baby."

Variants include ü´Ñ Pregnant Woman and ü´É Pregnant Man.

This emoji was approved to make the emoji keyboard more consistent and gender inclusive.

name: Pregnant Woman
description:
A pregnant woman holding her round stomach. Sometimes used in jest to represent feeling too full after overeating, as in a "food baby."

Variants include ü´Ñ Pregnant Person and ü´É Pregnant Man.

Twelve modified versions of Apple's pregnant woman emoji design are featured in English artist Damien Hirst's design for the cover artwork of hip-hop artist Drake's 2021 album Certified Lover Boy.

name: Pretzel
description: The heart-shaped twist of a hard or soft golden-brown pretzel, seasoned with grains of salt. A snack commonly associated with Germany.

name: Prince
description:
Male royalty, intended as a gender pair for the princess emoji. Shown as a man with a crown.

Not a reference to the musician Prince, however the man singer emoji on WhatsApp does show a character that bears a heavy resemblance to this artist.

name: Princess
description: The face of a princess; a girl or woman wearing a small crown or tiara. Could also be used to represent a Queen or other royalty.

name: Printer
description:
A computer printer, as at a home office. Generally depicted as a grayish device with a power button and paper loaded in its tray, sometimes printing out a document. May be used for various content concerning printing, including as a Print icon, as well as for office work and technology more generally.

Not to be confused with üì† Fax Machine.

name: Probing Cane
description:
A white cane, used by some people who are blind or visually impaired. The cane has a black or gray handle with a wrist loop, a white middle section, and a red end with a white cap. This cane differs from a support cane and is sometimes called a probing cane.

üë©‍ü¶Ø Woman With Probing Cane and üë®‍ü¶Ø Man With Probing Cane are ZWJ sequences that use White Cane.

name: Public Address Loudspeaker
description: A loudspeaker used to make announcements in public areas such as schools, or sporting grounds.

name: Purple Heart
description:
A purple heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts. Frequently used on Twitter in reference to Korean boy band Bangtan Sonyeondan, more commonly known as BTS.

Previously shown as a pink heart in Android 4.4.

name: Purse
Pushpin
description:
A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. Depicted at a 45° angle with its red, flat head to the upper right.

Often used as an icon for Pinterest or metaphorically pinning content online. Not to be confused with üìç Round Pushpin, though their applications may overlap.

name: Put Litter in Its Place Symbol
description: A symbol showing a person putting¬†litter (rubbish) in the trash (rubbish bin). A more positive version of the Do Not Litter Symbol.

name: Rabbit
description:
A rabbit, a hoppy mammal with long ears. Depicted as a white, gray, or brown rabbit in full profile facing left with pink ears and a short tail, sitting on its long, hind legs or on all fours.

May be used in association with spring, Easter, magic, bunny ears, or various rabbit-based characters or expressions (e.g., going down the rabbit hole).

See also üê∞ Rabbit Face. One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.

Apple’s rabbit has red eyes, WhatsApp’s whiskers. Microsoft’s rabbit was previously brown, Facebook’s white.

name: Rabbit Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a rabbit, looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a gray and/or white rabbit face with upright ears and pink ears and nose, often with whiskers and a buck tooth.

Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied üêá rabbit. Also often used to represent the Easter Bunny.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

Microsoft’s rabbit face was previously pink-colored with one ear flopping down. Facebook’s rabbit face was previously gray-colored with both ears flopping down.

name: Raccoon
description:
A raccoon, a nocturnal mammal with a mask around its eyes. Generally depicted as a friendly, cartoon-styled, gray raccoon face looking straight ahead, with black-and-white markings around its eyes and pointed ears and cheeks.

Apple and WhatsApp’s designs feature a raccoon in full profile on all fours facing left with a striped, bushy tail.

name: Racing Car
description:
A racing car which appears as a formula one vehicle or rally car on most platforms. Generally displayed in red.

Apple's version of this emoji features the Swift (programming language) logo on the side.

In April 2024, WhatsApp updated their design as part of a partnership between the messaging platform and the Mercedes-Benz F1 team.

name: Racing Motorcycle
description: A¬†motorcycle, otherwise known as a motorbike used for sport/racing purposes. For a transport-based motorcycle, use a motor scooter.

name: Radio
description:
A classic portable radio, as used to listen to music, news, or sports. Depicted in various colors and styles with a speaker, antenna, dial, and knobs.

Commonly used for various content concerning radio, broadcasting, and music.

name: Radio Button
description:
A radio button user interface element, used in form fields with two or more choices. Differs from a checkbox, in that only one response can be selected.

This emoji generally shows the on/enabled state for the radio button, with a smaller circle inside a larger outer circle.

Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here.

name: Radioactive Sign
description:
A hazard symbol for radiation or radioactivity. May appear similar to a three-pronged fan at small sizes.

Generally displayed on an orange or yellow background.

name: Railway Car
description:
A railway (railroad) car (carriage) that is generally pulled along a railway line by a locomotive. Shown with a pantograph above the carriage on many platforms which makes it look more like a tram car.

Google’s artwork previously looked like a bus and Microsoft's older versions appeared similar to a minecart.

name: Railway Track
description:
A railway track shown from a first-person perspective, as though someone is driving a train or walking down the tracks a la Stand By Me.

The track is usually surrounded by foliage and trees, sometimes with clouds in the sky and mountains in the distance. Microsoft's design previously showed the track heading directly towards a large looming mountain.

name: Rainbow
description:
The colorful arc of a rainbow, as may appear after rain. Generally depicted as the left half of a full rainbow, showing six bands of color: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and violet.

Commonly used to express gay pride. Also commonly used to convey various feelings of love and happiness. See also üè≥Ô∏è‍üåà Rainbow Flag.

WhatsApp’s design shows the right arc of rainbow disappearing into a cloud. Facebook’s rainbow is displayed on a blue sky, as Apple, Samsung, and Twitter’s previously were. Google and Microsoft previously displayed full rainbow arcs with clouds.

name: Rainbow Flag
description:
A flag with six colors of the rainbow, generally including red, orange, yellow, green, blue and purple. Commonly used by the LGBT movement as a gay pride flag, or simply pride flag and seen at Pride events.

In February 2019 misinformation was spread about a so-called "anti-lgbt emoji" which can be created using a combining character to show a black and white glyph like üö´ on top of the rainbow flag. This is possible with any emoji on supported platforms, in the same way keycaps are combining characters.

name: Raised Back of Hand
description: A raised hand, showing the reverse side of the palm. May be paired with the forward-facing raised hand emoji.

name: Raised Fist
description:
A fist raised in the air that may be used as a celebratory gesture: the fist pump. Can also be used to represent zero items, due to a lack of any fingers being held up.

Sometimes used as a symbol of resistance or defiance. Variations with darker skin tone are commonly used to represent the #BlackLivesMatter movement.

name: Raised Hand
description: A hand held up showing its palm. May be used to mean stop, or as a high-five.

name: Raised Hand with Part Between Middle and Ring Fingers
description: A raised hand, with the fingers separated between the ring finger and the middle finger.

name: Ram
description:
A ram, a male sheep with large, spiraling horns. Generally depicted in full profile on all fours facing left with a thick, white fleece and light-brown horns.

Occasionally used to represent antelopes and related animals. Not to be confused with üêë Ewe, though their applications may overlap.

Often considered (in lieu of üêê Goat) one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Also often used to represent ‚ôà Aries (the Ram) in the Western zodiac.

WhatsApp and Facebook’s designs resemble a bighorn sheep, as Apple’s once did. Google's design previously had its eyes closed.

name: Rat
description:
A rat, a large rodent with a long tail, known to frequent big cities. Depicted in gray in full profile on all fours facing left, with pink ears, feet, and tail.

May be use for various metaphorical senses of rat. Not to be confused with üêÅ Mouse, which has white hair.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.

Google’s design was previously standing on its hind legs and facing forward with a buck tooth.

name: Razor
description:
A safety razor, depicted in various colors across platforms.

Previously shown as a straight razor by Microsoft, WhatsApp, and JoyPixels.

name: Receipt
description:
A white paper receipt, as proof of payment, and shown flat or curled. May be used for other financial documents (e.g., invoice, tax form). May also be used for the slang receipts, or "evidence” or “confirmation” of some feat or controversy.

Some vendors feature easter eggs. Apple’s design, for instance, displays the date of July 17 (World Emoji Day); items referencing its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign (misfits, square pegs, round holes); and a balance $0.00.

name: Recreational Vehicle
description:
A blue or green Sport Utility Vehicle or station wagon, often with a spare tire on the back. Commonly used as a generic blue or green car.

Sport Utility Vehicle or SUV is an emoji whose meaning was likely lost in translation as it moved from Japanese phone carriers to the Unicode Standard in 2010.

This emoji goes back to the late 1990s when it was included in Docomo's emoji set. In 2009, it appeared on a proposal as one of many symbols available on Japanese phones recommended to be encoded into the Unicode Standard. In that proposal, the symbol was referred to as a "recreational vehicle" or RV. The original Japanese emojis look more like station wagons or SUVs than RVs.

At various points, platforms including Google and Samsung showed this emoji as an RV, but ultimately the designs across platforms converged to a car that looks more like an SUV or station wagon. At a small scale this emoji is barely distinguishable from üöó Automobile on some platforms.

name: Red Apple
description: A classic red apple, shown with a stem and single, green leaf on major platforms. Commonly associated with doctors, teachers, and New York.

name: Red Gift Envelope
Registered Sign
description: A registered trademark symbol, a circled capital letter R for registered.

name: Relieved Face
description:
A yellow face with soft, closed eyes, raised eyebrows, and a slight smile. Facebook’s design features a slightly open mouth, as if sighing.

Conveys various pleasant feelings, including contentment, calm, peace, and relief. May also convey feelings of happiness or good-natured humor more generally.

Google and Microsoft previously included sweat beads. Not to be confused with üòî Pensive Face, which has similarly shaped eyes but in a sadder expression.

name: Reminder Ribbon
description: An awareness ribbon, worn to show support of a cause or group.

name: Restroom
description:
A restroom symbol, depicting a iconography of a man and woman. Used to indicate the location of public bathrooms / toilets / restrooms.

Used as an alternative to the water closet symbol.

name: Reversed Hand with Middle Finger Extended
description: A middle finger emoji, used in some western cultures as a rude or insulting gesture. The back of the hand is shown with the middle finger raised.

name: Revolving Hearts
description:
Hearts revolving around one or more other hearts. This emoji was originally animated on a number of Japanese devices.

Apple’s artwork for this emoji shows two hearts switching places, with a circular line simulating the action this would make. Google’s artwork previously displayed five hearts in a circle-like shape.

name: Rhinoceros
description:
A rhinoceros, a large mammal with one or two massive horns on its nose. Generally shown in light gray with two horns, depicted in full profile on all fours or as a rhinoceros head looking left.

Resembles the white or black rhinoceros.

Apple, Google, Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs feature the full animal, while Samsung and Twitter’s designs feature only the rhinoceros' head.

Facebook’s design previously featured just the rhinoceros' head, as did Google's.

name: Ribbon
description:
A pink or red ribbon, as tied into a bow on a gift or woman's hat.

Often used to indicate something is pretty, cute, or special, including on holidays. Also used of various content concerning baby girls and for its pink or red color more generally.

Google’s ribbon was previously orange, Facebook’s blue.

name: Rice Ball
description: A Japanese onigiri, a cone-shaped ball of white rice, a snack wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed.

name: Rice Cracker
description: A Japanese senbei, or rice cracker, wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed, a snack commonly enjoyed with green tea.

name: Right Anger Bubble
description: A form of speech balloon used with angular edges, used to denote angry speech in comics.

name: Right-Facing Fist
description: A fist pointing right, which may be used in conjunction with the left-facing fist to complete a fist-bump gesture.

name: Right-Pointing Magnifying Glass
description:
A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed right. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper right.

Associated with detectives and search or zoom icons on computers. Like üîç Magnifying Glass Titled Left, commonly used for various senses of searching, looking, inspecting, etc.

name: Rightwards Arrow with Hook
description: An arrow pointing to the right, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a forward icon in an email application.

name: Rightwards Hand
description:
An open right hand facing right, so as to show the back of the hand with the thumb on the top and the pinky on the bottom.

This emoji was developed along with ü´≤ Leftwards Hand to allow for the creation of ZWJ Sequences that depict ü§ù Handshake with two different skin tone modifiers applied, one to each hand.

name: Rightwards Pushing Hand
description:
A profile of an open hand pushing or positioned with the palm toward the right. 

May be used to show a hand pushing something away or to represent rejection of something in general. May also be used with with ü´∑ Leftwards Pushing Hand to show hands high fiving or holding, pressing, or squishing something.

name: Ring
description: A ring with displaying a gem stone of some kind on the top, most likely a diamond. This piece of jewellery is often associated with a proposal and subsequent engagement to be married.

name: Ring Buoy
description:
A round white and orange or red ring buoy with string laced through its perimeter. Also called a life preserver.

Maybe be used to talk about water, boats, and safety. May also be used metaphorically to talk about someone or something that saves.

name: Ringed Planet
description: A ringed planet that appears with various number of rings, tilt angles, and colors across platforms. This vaguely Saturn-like orb was proposed as a stand-alone planet emoji to represent all planets.

name: Roasted Sweet Potato
description:
A sweet potato depicted with textured purple, orange, or brown skin and sliced in half to show its golden-brown flesh. Sometimes called a yam, though they are unrelated. Not to be confused with the Potato.

Commonly roasted as a snack in East Asia during winter, much as squash and pumpkin are popular in the United States during fall/autumn. Used as an offering to the full moon in Japan during the Moon Viewing harvest festival.

name: Robot Face
description:
The head of a classic robot. Commonly depicted as a vintage, tin toy robot with circular eyes, a triangular nose, knobs for ears, a light and/or antennae atop its head, and a grill-like mouth similar to a grimace. Colors vary across platform, but its head is metallic on most platforms. 

May be used of topics concerning robotics, electronics, computer programming, futurism, and science fiction. It also enjoys a range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of weirdness and fun as well as alarm, surprise, and excitement, given its wide-eyed, teeth-gritting expression.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

name: Rock
description:
A large rock the size of a small rock. May be considered a boulder, a rock, a stone, a pebble, or a piece of dirt. The scale and meaning are context dependent.

The color is gray or brownish gray.

name: Rocket
description: A rocket being propelled into space. Sometimes used to indicate a fast increase, for instance when referring to stocks going to the moon üöÄ (rising quickly in price).

name: Roll of Paper
description:
A roll of paper, as toilet paper (toilet tissue). May also be a roll of kitchen/paper towels. Depicted at various angles, with a sheet unfurling.

Commonly used for toilet paper but may also be used for various content concerning toilets, going to the bathroom, bathrooms, cleaning, or paper more generally.

name: Rolled-Up Newspaper
description:
A newspaper rolled up and bound, as for delivery to a house. Generally positioned at a 45° angle. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.

See also üì∞ Newspaper.

name: Roller Coaster
description: A roller coaster in a theme park going down a dip in the ride. Three carriages can be seen with two people in each red carriage.

name: Roller Skate
description: A single vibrantly colored roller skate. Colors and styles vary across platform.

name: Rolling on the Floor Laughing
description:
A yellow face with a big grin and scrunched, X-shaped eyes, tilted on its side as if rolling on the floor laughing (the internet acronym ROFL). Sheds two tears and tilts right on most platforms. Often conveys hysterical laughter more intense than üòÇ Face With Tears of Joy.

Using shown tilted leftwards, though WhatsApp's design tilts to the right.

Microsoft's design previously featured a smiley with hands and feet.

name: Rooster
description:
A rooster (cock), a male chicken known for its cock-a-doodle-do. Depicted as a white or multicolored rooster standing on its legs in full profile facing left, with a red comb on its head and red wattle on its neck.

Not to be confused with üêî Chicken, though their applications overlap. See also üê£ Hatching Chick, üê§ Baby Chick, and üê• Front-Facing Baby Chick. Occasionally used as sexual slang.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.

Google’s rooster is brown with a green tail, Facebook’s brown with a blue tail. Google’s rooster was previously white, Microsoft’s yellow, Samsung’s looking straight ahead.

name: Rose
description:
A red rose. Depicted as a single, vertical red rose on a green stem.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such sentiments as love and romance. Also used as a symbol of socialism or as a red accent color.

Not to be confused with üå∑ Tulip, though their applications may overlap.

Samsung’s rose was previously pink.

name: Rosette
description:
A rosette, a stylized, flower-shaped decoration often presented as an award with a ribbon or (military) medal. Appears as a motif in ancient cultures. Generally depicted as a circular, yellow-and-orange flower.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a yellow accent color.

Not to be confused with üåº Blossom, though their applications may overlap.

WhatsApp's rosette is orange, white, and purple; Twitter's is purple and blue. Samsung's was previously pink. A non-emoji Unicode character üè∂ Black Rosette was once shown as an emoji on LG phones.

name: Round Pushpin
description:
A pushpin, as used to indicate a location on a map. Generally depicted as an upright pin with a red, round head.

Commonly used to indicate locations and notably featured in the Pushpin Emoji Detour and Distance Between memes on Twitter. Also used unofficially as an icon for Pinterest or Google Maps.

Facebook’s pin is oriented at a 45° angle, as were previous designs on several other platforms.

Not to be confused with üìå Pushpin, though their applications may overlap.

name: Rowboat
description: A small rowboat suitable for a small number of people. Couples or families sometimes hire these as an activity on calm waters.

name: Rugby Football
description:
The oval-shaped ball used in the game of rugby. Varies slightly in shape in the two main versions of the game: rugby union and rugby league.

The appearance of this emoji varies, with a brown leather appearance in Apple and Google’s imagery, but a more popular white-with-highlight color in Twitter’s design.

name: Runner
description:
A person running, with a large stride and arms outstretched. May be wearing a running shirt.

This emoji does not specify a gender, but is shown as a man on most platforms. See also: üèÉ‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman Running or üèÉ‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man Running.

name: Running Shirt with Sash
description: A singlet or running shirt. Shown with a sash.

name: Safety Pin
description:
A silver safety pin or clip, as used to fasten fabric. Generally shown clasped at a 45° angle, with its spring at the lower left.

May be used for various content concerning arts, crafts, and sewing. Not to be confused with üìé Paperclip.

name: Safety Vest
description:
An orange safety vest with reflective lines across the chest and over the shoulders.

Used in the ZWJ sequence üêï‍ü¶∫ Service Dog, which was approved at the same time. A safety vest can also be seen in the designs of üë∑ Construction Worker on multiple platforms.

name: Sagittarius
description: The Sagittarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents an Archer.

name: Sailboat
description:
A sailboat, otherwise known as a sailing boat or yacht.  Uses wind as the source of propulsion to move around a body of water.

The color of the sails in this emoji vary by platform, with vendors displaying blue sails, orange sails, or a mix of red, yellow, orange, blue or white.

name: Sake Bottle and Cup
description: Japanese sake, an alcoholic beverage made from rice. Shown as a sake set with a carafe (tokkuri) and drinking cup (choko). Most platforms show a cream colored sake set with a blue or red stripe motif. Samsung's design used to show the Japanese script for 'sake' in red along the side of the carafe.

name: Salt Shaker
description: A clear glass shaker of salt with a silver cap, as paired with pepper to season food when eating at a restaurant.

name: Saluting Face
description:
A yellow face with its right hand saluting. Used as a sign of respect.

The expression of the face of this emoji can vary across platforms, with some designs featuring a neutral face while others are shown smiling to various degrees. 

Apple and Huewai's designs notably only display half a face, likely to make the saluting hand more prominent when this emoji is viewed in smaller sizes.

This emoji went viral across Twitter in late 2022 following the news that the platform would be dramatically reducing its staff numbers as part of a company-wide restructuring following its acquisition by Elon Musk. Learn more here.

name: Sandwich
description: A sandwich, as eaten at lunch, made with lettuce, tomato, and cheese on slices of white or wheat bread. Apple, Google, and WhatsApp add a deli meat that resembles ham.

name: Santa Claus
description: This version of the  Santa Claus emoji has the  Dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Black Skin Tone on supported platforms.  http://emojipedia.org/father-christmas-type-6/

name: Santa Claus
description: This version of the  Santa Claus emoji has the  Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms.  http://emojipedia.org/father-christmas-type-1-2/

name: Santa Claus
description: This version of the  Santa Claus emoji has the  Medium-dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Dark Brown Skin Tone on supported http://emojipedia.org/father-christmas-type-5/

name: Santa Claus
description: This version of the  Santa Claus emoji has the  Medium-light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Cream White Skin Tone on support http://emojipedia.org/father-christmas-type-3/

name: Santa Claus
description: This version of the  Santa Claus emoji has the  Medium Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Moderate Brown Skin Tone on supported  http://emojipedia.org/father-christmas-type-4/

name: Sari
description:
A brightly colored sari draped in different ways across platforms. Sometimes used to mean a dress in general.

This emoji is sometimes used playfully in English to stand in for the word 'sorry.'

name: Satellite
description: A satellite which orbits the earth, and is generally used for communications, weather, and GPS.

name: Satellite Antenna
description:
A dish antenna, as used to send or receive information to or from a communication satellite—or üëΩ Extraterrestrial Life. Generally depicted as a mounted, metal dish with its antenna positioned at 45° to the upper right.

Commonly used to represent satellite television, radio, and internet, as well as broadcasting, streaming, cellular, and wireless services or technologies. May also represent various concepts of signals and transmission.

Several platforms, including Microsoft and Twitter, feature curved, radiating lines, as if transmitting data.

name: Sauropod
description:
A sauropod, a massive, plant-eating dinosaur with a long neck and tail. Depicted as a blue, gray, or green sauropod, as a brachiosaurus, apatosaurus/brontosaurus, or diplodocus. Shown in full profile on all fours facing left.

May be used to represent various dinosaurs. See also ü¶ñ T-Rex.

May also be used to call a person a dinosaur, i.e. imply that they are old-fashioned or out-of-touch with modern sentiments.

Apple, Google and Samsung's sauropods resemble a brachiosaurus. Samsung’s sauropod was previously green, Facebook’s previously displayed only a green head.

name: Saxophone
description: A saxophone, a single-reed woodwind instrument instrument usually made of brass.

name: Scales
description:
A balance scale, as historically used to measure weight. A symbol of justice, as held by Lady Justice, and of the zodiac sign of Libra, the Scales. Depicted as two silver or gold pans suspended from a beam and supported on a base.

Commonly used for various content concerning law and justice as well as various senses of balance and weight.

Samsung’s design previously featured a stylized, white balance scale on a green square, as an icon or symbol of legal matters or institutions.

name: Scarf
description: A knitted wool scarf, generally worn for warmth. Colored red across most emoji design vendors.

name: School
description:
A school building with multiple storeys, and a clock on the front. A place that children or teenagers attend for their education.

This emoji tends to spike in use in September when many Northern Hemisphere countries' schools reopen after their summer holidays.

Previously displayed on Windows as a collection of school-related items: an apple, ruler, and pencil.

name: School Satchel
description: A school bag Emoji (also called a satchel) used by children attending school to carry books, lunch, and other personal belongings.

name: Scientist
description: A person who is studying or has expert knowledge of one or more of the natural or physical sciences. Generally depicted wearing safety goggles and a white lab coat while holding a test tube or beaker filled with colorful liquid.

name: Scooter
description: A non-motorized scooter, with two wheels and handles.

name: Scorpion
description:
A scorpion, an arachnid with lobster-like pincers and a stinging tail. Depicted as a light-brown scorpion from above, often facing left, with its pincers and curving stinger raised. Shown with six or, accurately, eight legs in addition to its pincers.

Often used to represent ‚ôè Scorpio in the Western zodiac.

WhatsApp’s scorpion is reddish in color.

name: Scorpius
description: The¬†Scorpius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Scorpion.

name: Screwdriver
description:
A silver Phillips-head or slotted-head screwdriver with a colorful handle. Most platforms show a red handle, though Apple's design has a green handle. Used to represent construction, building, carpentry, renovation, or tools in general.

Sometimes used in phrases with 'screw' in them like screw you or have a screw loose. Can also be used in sexual contexts due to the informal meaning of 'screw': "to have sex."

name: Scroll
Seal
description:
A gray seal with dark eyes and a dark nose. Most platforms feature a design with whiskers.

Can be used to talk about seals, marine life, or cute animals in general. May also be used in phrases with 'sealed' as in sealed with a kiss, my lips are sealed, or signed, sealed, and delivered.

name: Seat
description:
A seat, which could refer to any form of place to sit, with the distinction that a seat is generally fixed, and is not a chair which can be moved.

This emoji is intended to be a seat on some form of mass-transit, such as on an airplane, train or bus. Google previously displayed this as an orange wooden chair.

name: Second Place Medal
description: A silver medal, given to the person or team who comes second in a competitive sporting event such as a race.

name: See-No-Evil Monkey
description:
The see no evil monkey, called Mizaru (Japanese for “see not”), one of the Three Wise Monkeys. Depicted as the brown üêµ Monkey Face with hands covering its eyes.

The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil, frequently interpreted as a call for discretion or willful ignorance.

Often used as a playful way to convey a laughing, disbelieving, cringing I can’t believe what I’m seeing! or I can’t bear to look!

See also üôâ Hear-No-Evil Monkey and üôä Speak-No-Evil Monkey.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Seedling
description:
A seedling, or a young plant, as a newly sprouted tree. Depicted as a tiny, light-green plant with a short stem and two leaves. Often shown freshly sprung from a small mound of brown earth.

May be used for various content concerning plant life. May also be used as a symbol of spring or representation of various types of new growth.

Not to be confused with üåø Herb, though their applications may overlap.

Facebook’s seedling previously had three leaves.

name: Selfie
description: A mobile phone held up to take a selfie (photo of the person holding the phone or camera). Generally represented as a disembodied arm holding a mobile phone.

name: Serious Face with Symbols Covering Mouth
description:
An angry-red face with a black bar and white grawlixes covering its mouth, indicating it's swearing or being vulgar. Grawlixes are typographical symbols (e.g., @#$%&!) representing swear words or obscenities. Often used to convey an outburst of anger, frustration, or rage.

Most platforms feature the same eyes as on their üò† Angry Face and üò° Enraged Face.

name: Service Dog
description: A service animal displayed with a safety vest and lead. Differs from the guide dog as this animal is intended for detection of seizures or other “hidden disabilities”, according to the proposal from Apple.

name: Sewing Needle
description:
A threaded silver needle. Color of thread varies from platform to platform.

Can be used to talk about crafts including embroidery, quilting, or sewing in general. Can also be used in medical contexts to talk about stitches.

Used metaphorically at the beginning of a thread, or series of connected posts by one person, on social media.

name: Shaking Face
description:
A face that appears to be shaking from side to side with its eyes and mouth open wide.

This emoji finds its origins in the comic book and cartoon trope of a shaking face. It can be used to express shaking from external forces like earthquakes, loud noises, or dinosaurs walking nearby. It can also be used to express shaking caused by strong emotions such as shock, fear, confusion, disbelief, anticipation, and excitement. Additionally it can represent dizziness, double takes, or double vision.

name: Shallow Pan of Food
description:
A flat, shallow, black pan with side handles, containing saffron-colored rice, vegetables, a leg of poultry, and/or shrimp and lemon slices. Commonly associated with paella, a traditional dish from Spain. May be used for eating, cooking, dining, and meals more generally.

Apple's version of this emoji is considered to be representative of the traditional ingredients from Valencia. Samsung previously displayed this emoji as a Korean hot pot.

name: Shamrock
description:
A shamrock, a clover-like plant. Depicted as a bright green sprig with three, heart-shaped leaves.

An emblem of Ireland and symbol of St. Patrick, said to use the shamrock to explain the Christian concept of the Holy Trinity. Commonly used on St. Patrick’s Day and in association with Irish culture and heritage.

Not to be confused with üçÄ Four Leaf Clover, though their applications may overlap.

name: Shark
description:
A shark, a large, stealthy fish with many teeth. Generally depicted as a gray shark in full profile facing left, as a tiger, bull, or great white shark hunting in the water. Shown with a white underside and three gills, its pointed nose and teeth-lined mouth curving down to a sharp dorsal fin and long, pointed tail.

Not to be confused with üê¨ Dolphin.

name: Shaved Ice
description: A mound of shaved ice (snow cone) served in a dessert bowl with a short spoon, flavored with a cherry-red syrup on many platforms. Associated with Hawaiian shave ice or Japanese kakigori.

name: Sheep
description:
A ewe, or female sheep raised for its wool, meat, and milk and without the spiraling horns of a ram. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left with a thick, white fleece and black, gray, or white skin.

Not to be confused with üêè Ram, though their applications may overlap.

Often considered (in lieu of üêê Goat) one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.

Apple and Google’s designs previously depicted a ram. Samsung and Facebook’s designs previously featured only a ewe face.

name: Shield
description:
A shield, as blocks swords in close combat. Color and style varies across platforms, but generally depicted in a kite shape with a metal border and simple pattern.

Commonly used to represent various content concerning battle, defense, security, and protection.

Apple and Microsoft’s designs feature a red and white sawtooth pattern, Facebook and WhatsApp’s blue and white checkers.

May be paired with (or fending off) ‚öîÔ∏è Crossed Swords or üó°Ô∏è Dagger. Not to be confused with üî∞ Japanese Symbol for Beginner.

name: Shinto Shrine
description:
A shrine used for the Japanese Shinto religion. This emoji generally displays the torii, which is the gate to the Shinto Shrine. The torii is generally a red colored structure, with a curved roof section above two posts.

This icon is used on maps in Japan to represent the location of a Shinto Shrine, similar to how the hot springs emoji is the icon used on Japanese maps to show the location of an onsen.

name: Ship
description: A large ship, used for transport of people or cargo across the ocean. May be a cruise ship, commonly found around tropical locations.

name: Shocked Face with Exploding Head
description:
A yellow face with an open mouth, the top of its head exploding in the shape of a brain-like mushroom cloud. A visual form of the expression mind blown, it may represent such emotions as shock, awe, amazement, and disbelief.

Apple’s design features the same expression as its üò¶ Frowning Face With Open Mouth.

name: Shooting Star
description:
A stylized representation of a shooting star, a small, fast meteor that burns up in the atmosphere. Generally depicted as a gold, five-point star trailing yellow motion lines against a night sky, as if moving down to the left.

May be used for astronomical stars and other content concerning space. Also may be used for flair or flourish. Sometimes used as a visual reference to NBC’s More You Know public service announcement, popular in the 1990s and featuring a shooting star logo.

Not to be confused with üí´ Dizzy, ‚≠ê Star, üåü Glowing Star, or ‚ú® Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.

Google’s star was previously trailed, without backdrop, by yellow lines, though these lines were blue in an even earlier design. Microsoft’s star was also previously trailed, without backdrop, by blue lines, though they were yellow before that.

name: Shopping Bags
description:
Two colorful shopping bags, as contain consumer items bought at a department store. Depicted as gift bags in various bright colors, patterns, sizes, and positions across platforms. Apple's design, for instance, features a pink bag with light-pink dots in front of a gold bag with yellow stripes.

Commonly used for various content concerning retail shopping, stores, goods, and gifts or presents. May also convey a sense of indulgence or self-care, à la retail therapy.

Microsoft’s design previously included tissue paper, and was depicted as a bag of groceries prior to that.

name: Shopping Trolley
description: A metal shopping cart that you might find in a supermarket or grocery store.

name: Shortcake
description: A slice of strawberry shortcake, layered with whipped cream and topped with a whole strawberry. Like the Birthday Cake, may be used to represent birthday celebrations or cake in general.

name: Shorts
description:
Shorts or swimming trunks. This emoji is shown in different colors and styles across platforms. Most platforms depict this emoji in a casual sporty style.

Related emojis include üëô Bikini, ü©≤ Briefs, and ü©± One-Piece Swimsuit.

name: Shower
description:
A silver shower head, streaming water to the left. Pressure level varies across platforms. üßº Soap not provided.

Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and water. Shower heads are also featured in üõÅ Bathtub and üõÄ Person Taking a Bath.

name: Shrimp
description:
A shrimp (prawn), a small crustacean with a long tail. Generally depicted as a reddish-orange shrimp (as cooked) in full profile facing left, with tiny eyes, many limbs, and its long antennae curling back as its long tail curls in.

May be consumed in the form of üç§ Fried Shrimp or ü•ò Shallow Pan of Food. Often used to represent seafood.

The antennae of Apple’s shrimp curls under its body. The body of Facebook’s shrimp is straight. Google and Samsung’s shrimp previously faced right.

name: Shrug
Sign of the Horns
description: A "rock on" hand gesture raising the pinky and index fingers on one hand, which a variety of other meanings.

name: Silhouette of Japan
description: Shows a map of the country of Japan, which is the only country to have its own emoji map. Other countries can be found on the various globe emojis, or the world map emoji.

name: Singer
description:
A singer or rock star generally displayed with a microphone, and sometimes musical notes.

iOS and Android display this emoji as a Bowie-esque figure while WhatsApp appears heavily inspired by Prince.

name: Six Pointed Star with Middle Dot
description: A star with six points, and a dot in the center. Similar to the Star of David emoji.

name: Skateboard
description:
A skateboard emoji, usually showing the board from the top.

Twitter's design shows the under-side of the board, as did a previous Microsoft design.

Emojipedia's sample image was modelled after Tony Hawk's skateboard.

name: Ski and Ski Boot
description:
A pair of skis which are shown on some platforms alongside ski poles and/or ski boots. The color and design of the skis varies by platform, with some versions also showing the skis moving at speed.

Distinct from the skier emoji which features a person skiing.

name: Skier
description:
A person downhill-skiiing. Displayed with poles and skis, generally wearing a mask.

Platforms vary in display of scarf, helmet, and color of clothing. No gendered options are provided for this emoji. Skin tones support is not recommended for this emoji, but this is supported by some platforms.

name: Skull
description:
A whitish-gray, cartoon-styled human skull with large, black eye sockets. Commonly expresses figurative death, e.g., dying from extreme laughter, frustration, or affection.

Popular around Halloween. Not to be confused with ‚ò†Ô∏è Skull and Crossbones, though their applications may overlap.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

name: Skull and Crossbones
description:
A cartoon human skull atop an X-shaped pair of bones, as on a pirate flag or poison symbol. Samsung’s design previously displayed a skull and crossbones on a yellow triangle, indicating a hazardous material.

May represent various ideas of death or danger, e.g., dying from laughter or killing it with great skill. May also represent various pirate characters or mascots.

Popular around Halloween. Not to be confused with üíÄ Skull, though their applications may overlap.

name: Skunk
description:
A skunk, a bushy-tailed mammal that sprays a foul odor when threatened. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with black hair and its distinctive white stripe running from its head down to a curled-up tail.

Google’s original skunk design bore a humorously haughty air.

name: Sled
description: A sled, otherwise known as a toboggan or sledge.

name: Sleeping Accommodation
description:
A bed with a gender-unspecified person sleeping in it, as at a house, hotel, hostel, or other sleeping accommodation. Used especially for various content concerning sleeping as well as beds, furniture, housing, relaxing, and other bedroom activities.

Shown with a headboard at the left and footboard with a person under the covers, head on the pillow. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets.

The appearance of the person varies. Apple and Facebook's designs show only the hair of the sleeper, Apple's black and Facebook's brown and tousled. Other major vendors show the head of the sleeper in default yellow with short, brown or blonde hair. Skin tone support is not recommended for this emoji, though it is supported on some platforms.

Vendors implement the same style of bed as for their üõèÔ∏è Bed, but with a sleeper in it.

name: Sleeping Face
description:
A yellow face with eyes closed and mouth letting out three, cartoon-styled Zzz’s overhead to indicate it's sound asleep. The Zzz’s appear blue or purple across most platforms. May also represent boredom (slang, snooze).

Generally used instead of üò™ Sleepy Face to convey sleep or sleepiness.

name: Sleeping Symbol
description: A series of three Zs making a Zzz. Represents sleeping, snoring, dreaming, or any sleep-related state. Can also be used in some contexts to represent something that is boring.

name: Sleepy Face
description:
A yellow face with closed eyes, mouth slightly open, and a blue snot bubble coming from its nose. Snot bubbles indicate a character is tired or sleeping in anime or manga. Not to be confused with üò¥ Sleeping Face 

While sometimes used to convey sadness, dissastification, or illness, Sleepy Face is also not to be confused with üò¢ Crying Face, üò• Sad but Relieved Face, or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets. Samsung’s design previously featured two, cartoon-styled, sleeping-symbol Zz’s overhead.

A previous Microsoft design appeared similar to üòå Relieved Face.

name: Sleuth or Spy
description: An undercover investigator, wearing a hat, and sometimes using a magnifying glass to closely inspect evidence. This emoji did not originally recommend emoji modifiers, but a proposal was created to address this.

name: Slice of Pizza
description: A slice of pepperoni pizza, previously also topped with black olives on Google. WhatsApp adds green pepper, Samsung white onion.

name: Slightly Frowning Face
description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a slight frown. Often conveys a mild degree of concern, disappointment, or sadness, but usually less intensely than ‚òπÔ∏è Frowning Face.

Samsung and Facebook previously included eyebrows.

name: Slightly Smiling Face
description: A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a thin, closed smile. Conveys a wide range of positive, happy, and friendly sentiments. Its tone can also be patronizing, passive-aggressive, or ironic, as if saying This is fine when it’s really not.

name: Slot Machine
description: A gambling machine generally found in casinos. Shows three wheels with a lever to the side. Most platforms display three 7 digits on this emoji.

name: Sloth
description: A sloth, the slow-moving, tree-dwelling mammal. Depicted as a light-brown sloth with a wide, whitish, masked face hanging from a tree branch, facing left or right. Generally shown as a three-toed sloth.

name: Small Airplane
description: A light aircraft which is shown with propellers on some platforms.

name: Small Blue Diamond
description:
A small version of the large blue diamond emoji.

Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here.

name: Small Orange Diamond
description: A small version of the large orange diamond emoji.

name: Smiling Cat Face with Heart-Shaped Eyes
description: A cartoon cat variant of üòç Smiling Face With Heart-Eyes. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Smiling Cat Face with Open Mouth
description: A cartoon cat variant of üòÄ Grinning Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Smiling Face with Halo
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes, closed smile, and halo, usually blue, overhead. Often represents angels, prayers, and blessings. May also convey angelic behavior, e.g., doing good deeds. See also üëº Baby Angel.

Several platforms, including Apple, feature an expression similar to their üòä Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes.

name: Smiling Face with Heart-Shaped Eyes
description:
A yellow face with an open smile, sometimes showing teeth, and red, cartoon-styled hearts for eyes. Often conveys enthusiastic feelings of love, infatuation, and adoration, e.g., I love/am in love with this person or thing.

This emoji has a cat variant, üòª Smiling Cat Face With Heart-Eyes.

name: Smiling Face with Horns
description:
A face, usually purple, with devil horns, a wide grin, and eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward in the same manner as üò† Angry Face on most platforms. Google’s design is red and Facebook’s has black horns and green eyes.

Commonly used to convey mischief, naughtiness, and excitement or excellence (slang, bad or wicked). May also represent devils or devilish behavior, especially around Halloween. More playful and suggestive than its impish counterpart, üëø Angry Face With Horns.

Google and Samsung previously depicted orangish-red characters, with Google once featuring a frown and Samsung a sharp snaggletooth.

name: Smiling Face with Open Mouth
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth and tongue on some platforms. Often conveys general happiness and good-natured amusement.

Similar to üòÄ Grinning Face but with taller, more excited eyes.

name: Smiling Face with Open Mouth and Cold Sweat
description: Has the same grin and eyes as üòÑ Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes but with a single, blue bead of sweat, usually over its left eye. Intended to depict nerves or discomfort but commonly used to express a close call, as if saying Whew! and wiping sweat from the forehead.

name: Smiling Face with Open Mouth and Smiling Eyes
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth and tongue on some platforms. Often conveys general happiness and good-natured amusement.

Similar to üòÄ Grinning Face and üòÉ Grinning Face With Big Eyes, but with warmer, less excited eyes.

This emoji has a cat variant, üò∏ Grinning Cat Face With Smiling Eyes.

name: Smiling Face with Open Mouth and Tightly-Closed Eyes
description:
A yellow face with a broad, open smile and scrunched, X-shaped eyes. Often conveys excitement or hearty laughter.

Similar to üòÄ Grinning Face but with eyes that might say Squee! or Awesome! An emoji form of the >< or xD emoticons.

name: Smiling Face with Smiling Eyes
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, closed smile turning up to rosy cheeks. Often expresses genuine happiness and warm, positive feelings.

An emoji form of the ^^ emoticon.

On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you message that person often but they aren't your #1 Best Friend.

name: Smiling Face with Smiling Eyes and Hand Covering Mouth
description:
A yellow face with a hand covering its mouth. Displays most often with smiling eyes and/or blushing cheeks, suggesting coy laughter or embarrassment, as if cheekily saying Oops! 

Prior to the release of iOS 15.4 in March 2022, Apple's design featured simple, open eyes, suggesting someone gasping Oh my! in serious surprise, shock, concern, or apology. This same update assigned Apple's original ü§≠ design to Emoji 14.0's new ü´¢ Face with Open Eyes and Hand Over Mouth emoji.

May be used to similar effect as üôä Speak-No-Evil Monkey. See also ü§ê Zipper-Mouth Face. Joins ü§ó Hugging Face, ü§î Thinking Face, and ü§´ Shushing Face as one of the few smileys featuring hands.

Facebook's design previously featured open eyes, though an earlier version had smiling eyes like those in the vendor's current design.

name: Smiling Face with Smiling Eyes and Three Hearts
description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes, a closed smile, rosy cheeks, and several hearts floating around its head. Expresses a range of happy, affectionate feelings, especially being in love. The placement of the hearts varies slightly by platform.

Apple's design features the same expression as its ‚ò∫Ô∏è Smiling Face emoji design.

name: Smiling Face with Sunglasses
description:
A yellow face with a broad, closed smile wearing black sunglasses, as if a pair of classic Wayfarers. Often used to convey the slang sense of cool. May also express a confident, carefree attitude or that something is excellent.

ü§ì Nerd Face wears similarly shaped eyeglasses.

On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you have best friends in common with this person.

name: Smiling Face with Tear
description:
A yellow face with open eyes, a thin closed-mouth smile, and a single tear falling from one of its eyes. Can be used to express a wide range of emotions and expressions including gratitude, tender happiness, an attempt to look happy when actually sad, or smiling through pain. Can also be a response to something that is bittersweet.

This emoji and üôÇ Slightly Smiling Face have a similar smile, and üò¢ Crying Face and üòø Crying Cat have a similar lone tear. Not to be confused with üòÇ Face with Tears of Joy, which has a wide toothy grin and tears coming from both eyes.

name: Smirking Face
description:
A yellow face with a sly, smug, mischievous, or suggestive facial expression. It features a half-smile, raised eyebrows, and eyes looking to the side. Often used to convey flirtation or sexual innuendo.

Not to be confused with üòí Unamused Face, which has similar eyes but a pouting mouth. This emoji has a cat variant, üòº Cat Face With Wry Smile.

On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that this person snaps you frequently but you do not often snap them in return.

name: Smoking Symbol
description:
A lit, filtered cigarette, shown burning at different directions. Commonly used to represent various forms of smoking (e.g., tobacco, marijuana, vaping) as well as metaphorical senses of smoking.

Originally intended as a sign for a designated smoking area, as contrasted to üö≠ No Smoking Symbol. This is illustrated in Samsung’s previous design of a stylized, white cigarette on a blue background.

name: Snail
description:
A snail, a slow-moving, snail-like mollusk in a spiraling shell. Generally depicted as a brown snail in full profile facing left or right, with a brown, textured shell and tentacle-like eyes.

May be used to represent a slug and various senses of slow.

Twitter’s snail has a purple body and yellow shell. Microsoft’s snail previously had a green body.

name: Snake
description:
A snake, a slithering reptile without limbs. Generally depicted as a yellowish-green snake facing left, with a long, coiled body and flicking a red, forked tongue.

May be used for various metaphorical senses of snake.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. May also be used in association with ‚õé Ophiuchus, the Serpent-Bearer, sometimes considered a 13th sign of the Western zodiac.

Samsung’s snake was previously facing forward.

name: Sneezing Face
description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes sneezing or blowing its nose into a white tissue, as if from a cold or allergies. Often depicted with a crumpled-looking mouth.

May also represent someone in an emotional state wiping away tears, as at a wedding.

name: Snow Capped Mountain
description: A mountain with snow resting at higher altitudes. Similar in appearance to the Mount Fuji emoji.

name: Snowboarder
description: A person snowboarding downhill at a ski resort. Wearing clothing designed for cold climates.

name: Snowflake
description:
The unique, feathery ice crystal of a snowflake. Depicted as a bluish-white snowflake with six intricate symmetrical branches.

Like üå®Ô∏è Cloud With Snow, may be used as a weather icon to represent a snowstorm or a cold, snowy day. May also be used for various content concerning wintertime, cold climates, and winter activity, such as skiing.

Sometimes used as an insult to call a person weak and oversensitive.

name: Snowman
description:
A classic snowman, as Frosty the Snowman, with snowflakes falling on it. Depicted as a snowman, facing forward, made from two or three large snowballs and stick arms, dressed with a top hat, a carrot nose, coal eyes, and two or three buttons on its torso. Sometimes shown with a smile and a red scarf.

Often used for various content concerning winter fun and Christmastime.

Vendors implement the same figure for their ‚õÑ Snowman Without Snow, which does not have snowflakes.

Google’s snowman previously wore green gloves, while Samsung's design previously lacked a hat.

This snowman predates Unicode emoji support, which explains why it may display as the black-and-white outline of a snowman.

name: Snowman Without Snow
description:
A classic snowman, as Frosty the Snowman. Depicted as a snowman, facing forward, made from two or three large snowballs and stick arms, dressed with a top hat, a carrot nose, coal eyes, and two or three buttons on its torso. Sometimes shown with a smile and a red scarf.

Often used for various content concerning winter fun and Christmastime.

Vendors implement the same figure for their ‚òÉÔ∏è Snowman, but which has snowflakes falling on it.

Google’s snowman is wearing green gloves, though its snowman previously lacked any attire. Samsung's previously lacked a hat.

name: Soccer Ball
description: A round, black and white ball used in the game of soccer, which is known as football in much of the world. See also: emojis for the World Cup.

name: Socks
description:
A pair of socks, generally used to keep one's feet warm and protected.

Generally depicted as two matching socks with a block color and one or more lines around where the socks would cover the wearer's ankles.

JoyPixel's design previously featured a üí© Pile of Poo emoji pattern.

name: Soft Ice Cream
description: A swirl of soft-serve ice cream atop a wafer-style cone, white or cream-colored, as vanilla, on most platforms. Facebook’s design suggests strawberry. May be used more generally for ice cream, frozen yogurt, and frozen treats.

name: Softball
description: A softball, which is differentiated from a baseball by size (it is larger, though hard to tell in emoji form) and color (yellow, not white).

name: Soon with Rightwards Arrow Above
description: The word "soon" with an arrow above it, pointing to the right.

name: South East Arrow
description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-right, or south-east direction.

name: South West Arrow
description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-left, or south-west direction.

name: Spaghetti
description: A plate of Italian spaghetti with tomato sauce, as a bolognese, with a fork twirling its long, thin noodles. Garnished with a green herb, as parsley, on some platforms.

name: Sparkle
description:
Often used as a decorative bullet-point, the sparkle has both a ‚ùáÔ∏é text and ‚ùáÔ∏è emoji presentation available on most platforms.

Like with the ‚ú® Sparkles emoji, an icon similar to the four-point star design used to represent this emoji by several vendors (e.g. Apple, Microsoft) is often used within tech platforms to represent a feature that utilizes artificial intelligence.

name: Sparkles
description:
The glittering flashes of sparkles. One of the world's most popular emojis, it is generally depicted as a cluster of three, yellow four-point stars, with one large sparkle and two small ones to its left or right.

Commonly used to indicate various positive sentiments, including love, happiness, beauty, gratitude, and excitement, as well as newness or cleanliness.

May also be used as a form of ‚ú®emphasis‚ú® or to convey sarcastic or mocking tones.

As of late 2023, an icon similar to the sparkles emoji is also often used within tech platforms to represent a feature that utilizes artificial intelligence.

Both Microsoft and Twitter’s sparkles were previously multicolored, while Samsung’s sparkles were previously depicted on a night sky, suggesting firework sparklers. 

Twitter's mobile app uses ‚ú® Sparkles as a button users can tap to toggle between latest and top tweets on their timeline.

Similar emojis with less implied meaning include ‚≠ê Star, üåü Glowing Star, and üí´ Dizzy.

name: Sparkling Heart
description:
A pink love heart with stars around it, making it look like it is sparkling or shimmering.
