This emoji tends to spike in popularity on Valentine's Day.

name: Speak-No-Evil Monkey
description:
The speak no evil monkey, called Iwazaru (Japanese for “say not”), one of the Three Wise Monkeys. Depicted as the brown üêµ Monkey Face with hands covering its mouth.

The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil, frequently interpreted as a call for discretion or willful ignorance.

Often used as a playful way to convey I can’t believe what I just said!, express a mischievous Oops!, or communicate a secret-keeping I won’t say a word. May be used to similar effect as ü§≠ Face With Hand Over Mouth or ü§ê Zipper Mouth.

See also üôà See-No-Evil Monkey and üôâ Hear-No-Evil Monkey.

This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.

name: Speaker
description: A speaker cone displayed without any sound waves.

name: Speaker with Cancellation Stroke
description: A speaker with a red line through it, indicating muted volume or silencing of audio.

name: Speaker with One Sound Wave
description:
A speaker cone displayed with one sound wave, generally used as an icon to indicate the decreasing of volume on a phone or computer.

Previously displayed with two sound waves on Android, instead of one.

name: Speaker with Three Sound Waves
description:
A speaker cone displayed with three sound waves, generally used as an icon to indicate the increasing of volume on a phone or computer.

Used by the Google Chrome browser to indicate which of your browser windows is playing sound.

name: Speaking Head in Silhouette
description: The silhouette of a person speaking. Faces left-to-right, with lines demonstrating speech being expelled. Sometimes used in the context of shouting or mansplaining.

name: Speech Balloon
description: A cartoon-style balloon used to represent spoken word in comics. Sometimes  used in communication apps to indicate that another person is typing a message.

name: Speedboat
description: A motorized speedboat used for recreation on lakes, or¬†other bodies of water.

name: Spider
description:
A spider, an eight-legged arachnid that spins a web. Depicted as a common black spider, as a house spider or funnel-web spider, often shown from above with its large abdomen oriented at the bottom.

See also üï∏Ô∏è Spider Web. Commonly used during Halloween and to represent the superhero Spider-Man.

Facebook’s spider is facing left. Google's spider was previously upside down, suspended from a thread, though now is facing left. Microsoft’s spider was previously a black widow, while Samsung’s was brown.

name: Spider Web
description:
A classic spider web (cobweb), as spun by a üï∑Ô∏è Spider to catch prey. Depicted as a white, symmetrical, wheel-shaped web, as an orb web, with six or eight equal sectors.

Commonly used during Halloween, to represent the superhero Spider-Man, or for a metaphorical web, net, or network. Not to be confused with ‚ùÑÔ∏è Snowflake.

name: Spiral Calendar Pad
description:
A spiral-bound calendar. Generally depicted as a monthly calendar, with a red or blue header. Apple and Samsung’s pages are curled up at the bottom right, as to flip for a new month.

Like üìÖ Calendar and üìÜ Tear-Off Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally.

Microsoft, Twitter and Facebook’s design feature a generic month. WhatsApp's design shows in a green header February, when it was incorporated in 2009. Apple, Samsung, and JoyPixels’s designs show the month of July, when World Emoji Day falls on the 17th, a date Google's design used to specifically display.

name: Spiral Note Pad
description:
A spiral-bound, flip-style notepad or notebook of lined paper, as used for everyday note-taking. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

Most platforms depict a notepad opened to an empty, white page, sometimes shown curled at the bottom. Microsoft’s design is shown closed, with a yellow cover.

name: Spiral Shell
description:
A seashell, as found at the beach. Generally depicted as an empty, spiraling, white seashell, as grown by a sea snail or home to a hermit crab. Positioned at various angles across platforms.

Often used for various content concerning beaches, ocean and ocean life, and summer fun.

Apple’s design previously resembled a clam shell, Microsoft’s a snail shell. Google’s was previously blue.

name: Splashing Sweat Symbol
description:
Three, light blue droplets, as sweat beads, splashing down to the right. Resembles plewds, stylized sweat droplets used in comics and animation to show characters working hard or feeling stressed.

May be used to represent various types of liquids, including sexual fluids. May also be used to represent various liquid-based slang expressions (e.g., drip, “exceptional style, swagger").

Not to be confused with üíß Droplet, though their applications may overlap.

Google, Microsoft, and Samsung's design previously featured two, upwardly directed droplets.

name: Sponge
description: A peanut-shaped sponge, as used for cleaning or bathing. Generally depicted in yellow and at different angles across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning.

name: Spool of Thread
description:
A spool of thread, as used for sewing. Thread color varies across platforms, though often depicted in red or blue and on a wooden spool. Sometimes shown with an end unraveling.

Commonly used for various content concerning sewing, knitting, arts and crafts, clothing and fashion, and metaphorical threads (e.g., a discussion thread online).

WhatsApp and Microsoft's designs includes a needle.

name: Spoon
description: A silver spoon, as used to eat soup, cereal, or ice cream as well as serve food or stir drinks. Positioned at various angles across platforms. May be paired with Fork and Knife, Fork and Knife With Plate, and Bowl With Spoon.

name: Sports Medal
description:
A gold medal, given to a person who has won a sporting event, such as a race.

Usually shown as a circular medal with an embedded ‚≠ê Star design attached to a colorful ribbon. Distinctly, Huawei's design contains the text "FUTURE STAR" at the bottom of its unique medal shape.

Not to be confused with the üéñÔ∏è Military Medal emoji.

name: Spouting Whale
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled whale, shown spouting water from its blowhole. Generally depicted as a light-blue whale in full profile facing left, with a round body and white underside, its tail held upright.

Often used with an affectionate tone. Not to be confused with the more lifelike üêã Whale, though their applications may overlap.

WhatsApp’s whale is gray, as Microsoft and Facebook’s whales previously were. Twitter’s whale was previously purple.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-5272
description:
Symbol for a sale, or bargain prices in Japan (“cut prices”). Literally translated, this character means to cut or divide.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-5408
description:
Means “agreement” in Japanese. More literally, it means to unite, or join together.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-55b6
description:
Means “work” in Japanese.  This Emoji used to mean “open for business” and precedes business hours.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6307
description:
This character translates as meaning a finger or toe pointing to indicate a certain direction.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6708
description:
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Means “moon” or “month” in Chinese.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6709
description:
This emoji means to own or posses.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6e80
description:
This emoji means “full” in Japanese, usually used to denote “full capacity” such as a gas/petrol tank on a car or pre-paid phone card.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7121
description:
This means to lack, or have none of something.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7533
description:
This Emoji has two meanings.
One meaning is “request” in Japanese. An alternative meaning is “monkey” in the Chinese zodiac.
It is commonly used in Japan to denote an application form or contact information for inquiries.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7981
description:
This Emoji means “prohibit, restrict or forbid” in Japanese.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7a7a
description:
This Á©∫ character means empty and available in Japanese. This is used in the context of an empty parking space or a vacant hotel room.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

name: Squared CL
description: CL is what shows on the CLear button of some older mobile phones.

name: Squared Cool
description: The word cool, shown enclosed in a square. This generally displays in a shade of blue, or blue-gray on most platforms. Used as a text decoration.

name: Squared Free
description: The word free, shown enclosed in a square.

name: Squared ID
description: The letters ID in a square.

name: Squared Katakana Koko
description: Means ‚ÄúHere‚Äù in Japanese, referring to a destination.

name: Squared Katakana Sa
description: Translates as meaning complimentary, or free of charge. For example, a drink that is given "on the house" to a regular customer.

name: Squared NG
description:
The letters NG, shown enclosed in a square, which are an acronym for the words No Good.

The origin of NG refers to bloopers shown during or after the credits of a live television show in Japan (known as NGs), but can be used in any field as a form of shorthand for no good.

name: Squared New
description: The word new, shown enclosed in a square.

name: Squared OK
description: The letters OK, shown enclosed in a square. Meaning Okay, denoting approval. The opposite of the Squared NG Emoji.

name: Squared SOS
description: SOS is the description for the distress signal in Morse Code. This emoji means SOS or “emergency”.

name: Squared Up with Exclamation Mark
description: The¬†word¬†up with an exclamation point after it, shown enclosed¬†in a square. Originally intended to denote¬†leveling up in a game.

name: Squared Vs
description:
A square icon with rounded sides containing the letters "VS". Generally depicted as being orange in color.

Used to represent a contest between two sides, such as in competitive sports.

name: Squid
description:
A squid, an octopus-like sea animal with ten arms. Generally depicted as a pinkish-orange giant squid, facing forward or angled to the left, with a slender, arrow-like body, small eyes, and two, long arms raised up at its sides. Platforms generally depict six arms.

Occasionally used to represent squid as a food item. Not to be confused with üêô Octopus, though their applications may overlap.

Microsoft, WhatsApp and Twitter’s squid designs are facing forward, as was a previous Google design. Samsung’s squid was previously gray.

name: Stadium
description: A large capacity stadium, featuring a large amount of seating for sporting fans, or people attending other shows hosted by the stadium.

name: Staff of Aesculapius
description:
A symbol displaying of a rod with a snake entwined around the outside in a downward-spiral shape.

Associated with medicine and health care services such as doctors or hospitals. A similar and related symbol called the Caduceus is frequently used in the United States.

name: Standing Person
description:
A person standing upright. Commonly used to convey awkwardness, particularly on TikTok.

Similar in appearance to üö∂ Person Walking, but shown facing forward and without any motion implied.

name: Star and Crescent
description: The crescent moon and star is a symbol often associated with the religion of Islam. This symbol can be found on the flags of many countries, such as Algeria, Azerbaijan, Malaysia, Pakistan and Turkey.

name: Star of David
description: A symbol often used in relation to the religion of Judaism. Not to be confused with the Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot emoji.

name: Station
description: A station, presumed to be¬†a train station. Displays a train alongside a platform, where passengers can board.

name: Statue of Liberty
description:
The Statue of Liberty, often used as a depiction of New York City.

Due to its initial inclusion in an early Japanese emoji set, it is possible that this emoji was originally intended to represent the recreation of the Statue of Liberty located on the Odaiba island in Tokyo Bay.

name: Steam Locomotive
description: A steam train, powered by coal or wood. An early type of locomotive, now mostly replaced by electric or diesel trains.

name: Steaming Bowl
description:
A bowl of steaming-hot food. Depicted as Japanese ramen (noodles in broth) with chopsticks on most platforms, though it can represent a warm meal more generally.

Samsung’s design previously resembled Pot of Food.

name: Stethoscope
description: A stethoscope with a round resonator and two earpieces. Shown in black, blue, green, or red, depending on the platform.

name: Stopwatch
description:
An analog, handheld timepiece used to measure elapsed time, as for athletic sprints. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted with two or more control buttons on its top.

Used for various content concerning time. Not to be confused with ‚è∞ Alarm Clock or other clock emojis.

name: Straight Ruler
description:
A ruler, as used to draw straight lines and measure distances. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic straightedge with length markings at a 45° angle.

Commonly used for content concerning schooling, building, and measurement in various disciplines. May also represent various concepts of straightness and size.

name: Strawberry
description: The fruit of a rich red strawberry dotted with seeds and crowned with green leaves. Google previously depicted the fruit in orange.

name: Student
description: A person who is engaged in education. Generally depicted wearing a black graduation gown and cap, and occasionally holding a degree certificate or diploma.

name: Studio Microphone
description:
A microphone, as used for radio broadcasting or studio recording. Most platforms depict a vintage, silver microphone, like the Shure Unidyne 55.

Commonly used for various content concerning radio, broadcasting, music, recording, and podcasts.

Not to be confused with the handheld üé§ Microphone, associated with live singing.

name: Stuffed Flatbread
description: A flatbread, like pita, stuffed with lettuce, tomato, and/or meat. Resembles a doner kebab, falafel, shawarma, or gyro sandwich, popular in the Middle East and the Mediterranean. Some platforms have red onion and cucumber. Not to be confused with ü´ì Flatbread or üåØ Burrito.

name: Sun Behind Cloud
description:
A yellow sun half covered by a white cloud. Position of the sun varies across platforms.

May be used as a weather icon to represent a partly cloudy day.

Not to be confused with üå§Ô∏è Sun Behind Small Cloud or ‚õÖ Sun Behind Large Cloud, though their applications may overlap.

Microsoft’s cloud was previously gray, Samsung’s bluish.

name: Sun with Face
description:
A sun with a smiling face, as a Sun of May. Generally depicted as a golden-yellow disc with a smiling, often human face with a nose, radiating triangular rays, representing the sun's heat and light.

May be used to represent the sun more generally. Also used to represent sunny, warm, or hot weather and various positive and happy (sunny) feelings.

See also ‚òÄÔ∏è Sun. Not to be confused with üîÜ Bright Button or üîÖ Dim Button.

Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook's suns feature human faces. Other platforms, including Twitter, feature a simple smiley, as üôÇ Slightly Smiling Face.

Microsoft's eyes previously appeared open, though they were also closed in the platform's early designs. Facebook's expression previously resembled üòÅ Beaming Face With Smiling Eyes.

name: Sunflower
description:
A sunflower, a tall, round flower with large yellow petals. Depicted as a single, vertical sunflower with a large, dark-brown center on a green stem.

Commonly used for Mother’s Day and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such sentiments happiness and love. Also used as a yellow accent color and in association with summer and farming.

Not to be confused with üåº Blossom, which is yellow on many platforms.

name: Sunrise
description: A sun rising, early in the morning. Can be difficult to distinguish from a sunset in some versions of this artwork.

name: Sunrise Over Mountains
description: The sun rising over a mountain range, early in the morning.

name: Sunset Over Buildings
description: A beautiful view, featuring an orange sky, with the sun setting over the buildings of a city skyline.

name: Superhero
description:
A person who wields abilities beyond those of ordinary people and is dedicated to protecting the public. Generally depicted as wearing a colorful domino mask and a cape.

This base emoji does not specify a gender, but is used to create the emojis for Man Superhero and Woman Superhero.

The Supervillain is the nemesis of this emoji.

name: Supervillain
description:
A person who wields abilities beyond those of ordinary people who, unlike their nemesis the Superhero, uses their powers for evil. 

This base emoji does not specify a gender, but is used to create the emojis for Man Supervillain and Woman Supervillain.

Google's design is similar to that of Mr. Sinister from the X-Men Marvel comics.

name: Surfer
description: A person on a surfboard, riding on a wave in the ocean. Wears a wetsuit or board shorts in most versions.

name: Sushi
description: Japanese sushi, generally depicted as two pieces of raw pinkish-orange fish, as tuna or salmon, on white rice (nigiri). Some platforms show the cylindrical maki, a piece of seafood, vegetables, and white rice wrapped in seaweed (nori).

name: Suspension Railway
description: Similar to a monorail, a suspension railway is elevated, but the vehicle is suspended under the track.

name: Swan
description:
A swan, a waterbird with white feathers and a long neck. Depicted in full profile facing left, with a curving neck, orange bill, black eye marking, and wings and legs tucked in, as if gliding in water.

May be used to represent a goose or, metaphorically, love, grace, and beauty.

name: Swimmer
description:
A person swimming in a pool, the ocean, or another body of water. Lacked goggles on prior versions of iOS.

Swims facing to the left of screen on all major platforms.

name: Synagogue
description: A synague; a place of worship for followers of Judaism. Displayed with a Star of David on the front.

name: Syringe
description:
A medical syringe, as used to administer a vaccine or draw blood. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a needle to the upper right.

Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well as various senses of needles, drugs, tattoos, blood, or more recently – coronavirus vaccination.

Originally used for the representation of blood donation, and displayed with blood in the barrel. In 2021 many platforms are switching to a more general-purpose empty syringe. Google and Facebook’s designs previously featured green liquids.

name: T-Rex
description:
A Tyrannosaurus rex, a massive, meat-eating dinosaur with huge jaws, tiny arms, and a long tail. Depicted as a green tyrannosaur standing on its hind lefts facing left, often with a textured back, sharp teeth, and clawed toes.

May be used to represent various dinosaurs, including raptors. See also ü¶ï Sauropod.

May also be used to call a person a dinosaur, i.e. imply that they are old-fashioned or out-of-touch with modern sentiments.

Google’s T-rex used to look somewhat like a velociraptor, though the design has since changed. Samsung’s T-Rex was previously red, Microsoft's brown, and Facebook’s only a green head with open jaws.

name: T-Shirt
description:
A plain t-shirt, that can be worn by men or women. Displayed as a blue polo shirt on iOS, a light blue ringer t-shirt on Android, Samsung and Windows, or a standard green tee on other platforms.

The Facebook version of this emoji previously had a capital H on the front.

name: Table Tennis Paddle and Ball
description: A paddle and ping pong ball used in the sport of table tennis.

name: Taco
description: A Mexican or Tex-Mex taco on a hard or soft corn tortilla, filled with such ingredients as beef, lettuce, tomato, cheese, and onion. Apple’s design resembles a carne asada taco, with cilantro and white onion.

name: Takeout Box
description: A tall, folded, paper carton, usually white, as used for takeout/takeaway food at Western Chinese restaurants. Most platforms depict chopsticks inside its open lid, labeled with a red, multi-tiered, traditional Chinese building. Also called an oyster pail.

name: Tamale
description: A single tamale wrapped in a corn husk.

name: Tanabata Tree
description:
A Tanabata tree, a type of wish tree on which people hang wishes written on paper and other decorations during Tanabata, a Japanese festival celebrating two heavenly lovers. Depicted as one or two stalks of green bamboo, on which hangs one or more slips of paper, generally red.

Often used to represent various plants or as a green accent color.

Apple’s design includes a yellow star decoration. Microsoft’s design previously displayed a green branch with three, variously colored pieces of paper.

name: Tangerine
description: An orange-colored citrus fruit with a green leaf or leaves and stem. Officially depicting a tangerine, a type of mandarin (mikan in Japan). Often used as a garden-variety orange. Either way, a good source of vitamin C.

name: Taurus
description: The¬†Taurus astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Bull.

name: Taxi
description: A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the side, as opposed to the oncoming taxi emoji.

name: Teacher
description: A person standing in front of a chalkboard (aka blackboard) with the intention of teaching a class. Often shown holding a üìï Closed Book or a pointer.

name: Teacup Without Handle
description:
A cup of green tea, as the minty-colored Japanese matcha, usually shown on a wooden mat. Matcha is traditionally served in a small bowl that resembles a cup without a handle. Often taken as a bowl of soup, such as a split pea.

May also be used to refer to a person's physical attractiveness, as per the slang phrase "your body is tea."

name: Teapot
description:
A classic teapot with a wide bulbous body, a spout, a handle, and a lid. Can be used to talk about tea, tea time, or warm beverages in general.

May also be used to talk about gossip as in the expression spill the tea.

name: Tear-Off Calendar
description:
A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page on a two-ringed, daily desk calendar, as flipped or torn off to change the date. Displays month and day on a white, square page, curled up at the bottom right.

Like üìÖ Calendar and üóìÔ∏è Spiral Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally.

The date shown is July 17. This date was first used by Apple as a reference to when iCal for Mac premiered at MacWorld Expo in 2002. Since 2014 Emojipedia has celebrated World Emoji Day on July 17, because of this emoji.

Major platforms previously used a variety of dates on this calendar, but have changed in recent years to also show July 17, to avoid confusion on World Emoji Day. Some vendors still feature easter egg dates marking company founding or other milestones:


	üìÖ Apple: July 17 (Mac iCal announcement in 2002, later World Emoji Day)
	üìÖ Google: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a generic 12, as months in the year)
	üìÖ Microsoft: a generic month
	üìÖ Samsung: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a generic 31)
	üìÖ WhatsApp: Feb 24 (incorporation of WhatsApp in 2009)
	üìÖ Twitter: Jul 17  (changed from March 21 which was the founding date of Twitter in 2006; previously July 15, the date Twitter launched)
	üìÖ Facebook: February 4 (date of founding in 2004; previously a generic 31)
	üìÖ Huawei: September 15
	üìÖ JoyPixels: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
	üìÖ SerenityOS: 10


Discontinued:


	üìÖ Messenger: August 9 (first release of Messenger apps in 2011)
	üìÖ LG: March 27 (unknown)
	üìÖ HTC: generic 3
	üìÖ Mozilla: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
	üìÖ emojidex: December 12 (unknown)
	üìÖ Softbank: 12 (suggesting the number of months in a year)  
	üìÖ Docomo: 12
	üìÖ au by KDDI: 12

name: Technologist
description:
A person behind a computer screen, working in the field of technology.

Usually shown working on a laptop, though Google's design appears to be using a desktop computer instead.

The laptop in Apple's design includes the Apple logo, as per a Macbook. Samsung and Huawei's designs include their company's logotype, while the designs from Microsoft, WhatsApp, Telegram, and JoyPixels show their logomark.

name: Teddy Bear
description:
A classic teddy bear, as snuggled by a child when going to sleep.

Depicted as a brown, stuffed toy bear, shown seated with its arms to the sides, hind paw pads facing forward, and a friendly smile on its face. Google, WhatsApp, and Twitter's designs include a ribbon around the neck, while Facebook's is wearing a bow tie.

Commonly used to convey something or someone is cute or cuddly (e.g., teddy bear as a term of endearment) as well as other warm, loving sentiments (e.g., get well soon). May also be used for various content concerning toys and children more generally.

Not to be confused with üêª Bear Face, though their applications may overlap.

name: Telephone Receiver
description:
The handset of a traditional telephone, with speaker and microphone. Generally depicted in black at a 45° angle.

Like ‚òéÔ∏è Telephone, used for various content concerning literal and figurative phone-calling. Also used as an icon before a phone number.

Microsoft’s design is red.

Early designs for the telephone receiver emoji from au by KDDI resembled a mobile phone, and vice versa, before having their codepoints swapped in later releases.

name: Telescope
description:
A telescope, as used to gaze at stars and planets in the night sky. Shown with an optical tube mounted on a tripod, positioned at various angles and generally depicted as metal.

Commonly used for various content concerning astronomy, outer space, celestial objects, and science more generally. May also be used for various concepts of sight (e.g., spying, viewing).

Twitter’s designs feature red hardware, as did as an older Google design.

name: Television
description:
A classic television set, as people watched before streaming on flatscreens. Depicted in various colors and styles with a screen, knobs, and, on many platforms, rabbit-ear antennae.

Commonly used for television broadcasting as well as various content involving screens, from watching movies to playing video games.

Google’s design previously featured a more modern-looking orange TV. Apple’s first design was yellow, while Microsoft’s previous design was a flatscreen.

name: Tennis Racquet and Ball
description: A tennis racket (racquet) with a tennis ball. Only a ball is shown on certain platforms, including Apple, Twitter, and WhatsApp.

name: Tent
description:
A tent, used for protection from wind and rain when camping.

Facebook's version of this emoji shows it at night time, under stars, as did previous designs from Apple, Samsung, and Twitter. Microsoft's design does not feature stars, but it does include a crescent moon.

name: Test Tube
description:
A test tube, as used to conduct chemical experiments in a laboratory. Depicted as a clear cylinder, open at one end and containing a green liquid. Positioned at a 45° angle.

May be used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May also represent other liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well metaphorical laboratories and experiments.

Some platforms include volume markings or display the liquid as bubbling. WhatsApp’s design features a blue liquid.

name: Thermometer
description: A liquid-in-glass thermometer, as used to measure temperature. Depicted at various angles with a red liquid risen from the bulb to various levels on the scale. Commonly used for content concerning high temperatures, including warm weather, illness (having a fever), and various slang senses of hot.

name: Thinking Face
description:
A yellow face with furrowed eyebrows looking upwards with thumb and index finger resting on its chin. Intended to show a person pondering or deep in thought. Often used to question or scorn something or someone, as if saying Hmm, I don't know about that. Tone varies, including earnest, playful, puzzled, skeptical, and mocking.

May be paired with üí≠ Thought Balloon or üí° Light Bulb to represent thinking, (having) ideas, and learning.

Joins ü§ó Hugging Face, ü§´ Shushing Face, and ü§≠ Face With Hand Over Mouth as one of the few smileys featuring a hand.

name: Third Place Medal
description: A bronze medal, given to the person or team who comes third in a competitive sporting event such as a race.

name: Thong Sandal
description: A single flip flop or thong sandal. Often worn to the beach and/or in warm weather. Can be used to talk about sandals, the beach, or warm weather in general.

name: Thought Balloon
description:
A large cloud-like shape more commonly known as a thought bubble.

Used to represent thinking, or thoughts, and commonly used in comics to display the thoughts of a drawn character. May also be used to represent a dream, or daydream.

name: Three Button Mouse
description:
A mouse, as used to control a cursor on a computer. Generally depicted as a white or gray, cordless device with a scroll wheel between left- and right-click buttons.

Used for various content concerning computers, including gaming and various senses of click (e.g., clickbait).

Apple’s design resembles the company’s Magic Mouse, with a single button. Google’s mouse previously had a cord.

Not to be confused with üêÅ Mouse.

name: Thumbs Down Sign
description: A thumbs-down gesture indicating disapproval.

name: Thumbs Up Sign
description:
A thumbs-up gesture indicating approval.

In certain contexts, the use of the Thumbs Up emoji can be construed as being passive aggressive or sarcastic. Despite this possible use, it remains a popular means of quickly and earnestly expressing approval.

name: Thunder Cloud and Rain
description:
Blue raindrops falling from a white cloud with a lightning bolt flashing.

May be used as a weather icon to represent thundershowers.

Not to be confused with üå©Ô∏è Cloud With Lightning, though their applications may overlap.

name: Ticket
description: A paper ticket, which may be for a theatre show, sporting event, or other ticketed performance. Shown in blue, yellow or grey on most platforms.

name: Tiger
description:
A tiger, a large cat with an orange coat and black stripes. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long tail, its distinctive stripes, and, on some platforms, white patches.

See also üêØ Tiger Face. Not to be confused with üêÜ Leopard.

One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.

Google’s design is noticeably more cartoon-styled, as Facebook’s previously was. Microsoft’s design previously featured a yellow, forward-facing tiger, as if on the prowl.

name: Tiger Face
description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a tiger looking straight ahead. Generally depicted in yellowish-orange with black stripes on its forehead and cheeks, a white muzzle, and neutral expression.

Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied üêÖ Tiger.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

name: Timer Clock
description:
Time’s up! A timer set to count down and sound an alarm after a designated amount of time, as used in the kitchen. Appearance varies by platform. Commonly used for various content concerning time, including countdowns and deadlines.

Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs resemble kitchen timers. Other designs may be confused with üï∞Ô∏è Mantelpiece Clock or other clock emojis.

name: Tired Face
description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes, furrowed eyebrows, and a broad, open frown, as if yawning in exhaustion or groaning in exasperation. Usually shown with upper teeth and sometimes tongue.

While intended to represent tiredness, it commonly conveys various degrees and tones of frustration and sadness as well excitement and affection, as if it just can’t handle how great someone or something is.

Similar in appearance and meaning to üò© Weary Face, but with scrunched eyes. Not to be confused with üò™ Sleepy Face or üò¥ Sleeping Face, which often convey actually being asleep. 

Samsung’s design previously featured three, vertical, blue lines over its forehead, which can indicate fatigue in manga and anime. A previous Microsoft design was yawning.

name: Toilet
description:
A white toilet, as used to deposit a üí© Pile of Poo. (Don’t forget the üßª Roll of Paper.) Most platforms depict a porcelain toilet in profile, bowl facing to the left.

Commonly used for various content concerning going to the bathroom or bathrooms more generally. May also be used figuratively, e.g., down the toilet.

Google, Microsoft, and Twitter’s designs left the seat up.

name: Tokyo Tower
description:
The Tokyo Tower is the second-tallest building in Japan, located in Minato, Tokyo.

Built in 1957, the design of the Tokyo Tower  was inspired by the Eiffel Tower in Paris, France and may be confused for it due to the small size of the emoji. A previous Samsung design also added to this confusion as it was colored grey instead of red and white.

name: Tomato
description: A plump, red garden tomato topped with a leafy green stem. May resemble the red apple at small sizes.

name: Tongue
description: A tongue, sticking out. May be used as a childish sign of defiance. Alternatively: licking, in various contexts.

name: Toolbox
description:
A red box for holding and transporting tools, such as a hammer and wrench. Generally depicted as latched shut with silver hardware and a black handle.

Commonly used for literal or metaphorical tools, toolkits, and building.

WhatsApp's design includes a hammer in front. Google’s design was previously shown as open with two wrenches and a pair of pliers.

name: Tooth
description: A single tooth, like those found in your mouth. Shown as a premolar across all major emoji vendors.

name: Toothbrush
description:
A brightly colored plastic toothbrush with white bristles.

Used to talk about oral hygiene, daily routines, or something that is fresh and clean.

name: Top Hat
description: A top hat, worn in traditional British weddings and other formal occasions. This is also a popular playing piece in the game of Monopoly.

name: Top with Upwards Arrow Above
description: The word "top" with an arrow pointing up above it.

name: Trackball
description:
A trackball, as rotated to control a cursor on a computer. An alternative or supplement to a computer mouse or touchpad. Generally depicted as a cordless device with a blue or red ball in a cylindrical, black or gray socket.

Occasionally used for various content concerning gaming. Facebook’s design featurs a rectangular base, while Google’s design previously featured a cord.

name: Tractor
description: A tractor, may be used by a farmer or other occupation on the land.

name: Trade Mark Sign
description: A trademark symbol, the letters TM displayed after a word that is trademarked.

name: Train
description: A train, of no specified type.¬†Due to the presence of a steam train and fast train emoji, this is likely to be a regular electrified or diesel passenger train.

name: Tram
description:
A¬†form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys.
Trams tend to be similar to light rail, with the difference being that they don‚Äôt tend to have their own dedicated tracks.
This emoji is generally shown¬†as the front of the tram, on tracks.¬†The intended¬†usage¬†of this¬†emoji, instead of¬†the¬†tram car¬†emoji is not clear.

name: Tram Car
description:
A¬†form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys.
Trams¬†tend to be similar to¬†light rail, with the difference being that they don‚Äôt tend to have their own dedicated tracks.
This emoji is generally shown¬†as the side¬†of the tram.¬†The intended¬†usage¬†of¬†this¬†emoji,¬†instead of¬†the¬†tram¬†emoji is not clear.

name: Transgender Flag
description: A flag with horizontal pale blue and pale pink stripes with a single white stripe in the middle, used as a Transgender or Transgender Pride flag and commonly seen at Pride events.

name: Triangular Flag on Post
description: A triangular red flag on a post. Most commonly associated with golf, as shown in the flag in hole emoji. Can also be used to represent the term red flag, signaling a problem or issue.

name: Triangular Ruler
description:
A triangle or set square, as used by engineers or architects to draw straight lines at angles. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic right triangle with length markings, its hypotenuse to the right.

Commonly applied to a range of disciplines, including art, design, building, architecture, and STEM (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics). May also represent various concepts of angles and measurement.

name: Trident Emblem
description:
A trident is a three-pronged spear, that appears similar to a pitchfork. Often held by Greek or Roman Gods in statues.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity during Mardi Gras.

name: Troll
description:
A green troll, usually shown holding a club.

May be used to refer to the fantasy creature. May also be used to refer to an internet troll or the act of trolling.

Apple’s troll holds a scepter instead of a club. Microsoft, Twitter, and WhatsApp's designs show only the bust of a troll instead of the full-bodied creature.

name: Trolleybus
description: A type of bus that uses overhead electrical wires for power. Appears similar to a cross between a bus and a tram car.

name: Trophy
description:
A trophy given as an recognition of achievement, usually in sports. The trophy emoji is a gold cup, with a engraving on the bottom detailing the award.

In Snapchat, the trophy provides access to the Trophy Case for unlocking emoji achievements.

name: Tropical Drink
description:
A sunset-orange-colored tropical beverage in a stemmed glass, as a rum punch or mai tai. Served with a straw and fruit garnish. Many platforms include a cocktail umbrella, hence umbrella drink. Samsung previously featured an electric-blue concoction. See also Cocktail Glass.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity during the summer months.

name: Tropical Fish
description:
A tropical fish, as swims in the warm waters of a coral reef or is kept as a pet in an aquarium. Depicted as a brightly colored fish in full profile facing left, with slender fins. Often shown as a blue-and-yellow fish with stripes, as an angelfish.

May be used to represent a variety of fish (saltwater or freshwater), fishing, metaphorical senses of fish, and fish as food, as consumed in the form of üç£ Sushi. Not to be confused with üêü Fish or üê° Blowfish, though their applications may overlap. See also üé£ Fishing Pole.

Google and Facebook’s fish previously resembled a goldfish, while Samsung’s was black and white. Microsoft’s fish was previously orange with white stripes, and yellow and blue before that.

name: Trumpet
description: A trumpet, a brass instrument played in jazz bands.

name: Tulip
description:
A pink tulip flower. Depicted as a single, vertical pink tulip on a green stem.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such sentiments as love, appreciation, and happiness. Also used in association with the Netherlands and as a pink accent color.

Not to be confused with üåπ Rose, though their applications may overlap.

Google's tulip was once orange, Microsoft and Samsung's red.

name: Tumbler Glass
description:
A short, flat glass, as used for brown liquors like whiskey or Scotch whisky.

Apple, Google, Facebook, and WhatsApp serve theirs neat, while other platforms include ice ("on the rocks").

Samsung's glass previously featured the faint initials ONI, an apparent in-company easter egg.

name: Turkey
description:
A turkey, a gobbling bird traditionally eaten at Thanksgiving or Christmas. Depicted in full profile facing left, standing on its legs with a dark-brown body, a white-fringed plume, pink or blue head, and its distinctive red snood and wattle.

May be consumed in the form of üçó Poultry Leg.

name: Turtle
description:
A turtle, a slow-moving reptile with a shell. Depicted as a light-green turtle in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long neck and green, textured shell.

May be used to represent a tortoise and various senses of slow.

WhatsApp’s turtle has light-brown skin, Facebook’s a yellow-rimmed shell.

name: Twisted Rightwards Arrows
description: Two arrows pointing right while crossing over one another. Used to indicate putting music on shuffle: randomizing the order of tracks in the upcoming playlist. May also be used to indicate two items switching places.

name: Two Hearts
description:
Two pink love hearts. One larger than the other. Can be used to display that “love is in the air”.

This emoji tends to spike in popularity on Valentine's Day.

On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you have been #1 BFs with each other for two consecutive months. A bug in October 2019 has a yellow heart emoji showing instead of üíï for some Snapchat users.

name: Two Men Holding Hands
description: Two men holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

name: Two Women Holding Hands
description: Two women holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

name: Umbrella
description:
An opened, dry umbrella. Generally depicted with purple fabric and a hooked handle.

Commonly used for various content concerning rainy weather. Occasionally used as a purple accent color.

Not to be confused with ‚òî Umbrella With Rain Drops or üåÇ Closed Umbrella, though their applications may overlap.

WhatsApp’s umbrella is green. Google’s umbrella was previously blue, Microsoft and Samsung’s once red.

name: Umbrella on Ground
description:
A large, open umbrella, as provides shade at a beach or patio. Generally depicted as a striped umbrella inserted into a patch of sand and tilted to the right.

Commonly used for various content concerning the beach, summer vacations (holidays), sunny weather, and relaxing outdoors.

The color of the stripes varies across platforms; Apple (no sand) and Samsung’s are red and yellow, while Google, Twitter and Facebook’s red and white, and WhatsApp’s rainbow-colored. Google’s was previously blue and white.

Not to be confused with other umbrella-related emoji, such as üèñÔ∏è Beach With Umbrella, though their applications may overlap.

name: Umbrella with Rain Drops
description:
An umbrella, opened to provide cover from rain. Generally depicted with purple fabric and a hooked handle with several rain droplets falling on its top.

Commonly used for various content concerning rainy weather.

Not to be confused with ‚òÇÔ∏è Umbrella or üåÇ Closed Umbrella, though their applications may overlap.

WhatsApp’s umbrella is green. Google’s umbrella was previously blue, Microsoft and Samsung’s red, and Facebook’s once pink.

In 2016, a Durex poll voted this emoji to (unofficially) represent condoms and safe sex for World AIDS Day.

name: Unamused Face
description:
A yellow face with slightly raised eyebrows, a frown, and eyes looking to the side. May convey a variety of negative emotions, including irritation, displeasure, grumpiness, and skepticism, as if giving the side-eye.

Not to be confused with üòè Smirking Face, which features similar eyes but a wry smile.

name: Unicorn Face
description:
The face of a unicorn, a mythical creature in the form of a white horse with a single, long horn on its forehead. Generally depicted as a white horse head facing left with a pink or purple mane and a yellow or rainbow-colored horn.

In addition to the mythical unicorn, may be used to convey whimsy, fantasy, uniqueness, specialness, peace, and love. Often used for various content related to the LGBTQ community, thanks in part to its rainbow colors on many platforms. Also often used in association with “unicorn” startups. Sometimes used as a rainbow or holographic accent color.

Vendors implement the emoji with the same or similar design as üê¥ Horse Face, but with colorful hair and a horn.

Available as an Apple Animoji.

WhatsApp’s unicorn is facing right. Google’s unicorn previously had a brown mane, Samsung’s a pink mane. Twitter’s unicorn was previously purple-colored with a blue mane.

name: Up Down Arrow
description: A vertical line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing up and down.

name: Up-Pointing Red Triangle
description: A small red equilateral triangle, pointing upwards.

name: Up-Pointing Small Red Triangle
description:
A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing up. Styled similarly to the left and right triangles and colored as either gray or blue, but shown in orange on Android.

Previously displayed as red on Windows.

name: Upside-Down Face
description:
A classic smiley, turned upside down. Implemented as a flipped version of üôÇ Slightly Smiling Face on most platforms.

Commonly used to convey irony, sarcasm, joking, or a sense of goofiness or silliness. Its intent can be similar to the bemused Oh well! of ü§∑ Person Shrugging or the shruggie emoticon, ¯\_(„ÉÑ)_/¯.

Microsoft's design previously featured a full-toothed grin.

name: Upwards Black Arrow
description:
An arrow, pointing up.

See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Vampire
description:
A vampire shown wearing a dark cape, and with pointed fangs. This emoji supports skin tones, and variations that are female or male.

May be used to call someone an "energy vampire", i.e. a person whose actions leave others exhausted or drained of energy

name: Vertical Traffic Light
description: A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections.¬†More common than the horizontal traffic light.

name: Vibration Mode
description:
An icon representing vibration mode on a mobile phone, indicating that a phone should be switched to silent and/or vibrate mode.

Displayed as a phone with either zig-zag lines or muted-bell icon on most platforms. Early versions of this emoji often used a heart alongside a mobile phone, as commonly seen in Japan.

name: Victory Hand
description:
Most commonly known as a ‚úåÔ∏è Peace Sign, but traditionally called as a Victory Hand. Two fingers held up on one hand making a V sign.

The reverse of this symbol is considered an offence gesture in British culture, similar to giving the middle finger.

name: Video Camera
description:
A video camera, as a camcorder used to film home videos in the 1980–90s. Generally depicted as a gray or black video camera with viewfinder, control buttons, and lens pointed left.

Commonly used for various content concerning film and video as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit.

Samsung’s is fitted with a microphone. Google’s design was once blue and also previously featured a flip screen.

name: Video Game
description: A video game emoji, shown on major platforms as a console gamepad with D-pad, joysticks, and buttons.

name: Videocassette
description:
A videotape cassette, as a VHS tape used to watch movies or record TV on VCRs before DVDs , DVRs, and streaming. Generally depicted as a black cassette with a white label between its reels.

Occasionally used for various content concerning film and video (taping) as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit. May also be used to represent audio cassette tapes.

Microsoft’s design previously resembled a voicemail icon.

name: Violin
description: A violin emoji. Sometimes used in the context of the world’s smallest violin.

name: Virgo
description: The Virgo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Maiden.

name: Volcano
description: A volcano, erupting with smoke and lava.

name: Volleyball
description: A volleyball emoji, showing the round ball used in the sport. Played as part of the Summer Olympic Games.

name: Waffle
description: A round or square Belgian waffle, baked to a golden brown. Most platforms depict this emoji topped with a pad of butter, and some include gooey syrup running down the sides.

name: Waning Crescent Moon Symbol
description:
A waning crescent moon (appearing to become smaller), the last of the phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its left side illuminated in a thin, golden or silver crescent, its remainder dark.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.

In July 2023 this emoji trended on Emojipedia. This is likely due to it being required to complete developer Neal Agarwal’s viral hit The Password Game.

See also üåô Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with üåí Waxing Crescent Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning crescent moon in a night sky with stars.

name: Waning Gibbous Moon Symbol
description:
A waning gibbous moon (appearing more than half full but getting smaller), the sixth of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, mostly illuminated in gold or silver, but with its right side a dark crescent.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.

Not to be confused with üåî Waxing Gibbous Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning gibbous moon in a night sky with stars.

name: Warning Sign
description:
A triangle with an exclamation mark inside, used as a warning or alert.

This emoji is used prominently within social media platform BeReal's core time-sensitive "‚ö†Ô∏è Time to BeReal ‚ö†Ô∏è" push notification. This notification is shown when being prompted to share a photo of themselves and their immediate surroundings, with this notification given within a randomly selected two-minute window every day.

name: Wastebasket
description:
A wastebasket, as used to discard trash in an office. Generally depicted as a silver, wire-mesh container. Also known as a wastepaper basket, trash/garbage can, or rubbish bin.

Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative waste. May also be used in the context of basketball. Sometimes paired with üî• Fire as a visual representation of the slang expression dumpster fire ("chatoic situation").

Samsung’s design previously depicted a metal can/bin with a lid, as used for outdoor garbage—or lived in by Oscar the Grouch. Not to be confused with üß∫ Basket.

name: Watch
description:
A wristwatch, as used for telling time. Appearance varies across platforms, but widely depicted as an analog timepiece with a white face and brown or black straps.

Used for various content concerning time, including watches as accessories. Apple's design is an Apple Watch, though previously featured a traditional watch before the product’s release.

name: Water Buffalo
description:
A water buffalo, a bovine used to plough rice fields in parts of Asia. Depicted in gray or black in full profile on all fours facing left, with a tail and broad horns curled up at the tips.

Often used to represent a bull. Not to be confused with üêÇ Ox, though their applications may overlap.

Microsoft’s design was previously brown.

name: Water Closet
description: A water closet is a name used for public toilet, bathroom or restroom used in some countries. Typically abbreviated to the letters WC, this may be found on signage in public buildings, as an alternative to the restroom symbol.

name: Water Polo
description: A person shown in water with a ball, playing the sport of water polo.

name: Water Wave
description:
A wave of water, as breaks at the beach. Depicted as a blue wave with a foamy, white crest, curling to the right.

May be used to represent water in general, various bodies of water like oceans, and water activities, such as swimming, surfing, and sailing. May also be used to represent metaphorical waves.

Apple’s design resembles the iconic wave in Japanese artist Hokusai’s famous woodblock print, The Great Wave off Kanagawa (ca. 1830).

name: Watermelon
description:
A slice of watermelon, showing its rich pink flesh, black seeds, and green rind.

Can be used to reference the flag of the Palestinian Territories.

name: Waving Black Flag
description: A black-colored flag, shown waving on a post.

name: Waving Hand Sign
description:
A hand waving most commonly used to say “hello” or “goodbye”.

This emoji can be used to convey a sense of not being friends any more when used on WeChat in China.

name: Waving White Flag
description: A white flag, most often shown waving on a post. Traditionally used as a sign of surrender, the meaning of this flag as an emoji is less defined.

name: Wavy Dash
description: Just like a regular dash (hyphen), sometimes used in Asian character sets in the same way a ‚Äì or ‚Äî is used in latin character sets.

name: Waxing Crescent Moon Symbol
description:
A waxing crescent moon (appearing to become larger), the second of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its right side illuminated in a thin, golden or silver crescent, its remainder dark.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.

See also üåô Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with üåò Waning Crescent Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a crescent moon in a night sky with stars.

name: Waxing Gibbous Moon Symbol
description:
A waxing gibbous moon (appearing more than half full and getting larger), the fourth of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, mostly illuminated in gold or silver, but with its left side a dark crescent.

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.

Not to be confused with üåñ Waning Gibbous Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.

Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning gibbous moon in a night sky with stars.

name: Weary Cat Face
description: A cartoon cat variant of üò© Weary Face. Its expression more closely resembles üò± Face Screaming in Fear. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

name: Weary Face
description:
A yellow face with closed eyes, furrowed brows, and a broad, open frown, as if distraught to the point of giving up. Usually shown with upper teeth and sometimes tongue.

May convey various feelings of frustration, lust, sadness, amusement, and affection. Often playful in tone.

Similar in appearance and meaning to üò´ Tired Face, but with crescent-shaped eyes. Huawei's design has its tongue hanging out of its mouth. Samsung’s design previously featured large eyes half-closed in tiredness.

This emoji has a cat variant, üôÄ Weary Cat Face, though it more closely resembles üò± Face Screaming in Fear.

name: Wedding
description: An emoji to depict a wedding, displayed by most vendors as a Christian church and love hearts. Some platforms display a cross or bell on the building.

name: Weight Lifter
description: A person lifting a barbell loaded with weights above their head.

name: Whale
description:
A whale, the massive marine mammal. Generally depicted as a light-blue whale in full profile facing left, with its tail curving down towards is huge mouth. Shown with a white, textured underside, as a humpback or blue whale.

Not to be confused with the more cartoon-styled üê≥ Spouting Whale, though their applications may overlap.

Apple and Google's whales have slightly open mouths, revealing baleen.

name: Wheel
description:
A wheel with a rubber tire.

May be used in reference to wheels, tires, or vehicles with wheels. May also be used in expressions with 'wheel' like third wheel or hell on wheels.

name: Wheel of Dharma
description: A symbol often used in relation to the Indian religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism.

name: Wheelchair Symbol
description:
The international symbol of access, used to denote a facility which has been designed with accessibility or people in wheelchairs in mind. Appears as a blue sign, with a white graphic of a person sitting in a wheelchair.

Many platforms now use the Accessible Icon Project style image for this emoji, which displays the person in the wheelchair in a more active position.

name: White Down Pointing Backhand Index
description:
An index finger pointing downward, showing the back of the hand while doing so.

Generally used to highlight a piece of content placed below where this emoji can be used. This content could be a picture, a website link, or a different piece of text,

name: White Exclamation Mark Ornament
description: A large white exclamation mark (!) symbol emoji.

name: White Flower
description:
A stylized white flower. Generally depicted as a rosette-shaped cherry blossom in pink or red outline, often with a white fill.

Apple, Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Facebook's designs feature Japanese characters roughly translating to very well done, used by teachers as a stamp for students who did exceptional work, often accompanied by a score in red.

Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a pink, white, or red accent color.

Not to be confused with üå∏ Cherry Blossom and üå∫ Hibiscus, though their applications may overlap.

Apple's flower previously featured a red-outlined design, Google's an orange outline. Microsoft's flower was previously black and white, Samsung and Facebook's pink and white.

name: White Frowning Face
description:
A classic sad face. A yellow face with simple, open eyes and wide, steep frown. May convey such feelings as moderate concern or disappointment and affectionate sadness, as when missing a loved one. Its sentiment is usually more intense than üôÅ Slightly Frowning Face, which has a smaller frown.

This smiley predates Unicode emoji support. In its Unicode name of White Frowning Face, white does not refer to skin tone or ethnicity, although Samsung’s early designs colored the face white. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

name: White Heart
description:
A white heart emoji, used for love and affection. Also commonly used to discuss someone passing away.

An alternative character known as White Heart Suit is also available, but not intended to have an emoji appearance.

name: White Heavy Check Mark
description:
A check mark that displays with a white outlined appearance. Shows on most platforms with a bright green rounded rectangle or circle surrounding it.

Android previously displayed this as an outlined blue check mark / blue tick.

This emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark.

name: White Large Square
description: A square shown in the shade of white. May be used to represent anything white.

name: White Left Pointing Backhand Index
description: Index finger pointing to the left.

name: White Medium Small Square
description: A medium-small-sized square shaded completely white. Smaller than the White Large Square and White Medium Square but larger than the White Small Square.

name: White Medium Square
description: A medium-sized square shaded completely white. Smaller than the White Large Square and larger than the White Medium-Small Square and the White Small Square.

name: White Medium Star
description:
A classic, five-point gold star.

Commonly used for various metaphorical senses of star (e.g., for fame, success, excellence, reviews). Also used for emphasis or flair. Occasionally used for astronomical stars.

Not to be confused with üí´ Dizzy, üåü Glowing Star, üå† Shooting Star, or ‚ú® Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.

Samsung and Facebook’s stars were once silver.

See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

name: White Question Mark Ornament
description: A large white question mark (?) symbol emoji.

name: White Right Pointing Backhand Index
description: Index finger pointing to the right.

name: White Small Square
description: A medium-small-sized square shaded completely white. Smaller than the White Large Square, White Medium Square, and the White Medium-Small Square.

name: White Smiling Face
description:
A classic smiley. A yellow face with a modest smile, rosy cheeks, and soft, closed eyes. Many platforms, including Apple, feature relaxed eyebrows. Conveys a wide range of warm, positive feelings, including love, happiness, and gratitude.

Similar to üòä Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes, which has a broader smile, no eyebrows, and smiling eyes.

This smiley predates Unicode emoji support. In its Unicode name of White Smiling Face, white does not refer to skin tone or ethnicity. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

name: White Square Button
description: The inverse of the üî≤ Black Square Button.

name: White Sun Behind Cloud
description:
A yellow sun mostly covered by a large, white cloud. Position of the sun varies across platforms.

May be used as a weather icon to represent a mostly cloudy day.

Not to be confused with ‚õÖ Sun Behind Cloud or üå§Ô∏è Sun Behind Small Cloud, though their applications may overlap.

Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish.

See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

name: White Sun Behind Cloud with Rain
description:
A yellow sun half covered by a white rain cloud with blue raindrops. Most platforms depict the raindrops falling to the left. Position of the sun varies across platforms.

May be used as a weather icon to represent a mix of sunshine and scattered showers.

Not to be confused with ‚õÖ Sun Behind Cloud.

Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish.

See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

name: White Sun with Small Cloud
description:
A yellow sun partially covered by a small, white cloud. Position of the cloud varies across platforms.

May be used as a weather icon to represent a mostly sunny day.

Not to be confused with ‚õÖ Sun Behind Cloud or üå•Ô∏è Sun Behind Large Cloud, though their applications may overlap.

See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

name: White Up Pointing Backhand Index
description: Index finger pointing upward, showing the back of the hand while doing so.

name: White Up Pointing Index
description: A single finger pointing upward, which could be used to represent the number one, or to ask a question.

name: Wilted Flower
description:
A flower that has wilted, or is dying. Generally depicted as a limp, faded red rose drooping over the to the right on a dried-out, green stem, shedding a petal.

May be used to express such sad sentiments as heartbreak, though sometimes with a sense of irony. Sometimes used to represent a rose or other flower, with positive connotations.

Not to be confused with üåπ Rose.

WhatsApp's flower suggests a wilted üåª Sunflower; Twitter's a üå∑ Tulip, as Microsoft and Samsung's previously did. Facebook's flower was previously orange.

name: Wind Blowing Face
description:
A face blowing the wind, as a personification of nature (e.g., Mother Nature, the North Wind) who creates the wind by blowing air from its mouth. Depicted as a gray, profile of a human face, generally with a feminine appearance, blowing swirls from her mouth to the right.

May be used to represent windy weather. Occasionally used to represent clouds, fog, smoke, and smoking. Not to be confused with Dashing Away, though their applications may overlap.

Microsoft’s design is blue, as is Facebook’s, whose design most clearly suggests a woman’s face. WhatsApp’s design depicts a cloud with a face, as Samsung’s previously did.

name: Wind Chime
description:
A Japanese wind chime. Depicted as a glass bell with a strip of paper suspended from its clapper, often decorated with cherry blossom-like flowers.

Occasionally used for content concerning various senses of wind and chime. Thanks to its appearance, often used to represent jellyfish.

name: Window
description:
A square or rectangular window with glass panes. Most platforms show a wooden frame with two or four panels.

Used to talk about actual windows or metaphorical windows, which often represent opportunities, perspectives, or unique points of view.

name: Wine Glass
description: Red wine served in a stemmed glass. Google previously displayed an orange-colored drink that resembled cognac.

name: Wing
description:
A single white wing with feathers. 

Can be used to talk about flying, both literally and metaphorical. May be used in phrases such as when pigs fly or time flies. May also be used to talk about angels or to say that someone or something is angelic.

name: Winking Face
description:
A yellow face with a slight smile or open mouth shown winking, usually its left eye. May signal a joke, flirtation, hidden meaning, or general positivity. Tone varies, including playful, affectionate, suggestive, or ironic.

Not to be confused with the more mischievous or sexual üòè Smirking Face. An emoji form of the ;) emoticon.

name: Wireless
description: The symbol for a wireless or Wi-Fi connection enclosed in a square.

name: Wolf Face
description:
The face of a wolf, a howling canine that hunts in packs. Generally depicted as a cartoon-styled face of a gray wolf with pointed ears, white cheeks and muzzle, and black nose.

Its expression is variously neutral, friendly, or slightly menacing, as in Google and Samsung’s designs. Apple and Huawei's designs features the head of gray wolf, facing left.

Occasionally used to represent metaphorical senses of wolf, e.g., lone wolf, wolf pack.

Apple and SoftBank’s designs previously resembled a reddish-brown canine, resembling a dog or fox.

name: Woman
description: The female version of üßë Person.

name: Woman Artist
description: A woman engaged in the visual art of painting, shown holding a palette and paintbrush.

name: Woman Astronaut
description: A female astronaut or cosmonaut shown wearing a space suit and helmet.

name: Woman Biking
description: The female version of the üö¥ Bicyclist emoji.

name: Woman Bouncing Ball
description: The female version of the ‚õπ Person With Ball emoji.

name: Woman Bowing
description: The female version of the üôá Person Bowing Deeply emoji.

name: Woman Cartwheeling
description: A woman doing a cartwheel, representing the sport of gymnastics.

name: Woman Climbing
description:
A female rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope.

Variations exist for üßó‍‚ôÇÔ∏è Man Climbing and üßó Person Climbing.

name: Woman Construction Worker
description: The female version of the üë∑ Construction Worker emoji.

name: Woman Cook
description:
A woman responsible for food preparation wearing a white buttoned chef jacket and toque hat.

Usually shown with either a wooden spoon or a skillet frying an egg, though WhatsApp's design is holding a spatula.

name: Woman Detective
description: The female version of the üïµ Sleuth or Spy emoji.

name: Woman Elf
description: A female creature with pointed ears and a human-like face.

name: Woman Facepalming
description: A hand shown pressing against the head of a woman, commonly written as facepalm. Used to display frustration or embarrassment at the ineptitude of a person or situation.

name: Woman Factory Worker
description: A woman working in a factory setting, depicted as wearing overalls and protective headgear while holding an active welding gun.

name: Woman Fairy
description: A magical female creature found in myths and fantasy stories. Generally depicted as having insect-inspired wings, it can also be assumed to be quite diminutive in size.

name: Woman Farmer
description: A woman engaged in agriculture, raising living organisms for food or raw materials. Generally depicted as wearing a wide-brimmed hat and holding a crop (such as carrots or corn) or a pitchfork.

name: Woman Feeding Baby
description:
A woman feeding a baby with a bottle, sometimes looking down to the infant and smiling.

This emoji supports skin tone modifiers, which apply to the adult. The head of the baby is recommended to be hidden to avoid a situation where the skin tone of the baby would only correlate to the skin tone of the adult.

Variants include üßë‍üçº Person Feeding Baby and üë®‍üçº Man Feeding Baby. See also ü§± Breast-Feeding.

name: Woman Firefighter
description: A woman professionally tasked with controlling and extinguishing fires.

name: Woman Frowning
description: The female version of the üôç Person Frowning emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.

name: Woman Genie
description: A supernatural female being, which is generally shown to be imprisoned within a bottle or lamp. May be capable of granting wishes when summoned.

name: Woman Gesturing No
description: A woman with arms crossed forming an ‘X’ to indicate ‘no’ or ‘no good’. This motion is used on the TV game show Deal or No Deal to indicate ‘No Deal’.

name: Woman Gesturing OK
description: The female version of the üôÜ Face With OK Gesture emoji.

name: Woman Getting Haircut
description: The female version of the üíá Haircut emoji.

name: Woman Getting Massage
description: The female version of the üíÜ Face Massage emoji.

name: Woman Golfing
description: The female version of the üèå Golfer emoji.

name: Woman Guard
description: The female version of the üíÇ Guardsman emoji.

name: Woman Health Worker
description:
A woman working in the field of health care. This may be used to represent a doctor, nurse, or pharmacist.

See also: üë®‍‚öïÔ∏è Male Health Worker

name: Woman Judge
description: A woman who presides over court proceedings, wearing the traditional black gown and wielding a gavel.

name: Woman Juggling
description: A woman juggling between three and five colored balls. The person shown in this emoji wears a hat on most major platforms.

name: Woman Kneeling
description: A woman kneeling down on one or both knees. May be used to represent someone in prayer, or a person resting on the floor.

name: Woman Lifting Weights
description: The female version of the üèã Weight Lifter emoji.

name: Woman Mage
description: A woman who wields magical powers derived from supernatural or occult sources. May also be referred to as a witch, enchantress, or sorceress.

name: Woman Mechanic
description: A woman engaged in the construction, maintenance, or repair of machinery. Depicted wearing overalls and holding a wrench. Frequently also shown wearing a billed cap.

name: Woman Mountain Biking
description: The female version of the üöµ Mountain Bicyclist emoji.

name: Woman Office Worker
description: A woman wearing business attire. This may include items such as a shirt, blouse, tie, jacket, or headset.

name: Woman Pilot
description: A woman tasked with flying an aircraft, such as an ‚úàÔ∏è Airplane or a üöÅ Helicopter, shown wearing a traditional airline pilot uniform.

name: Woman Playing Handball
description: A woman playing the sport of handball, shown jumping in the air about to throw the ball. Apple's design is shown wearing protective goggles.

name: Woman Playing Water Polo
description: A woman shown in water with a ball, playing the sport of water polo.

name: Woman Police Officer
description: The female version of the üëÆ Police Officer emoji.

name: Woman Pouting
description: The female version of the üôé Person With Pouting Face emoji.

name: Woman Raising Hand
description: The female version of the üôã Happy Person Raising One Hand emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.

name: Woman Rowing Boat
description: The female version of the üö£ Rowboat emoji.

name: Woman Running
description: The female version of the üèÉ Runner emoji.

name: Woman Scientist
description: A woman who is studying or has expert knowledge of one or more of the natural or physical sciences. Generally depicted wearing safety goggles and a white lab coat while holding a test tube filled with colorful liquid.

name: Woman Shrugging
description: A woman shrugging her shoulders to indicate a lack of knowledge about a particular topic, or a lack of care about the result of a situation. ¯\_(„ÉÑ)_/¯

name: Woman Singer
description:
A woman singer or rock star generally displayed with a microphone, and sometimes musical notes.

iOS and Android display this emoji as a Bowie-esque figure while WhatsApp appears heavily inspired by Prince.

name: Woman Standing
description:
A person standing upright. Commonly used to convey awkwardness, particularly on TikTok.

Similar in appearance to üö∂‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Woman Walking, but shown facing forward and without any motion implied.

name: Woman Student
description: A woman who is engaged in education. Generally depicted wearing a black graduation gown and cap, and occasionally holding a degree certificate or diploma.

name: Woman Superhero
description:
A woman who wields abilities beyond those of ordinary people and is dedicated to protecting the public. Generally depicted as wearing a colorful domino mask and a cape.

The Supervillain is the nemesis of this emoji.

name: Woman Supervillain
description:
A woman who wields abilities beyond those of ordinary people who, unlike their nemesis the Superhero, uses their powers for evil. 

Google's design is similar to that of Mr. Sinister from the X-Men Marvel comics.

name: Woman Surfing
description: The female version of the üèÑ Surfer emoji.

name: Woman Swimming
description: The female version of the üèä Swimmer emoji.

name: Woman Teacher
description: A woman standing in front of a chalkboard (aka blackboard) with the intention of teaching a class. Often shown holding a üìï Closed Book or a pointer.

name: Woman Technologist
description:
A woman behind a computer screen, working in the field of technology.

See also: üë®‍üíª Male Technologist

name: Woman Tipping Hand
description:
A woman tipping her hand by her shoulder as if she’s carrying a tray of drinks or flipping her hair.

This emoji is commonly used to express sassiness or sarcasm.

The earlier gender-unspecified version of this emoji, üíÅ Person Tipping Hand, was originally depicted as a woman across most platforms.

name: Woman Vampire
description: A female vampire shown wearing a dark cape, and with pointed fangs.

name: Woman Walking
description: The female version of the üö∂ Pedestrian emoji.

name: Woman Wearing Turban
description: The female version of the üë≥ Man Wearing Turban emoji.

name: Woman Zombie
description: A reanimated human woman, often found in works of horror fiction.

name: Woman in Lotus Position
description:
A sitting woman with their eyes closed and their legs crossed in the lotus position. 

Can be used to broadly represent yoga, meditation, relaxation, or calmness.

name: Woman in Manual Wheelchair
description: A woman using a manual wheelchair as a mobility aid.

name: Woman in Motorized Wheelchair
description: A woman using a motorized wheelchair as a mobility aid.

name: Woman in Steamy Room
description:
A woman in a sauna, usually with a towel or robe and sometimes holding a ladle for pouring water on hot stones to create the steamy environment.

Apple and Samsung's designs are also wearing a towel around their head.

name: Woman in Tuxedo
description: A woman dressed for a formal occasion, wearing a tuxedo.

name: Woman with Veil
description: A woman wearing a traditional western wedding dress with a veil over their head.

name: Woman with White Cane
description: A woman using a white cane as a mobility aid, presumably due to them being blind or visually impaired.

name: Woman: Bald
description:
A woman with a bald head. Can be used to represent a bald woman or a woman with a shaved head. May also be used to represent a woman experiencing hair loss from chemotherapy, alopecia, or other medical treatments or conditions. 

Variants include üßë‍ü¶≤ Bald Person and üë®‍ü¶≤ Bald Man.

name: Woman: Beard
description: A woman shown with long hair and a beard.

name: Woman: Blond Hair
description: The female version of üë± Person with Blond Hair.

name: Woman: Curly Hair
description: The female version of üßë‍ü¶± Person with Curly Hair.
